INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (34,'REUTERS','New York regulator to end supervision of Standard Chartered for compliance failings','Anonymous','November 21, 2018   4:35 PM','[{\"content\": \"LONDON (Reuters) - New York\\u2019s Department of Financial Services (DFS) will end a period of monitoring of Standard Chartered (STAN.L) on Dec. 31, the DFS said on Wednesday, bringing to a close one strand of the bank\\u2019s punishment for past failings in compliance controls. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Standard Chartered agreed to the supervision with the regulator in 2012 as part of a wider settlement with U.S. authorities in relation to the bank\\u2019s dealings with Iran-related entities. The bank agreed an extension to that deal, which saw an independent monitor installed in the bank to check on progress in improving controls, in 2014 and again in April 2016. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"That last extension was set to expire on Dec. 31 this year, but the news that there are to be no further extensions to the monitorship will be welcomed by StanChart bosses as they seek to convince U.S. authorities they have learned from past mistakes. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The bank\\u2019s problems over failing in the past to prevent customers from breaching Iran-related sanctions are not over. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"StanChart faces a separate investigation by U.S. authorities into the extent to which it allowed clients with Iranian interests to conduct transactions after 2007, as well as the extent to which it shared such dealings with authorities at the time of the 2012 settlement. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The end of the monitorship announced on Wednesday has no bearing on that investigation, StanChart said in a regulatory filing.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Media reports in October said the bank could face a further $1.5 billion fine for those violations, in addition to the $667 million it paid in 2012 to settle alleged breaches between 2001 and 2007. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The reports said the fine amount was a preliminary assessment based on some of the communications between the bank and regulators. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"StanChart CEO Bill Winters in an internal email to staff in October criticized media coverage of the bank\\u2019s efforts to improve its controls.      \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Lawrence White; Editing by Adrian Croft and David Evans\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(35,'REUTERS','EU moves to discipline Italy over budget, Rome remains defiant','Jan Strupczewski, Gavin Jones','November 20, 2018   11:06 PM','[{\"content\": \"BRUSSELS/ROME (Reuters) - The European Commission took the first step on Wednesday toward disciplining Italy over its expansionary 2019 budget after Rome refused to change it, raising the stakes in a dispute that has alarmed the whole euro zone and could eventually lead to fines. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Commission said the Italian draft increased the 2019 structural deficit, which excludes one-offs and business cycle swings, by 1.0 percent of gross domestic product rather than cut it by 0.6 percent as required by EU laws. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy also would not trim its huge debt in a \\u201ca particularly serious case of non-compliance\\u201d with the rules, the Commission said, warranting the launch of an excessive deficit procedure. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy\\u2019s debt, at 131 percent of GDP, is proportionally the second highest in the euro zone after Greece\\u2019s. Under EU rules it should be falling every year towards 60 percent, but the Commission said it would be stable for the next two years. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe opening of a debt-based excessive deficit procedure is thus warranted,\\u201d Commission Vice President Valdis Dombrovskis told a news conference. \\u201cIn a situation of very high debt, Italy is essentially planning significant additional borrowing, instead of the necessary fiscal prudence.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy believes its borrow-and-spend policy - which the Commission regards as profligate - would boost economic growth, helping reduce the country\\u2019s debt ratio, while reducing unemployment, which was at 10.1 percent in September. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italian Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte, scheduled to meet Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker on Saturday, said on Wednesday that the government was convinced the budget was excellent and in the interest of Italy and Europe. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Economy Minister Giovanni Tria and Deputy Prime Minister Luigi Di Maio also made some conciliatory remarks that Rome and the EU had the same objectives and would seek a shared solution. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe want the same thing: to reduce the debt,\\u201d Di Maio said on Facebook. Tria said Italy believed the \\u201cmoderately expansionary\\u201d budget was needed to counter a slowdown in the economy and that he would \\u201ccontinue dialogue with the Commission to seek a shared solution in our mutual interests\\u201d. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But with memories of the sovereign debt crisis that nearly destroyed the euro still fresh, the Commission noted - like all euro zone finance ministers this month - that problems in Italy could affect all other countries sharing the single currency. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The chairman of euro zone finance ministers, Mario Centeno, speaking in The Hague, reiterated that euro zone governments supported the Commission and would discuss Italy\\u2019s controversial draft budget at their next meeting in December. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Commission believes Italy\\u2019s 2019 budget will not boost growth as expected by the eurosceptic government in Rome. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe impact of this budget on growth is likely to be negative in our view. It does not contain significant measures to boost potential growth, possibly the opposite,\\u201d Dombrovskis said. \\u201cWith what the Italian government has put on the table, we see a risk of the country sleepwalking into instability.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In Rome, the government of the right-wing League and the anti-establishment 5-Star Movement remained defiant. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe are convinced about the numbers in our budget. We will talk about it in a year\\u2019s time,\\u201d Deputy Prime Minister and League leader Matteo Salvini told reporters. Fines against Italy would be \\u201cdisrespectful\\u201d, he added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Before any financial sanctions, the Commission needs to get backing for its view from the EU\\u2019s deputy finance ministers in the next two weeks, and then from the finance ministers, probably at their next meeting in January. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This is highly likely, given the joint statement of all euro zone finance ministers that backed up the Commission against Italy earlier in November. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In December, the Commission will prepare recommendations for Italy to cut the debt and a deadline to take action within three to six months to be endorsed by ministers in January.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Only if Italy then fails to comply would financial sanctions kick in. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy\\u2019s borrow-and-spend plans have boosted its borrowing costs to 3.523 percent for the benchmark 10-year bond, and their spread over German paper has more than doubled this year.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But the bonds rallied on Wednesday, pushing two-year yields down as much as 23 bps as markets shrugged off the Commission\\u2019s rejection of Rome\\u2019s draft budget and focused on the possibility of compromise between the two sides. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Dombrovskis said the higher borrowing costs were already hurting the economy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe uncertainty and the rising interest rates are taking their toll on the Italian economy. Also it hinders the ability of Italian banks to lend to Italian companies and households at affordable cost,\\u201d he said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Jan Strupczewski and Gavin Jones; Additional reporting by Bart Meijer in The Hague; Editing by Mark Heinrich and Hugh Lawson\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(36,'REUTERS','U.S. business spending slowing; housing market weak','Lucia Mutikani','November 21, 2018   1:37 PM','[{\"content\": \"WASHINGTON (Reuters) - New orders for key U.S.-made capital goods were unexpectedly unchanged in October and shipments rebounded modestly, which could temper expectations of an acceleration in business spending on equipment early in the fourth quarter. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"While other data on Wednesday showed home resales rising last month after six straight monthly declines, house purchases remained sharply down this year. Sluggish business spending on equipment together with a lackluster housing market could stoke fears that higher interest rates are hurting the economy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"There was also disappointing news on the labor market. The number of Americans filing applications for unemployment benefits rose to more than a four-month high last week.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe economy may have seen its best day already for growth and prosperity back a couple of months ago in late summer,\\u201d said Chris Rupkey, chief economist at MUFG. \\u201cWinter is coming for the economic outlook where business investment spending looks to be topping out, and companies have let a few workers go.\\u201d  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Commerce Department said the flat reading in orders for non-defense capital goods excluding aircraft, a closely watched proxy for business spending plans, followed a downwardly revised 0.5 percent drop in September.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"These so-called core capital goods orders were previously reported to have dipped 0.1 percent in September.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Last month, there were declines in orders for primary metals and machinery. That offset increases in orders for fabricated metal products, computers and electronic products, as well as electrical equipment, appliances and components.   \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Economists polled by Reuters had forecast core capital goods orders rising 0.2 percent last month. Core capital goods orders increased 6.4 percent on a year-on-year basis. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shipments of core capital goods rose 0.3 percent in October after a downwardly revised 0.2 percent drop in the prior month. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Core capital goods shipments are used to calculate equipment spending in the government\\u2019s gross domestic product measurement. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"They were previously reported to have slipped 0.1 percent in September. Business spending on equipment stalled in the third quarter and is faltering despite the Trump administration\\u2019s $1.5 trillion tax cut.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some companies including Apple Inc (AAPL.O) used their tax windfall to buy back shares on a massive scale. Spending on equipment could also be undercut by declining oil prices. Brent crude has dropped about 28 percent since early October amid rising concerns about slowing global growth. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In a separate report on Wednesday, the National Association of Realtors said existing home sales rose 1.4 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.22 million units last month. Sales, however, were 5.1 percent lower than in October 2017, the sharpest 12-month drop since July 2014. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The report came on the heels of data on Tuesday showing a second straight monthly decline in single-family homebuilding in October. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The raft of tepid economic data, a sharp stock market selloff and signs of slowing global growth likely will put the Federal Reserve under the spotlight. Officials at the U.S. central bank have recently started talking about headwinds to domestic growth. The Fed is expected to raise interest rates in December for the fourth time this year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar .DXY was trading lower against a basket of currencies on Wednesday. U.S. Treasury prices fell, while stocks on Wall Street rebounded after a brutal two-day drop. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Lack of growth in core capital goods orders in October suggests that shipments of these goods could drop in November, posing a downside risk to GDP estimates for the fourth quarter. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Economists say the White House\\u2019s \\u201cAmerica First\\u201d policies, which have resulted in tit-for-tat tariffs with major trade partners as well as a trade war with China, are also weighing on business investment.       \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt appears that businesses are becoming more concerned about domestic growth and the negative impact on trade conflicts and future trade relationships, and may be more reluctant to up their investment,\\u201d said Jennifer Lee, a senior economist at BMO Capital Markets in Toronto. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A third report on Wednesday from the Labor Department showed initial claims for state unemployment benefits increased 3,000 to a seasonally adjusted 224,000 for the week ended Nov. 17, the highest level since the end of June. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Data for the prior week was revised to show 5,000 more applications received than previously reported. Economists had forecast claims slipping to 215,000 in the latest week. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The four-week moving average of initial claims, considered a better measure of labor market trends as it irons out week-to-week volatility, rose 2,000 to 218,500 last week. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The claims data covered the survey period for the nonfarm payrolls component of November\\u2019s employment report. The four-week average of claims rose by 6,750 between the October and November survey weeks, suggesting some moderation in job growth this month.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe initial claims data signal some softening in the labor market in that period relative to the reference week for the October report,\\u201d said Daniel Silver, an economist at JPMorgan in New York.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Payrolls increased by 250,000 jobs in October, with the unemployment rate holding near a 49-year low of 3.7 percent.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Writing by Lucia Mutikani; Additional reporting by Jason Lange; Editing by Paul Simao\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(37,'REUTERS','Wall Street regains footing as tech shares recover','Medha Singh','November 21, 2018   1:09 PM','[{\"content\": \"(Reuters) - U.S. stocks recovered from a brutal two-day selloff on Wednesday as strong earnings from Foot Locker and gains in technology stocks lifted investor sentiment ahead of the Thanksgiving holiday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Foot Locker Inc shares surged 15.4 percent after the footwear retailer\\u2019s quarterly same-store sales trumped expectations and boosted other sports retailers with Dick\\u2019s Sporting Goods Inc and Hibbett Sports Inc rising about 3 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares of Nike Inc, a Foot Locker supplier, gained 1.6 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Gap Inc rose 3.5 percent, reversing earlier losses after a number of Wall Street brokerages said the company\\u2019s planned closure of underperforming stores could eliminate significant losses. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Both, Foot Locker and Gap helped boost the S&P consumer discretionary index, making it the top gainer among the 11 major S&P indexes. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The pressure on technology stocks appeared to have eased on Wednesday, with the FAANG group \\u2014 Facebook Inc, Apple Inc, Amazon.com Inc, Netflix Inc and Alphabet Inc - gaining between 0.2 percent and 3 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Autodesk Inc jumped 9.3 percent after the software company reported third-quarter results ahead of analysts\\u2019 estimates and announced an $875 million deal to buy cloud-based software company PlanGrid. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Autodesk was the top gainer in the S&P technology sector, which was up 0.9 percent after three days of declines. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cEquity markets are finding some footing after two days of steep decline. It\\u2019s probably a reaction to over-sold condition,\\u201d said Emily Roland, head of capital markets research, John Hancock Investments. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A report by MNI saying that the Fed may pause its rate hiking cycle as early as spring could also be supporting the markets, Roland added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAny signs that the Fed is more dovish than the investors have expected is going to be a positive for risk assets.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"At 10:59 a.m. ET the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 107.36 points, or 0.44 percent, at 24,573.00, the S&P 500 was up 17.74 points, or 0.67 percent, at 2,659.63 and the Nasdaq Composite was up 79.74 points, or 1.15 percent, at 6,988.56. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The S&P energy index gained 1.2 percent as oil prices bounced back from a 6 percent plunge the previous day. [O/R] \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Worries about slowing global growth and peaking corporate earnings have sapped risk appetite in recent months, throwing into doubt the longevity of the decade-old bull run for stocks. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Nasdaq closed at its lowest level in over seven months on Tuesday, while the S&P 500 and the blue-chip Dow erased all their gains for the year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Latest economic data showed new orders for key U.S.-made capital goods were unexpectedly unchanged in October and shipments rebounded modestly, which could temper expectations of an acceleration in business spending on equipment early in the fourth quarter. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThis is a sign that the economy is adjusting to higher rates here. The pace of the economic growth is slowing, but the U.S. economy by no means is falling off a cliff here,\\u201d said Roland. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Advancing issues outnumbered decliners for a 4.25-to-1 ratio on the NYSE and a 3.39-to-1 ratio on the Nasdaq. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The S&P index recorded four new 52-week highs and two new lows, while the Nasdaq recorded seven new highs and 48 new lows. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Medha Singh in Bengaluru; Editing by Anil D\'Silva and Shounak Dasgupta\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(38,'REUTERS','Bolsonaro weighs options to reform complex Brazil tax system: source','Marcela Ayres','November 21, 2018   4:52 PM','[{\"content\": \"BRASILIA (Reuters) - Far-right president-elect Jair Bolsonaro, in a bid to reform Brazil\\u2019s complex tax system, is analyzing three models: a program of gradual adjustment, adopting a value-added tax, or a broader plan that could include a tax on financial transactions, a source with direct knowledge of the proposals said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Bolsonaro was elected president in October on a market-friendly platform that included privatizations, cost-cutting, reforming a ballooning public pension system and stopping the fiscal deficit.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Economists have often criticized Brazil\\u2019s complicated tax system as a barrier to long-term growth. Companies spend on average 2,038 hours to do their taxes, or about 12 times the average in the wealthy OECD group of nations, according to the World Bank\\u2019s \\u201cDoing Business\\u201d index. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The source said Bolsonaro\\u2019s team had not yet settled on any of the three proposals. Marcos Cintra, one of his advisors, has often defended in public a tax on financial transactions. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"At the same time, Brazil\\u2019s Congress has been working on a tax reform plan of its own that supports adopting a value-added tax. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some Congressmen have said that they want to see that plan approved before the end of the year. Yet the plan would require a constitutional amendment, which under Brazilian law cannot be put to a vote until an army security federal intervention in the state of Rio de Janeiro is suspended. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Bolsonaro will be inaugurated as president on Jan. 1.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe mood in the Lower House and in the Senate is 100 percent behind approving the creation of a value-added tax this year,\\u201d said Luiz Carlos Hauly, the Congressman behind the plan. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Cintra has said in the past that a value-added tax \\u201cwould be disastrous\\u201d and that \\u201ctax reform requires a way to collect the tax based on the electronic cash flow of the banking system.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Marcela Ayres; Writing by Marcelo Rochabrun; Editing by Bruno Federowski and Bernadette Baum\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(39,'REUTERS','UPDATE 1-U.S. Treasury to sell more debt in auctions from October','Anonymous','November 21, 2018   4:41 PM','[{\"content\": \"(Adds background) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Nov 21 (Reuters) - The U.S. Treasury Department said on Wednesday it enlarged the auction sizes of short- and medium-term government notes for sale from a month ago, bringing the total of coupon debt for sale next week to $129 billion. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The government has been ramping up its debt issuance this year to finance a growing budget deficit as a result of the massive tax cut enacted last December and a spending agreement reached in February. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"On Monday, the Treasury will hold a $39 billion auction of two-year notes, which is $1 billion larger than the two-year auction in October. This is largest two-year offering since June 2010. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"On Tuesday, it will sell $40 billion of five-year debt , which is the largest monthly supply of this maturity since May 2010. It is $1 billion more than the five-year debt sold last month. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"On Wednesday, the Treasury will auction $32 billion in seven-year notes, $1 billion bigger than the seven-year auction held in October. It is the largest seven-year offering since April 2010. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Treasury also sell $18 billion in two-year floating-rate notes on Wednesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Separately, the Treasury said on Wednesday it will sell $39 billion in three-month bills and $36 billion in six-month bills on Monday. Earlier this week, it sold $42 billion in three-month T-bills and $36 billion in six-month T-bills. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Richard Leong\\nEditing by Tom Brown\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(40,'REUTERS','StanChart to end supervision by New York regulator for compliance failings','Anonymous','November 21, 2018   4:32 PM','[{\"content\": \"LONDON, Nov 21 (Reuters) - Standard Chartered will on Dec. 31 end a period of supervision by an independent monitor it had agreed with New York\\u2019s Department of Financial Services (DFS), the DFS said on Wednesday, bringing to a close one strand of the bank\\u2019s punishment for past failings in compliance controls. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Standard Chartered agreed to the supervision with the regulator in 2012 as part of a wider settlement with U.S. authorities in relation to the bank\\u2019s dealings with Iran-related entities. The bank agreed an extension to that monitorship in 2014 and again in April 2016. (Reporting by Lawrence White; Editing by Adrian Croft)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(41,'REUTERS','Italian bond yields tumble as investors hold nerve after EU budget rejection','Virginia Furness','November 21, 2018   4:37 PM','[{\"content\": \"LONDON (Reuters) - Italian bonds rallied on Wednesday, pushing two-year yields down as much as 23 basis points as markets shrugged off the European Commission\\u2019s rejection of Rome\\u2019s draft budget and focused on the possibility of compromise between the two sides. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Deputy Prime Minister Matteo Salvini refuted a La Stampa newspaper report that he was open to reviewing the 2019 deficit of 2.4 percent of GDP, but said other aspects of the budget could be discussed. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte said he was worried about Italy\\u2019s bond spread over Germany and that the government would respond with reforms. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Italy/Germany 10-year bond yield spread tightened to 313 basis points, having widened to 335 bps on Tuesday DE10IT10=RR. It has more than doubled this year.   \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThere is obviously a hint in the reports from Italy that there might be some tweaks to the budget in due course,\\u201d said Chris Scicluna, head of economic research at Daiwa Capital Markets in London.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cI don\\u2019t think there will be substantive changes but we did have a significant selloff yesterday, so there\\u2019s a better mood around bond markets today.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The European Commission said the Italian budget does not comply with the EU debt reduction criteria and that an excessive deficit procedure is warranted. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"While the euro EUR= briefly turned negative and Italy\'s benchmark stock index .FTMIB hit a session low on the news, markets soon recovered. Italian bank shares were up 2.5 percent on the day .FTIT8300 and bond yields extended their slide.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe know how negotiations work in Europe and the most likely outcome in this case is that both sides agree on a compromise,\\u201d said Jonas David, a strategist at UBS Global Wealth Management. \\u201cWe may see further negative headlines but at this stage we need to read between the headlines a bit.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy\\u2019s two-year bond yield fell 23 bps to touch 1.15 percent, the lowest in almost two weeks, while 10-year yields were down 13 bps, falling to about 3.49 percent IT10YT=RR.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Yields were set for their biggest daily drop in over three weeks, with an improvement in global risk sentiment helping equity markets to stabilize. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy\\u2019s bond price gains also followed hefty losses on Tuesday, caused partly by a \\u201cBTP Italia\\u201d retail debt sale in which small investors took up just 723 million euros ($824 million) of the bonds on Monday and Tuesday. The previous such sale had received orders worth 3.7 billion euros in the first two days. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Many remain skeptical about a sustained Italian recovery, noting Rome had made no significant changes in the revised budget it submitted to Brussels. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe don\\u2019t think they\\u2019re going to budge much. There might be some word play with the Commission, but Italy is still going to run a deficit of 2.4 percent,\\u201d said Lyn Graham Taylor, rates strategist at Rabobank. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile, PIMCO\\u2019s chief investment officer for global fixed income, Andrew Balls, said the possibility of Italy defaulting on its debt is unlikely but cannot be ruled out altogether. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"As Italian yields fell, Greece\\u2019s bond market also recovered slightly from a heavy selloff in the previous session, with five-year yields down 3 bps GR5YT=RR.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"They had earlier touched the highest in more than two months, coming under pressure from renewed concern about the  Greek banking sector and contagion from Italy\\u2019s volatility. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Commission said on Wednesday Athens needed to speed up implementation of reforms. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The rally in riskier euro zone bonds dented demand for safer  debt, with 10-year German yields rising 2 basis points to 0.37 percent DE10YT=RR.   \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Graphic: Italian bond yields fall - tmsnrt.rs/2R2kqHR \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Virginia Furness; Additional reporting by Dhara Ranasinghe and Sujata Rao; Editing by David Stamp\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(42,'REUTERS','Google invests $700 million in Danish data center, secures green energy','Stine Jacobsen, Teis Jensen','November 20, 2018   6:32 AM','[{\"content\": \"COPENHAGEN (Reuters) - Google will invest almost $700 million in a Danish data center powered by the abundant green energy that underpins power- \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"intensive companies\\u2019 interest in the Nordic region.     \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Google also said it would sign a power purchase agreement (PPA) for the new Danish data center to ensure it is powered by renewable energy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Nordic countries, which can generate electricity relatively cheaply from renewable sources such as hydropower and wind, have long been a magnet for heavy power-using industries, but are now attracting power-hungry data centers. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Annual investment in Nordic data centers could double to more than 4 billion euros ($4.57 billion) by 2025, a new study published by the Nordic Council of Ministers, the official body for regional cooperation, said on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Big companies have rushed to secure cheap renewable energy to manage costs and reduce their carbon footprint through corporate PPAs which allow firms such as Google, owned by Alphabet Inc, Facebook and Microsoft to buy directly from energy generators. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Nordic countries are competing for the multi-billion-euro investments with the more established FLAP-D markets, an acronym for Frankfurt-London-Amsterdam-Paris-Dublin.      \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"While the Nordics are still perceived as less connected than these markets, the region is likely to gain market share, the Council of Ministers\\u2019 study said.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This is partly due to the region\\u2019s plentiful renewable energy and political stability while the planned installation of major fiber optic links to North America and Asia will improve connectivity. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Google said it is also evaluating investments in a number of onshore and offshore wind and solar energy projects in Denmark.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In September, Google signed a 10-year deal to buy renewable energy from three new wind farms being built in Finland that will power one of its data centers. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Last year, the number of new corporate PPAs, primarily wind and solar, reached a record with more than 5 gigawatt contracted, up almost a third from the 2016 level, according to the International Renewable Energy Agency. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The new data center in the small city of Fredericia will cost 4.5 billion Danish crowns ($689 million) and employ 150 to 200 staff once completed in 2021, according to the plans.     \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Besides Fredericia, Google bought another plot last year in Aabenraa, Denmark, next to a planned Apple Inc data center. Facebook has also planned a data center in Denmark. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Denmark is home to a large wind energy sector including turbine maker Vestas Wind Systems and offshore wind farm developer Orsted. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Stine Jacobsen and Teis Jensen, Editing by Sherry Jacob-Phillips, Louise Heavens and Adrian Croft\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(43,'REUTERS','CORRECTED-PIMCO\'s bond chief Balls says Italy default cannot be ruled out','Anonymous','November 21, 2018   2:07 PM','[{\"content\": \"(Corrects paragraph 4 to show Balls said California issued parallel currency after 2008, not in 2008) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"LONDON, Nov 21 (Reuters) - The possibility of Italy defaulting on its debt is unlikely but cannot be ruled out altogether, a senior official at the world\\u2019s biggest bond investor said on Wednesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"PIMCO\\u2019s chief investment officer for global fixed income, Andrew Balls, said the issuance of a parallel currency or redenomination to the Italian lira were more plausible scenarios. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cItalian sovereign default is unlikely but it is not a zero probability. The more plausible scenario is a combination of issuing a parallel currency or even redenomination,\\u201d he said at a conference in London. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cCalifornia issued a parallel currency after 2008 so if it could happen there it is not obvious it couldn\\u2019t happen in Italy.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Balls said that it makes sense to be underweight France and European credit in general in case of a full-blown crisis in Europe. He added that he does not see great scope for the European Central Bank to raise interest rates in 2019. (Reporting by Virginia Furness, Writing by Abhinav Ramnarayan, Editing by Tommy Wilkes)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(44,'REUTERS','European shares set to snap five-day losing streak, Italy banks off highs','Danilo Masoni','November 21, 2018   8:51 AM','[{\"content\": \"MILAN (Reuters) - European shares rose on Wednesday in a broad-based bounce that saw the battered tech sector recover following a widespread sell-off on worries over iPhone demand and pricey valuations. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italian banks also rose but came off highs after the League Party denied a report that Matteo Salvini, its leader and the deputy Prime Minister, was willing to compromise on the budget.      \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The STOXX 600  rose 0.5 percent by 1000 GMT, and was set to snap a five-day losing streak that had pushed the pan-European benchmark close to the nearly two-year low hit last month.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Germany\'s DAX .GDAXI index rose 0.6 percent and London\'s FTSE 100 .FTSE added 0.7 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italian banks .FTIT8300 rose as much as 2.6 percent at the open after a report said Salvini might be open to review the government\\u2019s 2019 budget, fuelling hopes the country could avert a clash with the European Commission. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But later they pared some gains as the League Party said Salvini was not seeking any changes to the 2019 draft budget. The European Commission is set to release its response to Italy\\u2019s draft plan later in the day.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Italian banking index was up 2.3 percent.     \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italian banks have lost around 40 billion euros in market cap from their May peak as worries over Italy\\u2019s spending plans lifted government bonds yields to multi-year highs, eroding the value of their large sovereign bond portfolios and raising the risk of possible capital injections for the weaker lenders. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Top gainer among Italian banks was Milan-based Banco BMP (BAMI.MI), which rallied 6 percent to the top of the euro STOXX index, while heavyweight lenders Intesa Sanpaolo (ISP.MI) and UniCredit (CRDI.MI) rose 2.6 and 1.8 percent respectively.          \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The broader European banking index .SX7P was the biggest sectoral gainer in early morning trading, up 1.4 percent, while tech stocks .SX8P advanced 0.6 percent, after falling to their lowest level since the end of February. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Stocks supplying chips to Apple rose. STMicroelectronics (STM.MI), Infineon (IFXGn.DE) and AMS (AMS.S) rose between 1.7 percent to 3.7 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Even though the rebound was broad-based with most sectors trading in positive territory, investors remained cautious over the outlook for the market due to lingering concerns over slowing economic and earnings growth. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe record highs for the FTSE 100 and the DAX ... now seem a distant memory and with the U.S. FAANG (Facebook, Apple, Amazon, Netflix and Google) rally now also in bear market territory, the big question now is how much further can we fall, or are we near a short term base?,\\u201d said CMC Markets analyst Michael Hewson. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Elsewhere, corporate updates triggered sharp share price moves. Babcock (BAB.L) plummeted 8 percent after the British defense contractor took a one-off charge of 120 million pounds to reshape its business and warned that revenue from its nuclear decommissioning division would drop more than expected. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Indivior (INDV.L) fell 13 percent after it warned it could take a hit if the rival drug from Dr. Reddy\\u2019s Laboratories (REDY.NS) comes to market this year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Johnson Matthey (JMAT.L) led gainers on the STOXX, up 8 percent, after the specialty chemicals company raised its full-year guidance.    \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Danilo Masoni; Editing by Andrew Heavens\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(45,'REUTERS','Sliding banks, tumbling tech drag Europe stocks to three-week low','Helen Reid','November 20, 2018   8:45 AM','[{\"content\": \"LONDON (Reuters) - European stocks fell on Tuesday, with banks weighing heavily on worries about slowing economic growth, fading earnings momentum, Italy\\u2019s budget, and a lower likelihood of rate hikes in Europe next year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The pan-European STOXX 600  index fell 1.1 percent to its lowest level in more than three weeks, with Germany\'s DAX .GDAXI down 1.2 percent and Britain\'s FTSE 100 .FTSE down 0.8 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Though European stocks have substantially lagged the United States this year and valuations have fallen, investors said it was too early for the region to be an attractive value play. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt would have to be table-thumpingly cheap to make valuations themselves offset people\\u2019s scepticism about Europe\\u2019s ability to grow,\\u201d said Kevin Gardiner, global investment strategist at Rothschild & Co Wealth Management.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Europe\\u2019s bank stocks index .SX7P sank 2.3 percent, its worst day in nearly six weeks, with Italian lenders .FTIT8300 down 2.6 percent at their lowest level since the end of November 2016.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italian government bond yields soared as investors fled its sovereign debt again with Rome showing no signs of backing down in a budget row with the European Commission. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Mediobanca (MDBI.MI), UniCredit (CRDI.MI), Banco BPM (BAMI.MI), and UBI Banca (UBI.MI) fell 2.4 to 5.4 percent.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Deutsche Bank (DBKGn.DE) fell 4.8 percent to a fresh record low. Also weighing on the German lender was a Wall Street Journal report saying Deutsche Bank handled about $150 billion in potentially suspicious transactions as a correspondent bank for Danske Bank (DANSKE.CO).         \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Weak earnings also hurt the bank sector. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Swiss bank and wealth manager Julius Baer (BAER.S) fell 7.2 percent after it said it was cutting spending under adverse market conditions, warning it may not achieve its cost-income target this year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cMarket estimates are set to drop significantly,\\u201d wrote Baader Helvea analysts. \\u201cThere are clear challenges within the Wealth Management sphere which look set to continue short term,\\u201d wrote KBW analysts.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Anxieties about iPhone growth at Apple swept tech stocks, another big drag on the region. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The sector .SX8P fell two percent to its lowest level since the end of February. Stocks supplying chips to Apple were among the worst-performing. STMicroelectronics (STM.MI) shares tumbled 1.8 percent, Infineon (IFXGn.DE) fell 1 percent and AMS (AMS.S) lost 0.9 percent.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The tech sector is down 9.8 percent this year, lagging oil, healthcare, media, and utilities. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"French carmaker Renault (RENA.PA) remained under pressure, down 1.2 percent as Exane and BAML analysts downgraded the stock. It fell 8.4 percent on Monday when CEO Carlos Ghosn was arrested on allegations of financial misconduct.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"German payments firm Wirecard\\u2019s (WDIG.DE) shares fell 5.8 percent after the company said it expected core earnings between 740 and 800 million euros, implying profits growth of 37.5 percent \\u2013 at the midpoint of the expected range. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Overall earnings growth expectations for MSCI Europe have been falling recently as analysts readjust their estimates to a bleaker picture for the global economy.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe expect low equity returns across all regions for 2019,\\u201d wrote Goldman Sachs analysts.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWith slow profit growth, investors are likely to focus on a deterioration in the growth and inflation mix.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Graphic: MSCI Europe earnings growth expectations fall Nov 20 - tmsnrt.rs/2PCbXP7 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Helen Reid and Danilo Masoni, Editing by Josephine Mason, John Stonestreet, William Maclean\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(46,'REUTERS','Tech tremors drive European stocks down to three-week low','Anonymous','November 20, 2018   8:42 AM','[{\"content\": \"(For a live blog on European stocks, type LIVE/ in an Eikon news window) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"LONDON, Nov 20 (Reuters) - Fresh anxieties about tech stocks dented European stocks as a drop in Apple shares on Wall Street, after a report the consumer tech giant is cutting production for its new iPhones, sapped appetite for the sector globally. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The tech sector sank as much as 1.7 percent, hitting its lowest level since Feb 28 2017 as stocks supplying chips to Apple suffered. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Apple suppliers were among the worst-performing. STMicroelectronics shares tumbled 3 percent, Infineon fell 3 percent, and AMS lost 3 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Tech has lost its crown as best-performing sector in Europe and is now down 8 percent this year, behind sectors including oil, healthcare, media, and utilities. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The pan-European STOXX 600 fell 0.4 percent by 0825 GMT, with Germany\\u2019s DAX down 0.7 percent and Britain\\u2019s FTSE 100 down 0.2 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares in French carmaker Renault remained under pressure after its 8.4 percent drop on Monday when CEO Carlos Ghosn was arrested. Downgrades from Exane and BAML analysts weighed the stock down 1.3 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Outside tech, results drove the biggest moves. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"German payments firm Wirecard\\u2019s shares fell 4.5 percent to the bottom of the DAX after the company said it expected core earnings between 740 and 800 million euros, implying profits growth of 37.5 percent \\u2013 at the midpoint of the range. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"British electrical components maker Halma rose 2.7 percent, among top STOXX 600 gainers after the company reported a 19 percent jump in pretax profit for the six months ended Sept. 30. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It also warned Brexit could cause supply chain disruptions. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Peer Spectris topped the STOXX with a 7.3 percent gain after the company stuck to its full-year outlook. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"British challenger bank CYBG, however, sank 8 percent to the bottom of the European index as profits disappointed. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Helen Reid, Editing by Josephine Mason\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(47,'REUTERS','European stocks resume their slide a tech tumbles, Renault slumps','Helen Reid','November 19, 2018   8:48 AM','[{\"content\": \"LONDON/MILAN (Reuters) - European shares resumed their slide on Monday to end at a three-week low as tech stocks came under fresh selling pressure on worries over Apple\\u2019s iPhone demand and as carmaker Renault sank after the arrest of its CEO for alleged financial misconduct. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The pan-European STOXX 600  opened up 0.6 percent but flagged rapidly and ended the day down 0.7 percent, its fourth straight day of losses. The current bear market has made it increasingly hard for indexes to hold on to early gains.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"With the earnings season petering out, management issues, broker notes and M&A were the main drivers of the market. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Renault (RENA.PA) was the top faller on the STOXX 600 after its CEO Carlos Ghosn, who is also chairman of the car maker\\u2019s Japanese partner Nissan, was arrested in Japan on allegations of under-reporting his salary. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dramatic fall for one of the best-known figures in the global car industry raised questions among investors about the future of the alliance, sending Renault shares down 9.4 percent to their lowest level since October 2014. Ghosn could not be reached for comment. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt is hard not to conclude that there may be a gulf opening up between Renault and Nissan,\\u201d said Bernstein analyst Max Warburton, raising the prospect of a potential \\u201cre-Japanization\\u201d of Nissan and the end of the alliance. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The fall, the biggest since Britain\\u2019s vote in 2016 to leave the European Union, wiped about $2 billion off the company\\u2019s market capitalization.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Tech stocks were the biggest sectoral fallers, down 2 to a 20-month closing low, with the sector hit by a slide in Apple  (AAPL.O) shares on concerns about iPhone demand.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A report by the Wall Street Journal said Apple had cut production orders in recent weeks for all three iPhone models launched in September. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Apple suppliers ams (AMS.S), Infineon (IFXGn.DE) and BE Semiconductor (BESI.AS) fell between 0.2 and 3 percent, while   STMicro (STM.PA) added 0.3 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Telecom Italia (TLIT.MI) shares climbed 3.9 percent after Italy\\u2019s biggest telecoms company appointed Luigi Gubitosi as its new CEO, fuelling talk of a possible sale of its fixed-line network .     \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Salvatore Ferragamo (SFER.MI) shares fell 3.3 percent after Bank of America Merrill Lynch cut the stock to underperform after a four-day luxury goods field trip to China, a key market for the luxury sector. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Swatch (UHR.S) shares lost 3.8 percent after BAML slashed its price target on the stock by 27 percent, saying watch retailers they met confirmed a significant slowdown in recent months.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Overall Europe\\u2019s earnings season has failed to impress investors, and analysts have continued to cut their earnings estimates for the STOXX 600 at the fastest pace since the Brexit vote selloff of June 2016.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe current economic cycle has been particularly weak and has generated very little revenue growth,\\u201d wrote Goldman Sachs analysts. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cNet income margins have reached their pre-crisis level and we expect them to peak this year,\\u201d they added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Helen Reid and Danilo Masoni; Editing by Gareth Jones\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(48,'REUTERS','Miners drive European stocks up on trade war hopes, Renault falls','Anonymous','November 19, 2018   8:37 AM','[{\"content\": \"(For a live blog on European stocks, type LIVE/ in an Eikon news window) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"LONDON, Nov 19 (Reuters) - European shares started the week on the front foot, against spreadbetters\\u2019 early expectations for a fall, as signs of an easing in U.S.-China trade war tensions boosted mining and technology stocks. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Miners drove the lion\\u2019s share of gains in Europe, with the basic resources sector up 1.2 percent and construction & materials up 1 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"London copper edged up after U.S. President Donald Trump said he may not impose more tariffs on Chinese goods, but gains were capped amid tensions between the two major economies at a regional AEPC summit. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The pan-European STOXX 600 was up 0.6 percent by 0830 GMT, after three straight down days, with miners and healthcare stocks the top gainers while the tech sector also benefited from trade war easing. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"With the earnings season petering out, management issues, broker notes and M&A were the main drivers of the market. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Novo Nordisk shares climbed 4.6 percent, among top STOXX gainers, after JP Morgan upgraded the pharmaceuticals company to \\u201coverweight\\u201d. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Renault shares fell 3.9 percent, the biggest STOXX 600 fallers, as Japan\\u2019s Asahi newspaper reported Nissan chairman Carlos Ghosn is to be arrested for alleged financial trading violations. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Telecom Italia shares climbed 2.9 percent after Italy\\u2019s biggest telecoms company appointed Luigi Gubitosi as its new CEO. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Salvatore Ferragamo shares fell 3.7 percent, bottom of Italy\\u2019s FTSE MIB index, after Bank of America Merrill Lynch analysts cut the luxury stock to \\u201cunderperform\\u201d after a four-day luxury goods field trip to China. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Swatch shares also lost 2.7 percent after BAML slashed its price target on the stock by 27 percent, saying watch retailers they met confirmed a significant slowdown in recent months. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Chipmaker stocks AMS, STMicro and Siltronic , which are highly sensitive to trade war news, were among top gainers, up 2.9 to 4.7 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The gains were helping the sector claw back some of the ground lost last week after a series of profit warnings ahead of the crucial holiday season. (Reporting by Helen Reid; editing by Josephine Mason)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(49,'REUTERS','European shares wobble as Brexit angst lingers','Helen Reid, Julien Ponthus','November 16, 2018   8:45 AM','[{\"content\": \"LONDON (Reuters) - European shares wobbled and closed just in the red after a choppy session on Friday as traders waited to see if Britain\\u2019s Prime Minister Theresa May would face a no-confidence vote over her draft European Union divorce deal. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The pan-European stocks index  started morning trading on a gentle rebound from losses on Thursday. But it gradually lost steam as speculation mounted about a leadership challenge.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy\\u2019s budget showdown with the European Commission also did little for risk appetite. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The STOXX 600 closed down O.12 percent and Britain\'s FTSE 100 .FTSE fell 0.3 percent.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cEquities in general continue to trade in a sideways fashion, with attempts to move higher frustrated by a collection of worries\\u201d, IG analyst Chris Beauchamp commented. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"French media company Vivendi\\u2019s (VIV.PA)  quarterly results helped to lift the media sector .SXMP 0.55 percent.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Vivendi shares topped the CAC 40, climbing 3 percent after the company posted stronger than expected third-quarter sales, helped by growth in music streaming at its Universal Music Group (UMG). It also said it was lining up banks for a possible sale of part of the UMG division. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Deutsche Bank analysts said the fourth-quarter slate for Universal looks \\u201cstrong\\u201d with releases announced for multiple platinum sellers and ongoing Drake and Eminem sales. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWith solid steps toward a stake sale in 2019, this is a timely reminder that valuations of over 20 billion euros for UMG are not hype,\\u201d they wrote in a note to clients.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The technology sector .SX8P lagged the market, down 0.7 percent after worse than expected results from U.S. chipmaker Nvidia (NVDA.O), the latest in a run of negative news for tech components producers. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"German semiconductor maker Siltronic (WAFGn.DE) slid 3 percent, among the biggest STOXX fallers.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Dutch lender ABN AMRO (ABNd.AS) also fell 2 percent after its results. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"ABB (ABBN.S) shares were up 1.5 percent after sources said the Swiss industrials group is in talks with three Asian suitors for the sale of its Power Grids business. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Swedish electrical components company Nibe (NIBEb.ST) jumped 5.7 percent, the top STOXX gainer, after its results. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Outside large-cap stocks, Danish industrial component maker NKT (NKT.CO) plunged 22.7 percent after it cut its full-year earnings outlook and CEO Michael Hedegaard left the company. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares in the maker of the \\u201cAngry Birds\\u201d mobile game, Rovio Entertainment (ROVIO.HE), jumped 12.4 percent after third-quarter results. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Fewer companies than usual have beaten expectations in Europe\\u2019s third-quarter results season, with companies facing difficulties converting sales into profits as costs climbed.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"IBES Refinitiv showed analysts expect third-quarter earnings to grow 15.8 percent year on year in euro terms, and 2019 European earnings to edge higher than the United States. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Helen Reid and Julien Ponthus; Editing by David Goodman and Andrew Heavens\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(50,'REUTERS','European shares bounce back from Brexit bruising','Anonymous','November 16, 2018   8:37 AM','[{\"content\": \"(For a live blog on European stocks, type LIVE/ in an Eikon news window) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"LONDON, Nov 16 (Reuters) - European shares recovered on Friday as investors licked their wounds after a tumultuous week and strong results from Vivendi boosted the media sector. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The pan-European stocks index was still on course for a weekly loss after two straight weeks of gains, though, as Brexit chaos, Italy\\u2019s budget showdown with the European Commission, and anxious oil markets sapped risk appetite. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The STOXX 600 was up 0.7 percent by 0830 GMT, with Germany\\u2019s DAX up 0.6 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Britain\\u2019s FTSE 100 and FTSE 250 both recovered, rising 0.6 percent after Thursday\\u2019s sharp selloff in domestic stocks on ministerial resignations. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The tech market lagged the market with the weakest sectoral performance, up just 0.3 percent, after disappointing results from U.S. chipmaker Nvidia, the latest in a string of negative news for tech components producers. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Strong results from French media company Vivendi helped boost the media sector up 1.5 percent, the top gainer. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Vivendi shares climbed 4.7 percent after the firm reported stronger than expected third-quarter sales, helped by growth at its Universal Music Group (UMG) arm. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It also said it was lining up banks for a possible sale of part of the UMG division. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"ABB shares gained 3.3 percent after sources said the Swiss industrials firm is in talks with three Asian suitors for the sale of its Power Grids business. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares in British pharmaceuticals firm AstraZeneca fell 2.5 percent after its lung cancer drug Imfinzi failed a key study. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Chocolate producer Barry Callebaut fell 3.7 percent, the biggest faller in Europe, after members of the majority stakeholder Jacobs family sold 150,000 shares, amounting to 2.7 percent of the company. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Outside the large-cap space, Danish industrial component maker NKT plunged 21 percent after it slashed its full-year earnings outlook and its CEO Michael Hedegaard left the company. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares in the maker of the \\u201cAngry Birds\\u201d mobile game, Rovio Entertainment, jumped 9.8 percent after its third-quarter results. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Helen Reid; editing by Josephine Mason\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(51,'REUTERS','Dollar falters as risk appetite increases','Gertrude Chavez-Dreyfuss','November 21, 2018   1:16 AM','[{\"content\": \"NEW YORK (Reuters) - The dollar fell on Wednesday, as risk appetite improved, bolstered by higher stocks and a stronger euro, which was boosted by hopes for a resolution of Italy\\u2019s budget. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Wall Street shares recovered after a steep two-day sell-off, led by a rebound in Apple Inc and other major technology stocks. For two days, U.S. equity losses had bolstered safe-haven currencies such as the dollar, yen, and Swiss franc. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe melting of risk appetite generated little follow-through, offering risk appetite a pop,\\u201d said Mark McCormick, North American head of FX strategy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Another factor boosting risk appetite was optimism about the Italian budget, even though the European Union rejected Rome\\u2019s fiscal plans for failing to comply with euro zone rules. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In mid-morning trading, the dollar index was down 0.2 percent at 96.627. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro, the largest component in the dollar index, rose 0.2 percent at $1.1392. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The European Commission took its first step toward disciplining Italy over its draft budget and said the government should face EU action to reduce its deficit. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Still, the euro rallied, especially after Italian Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte expressed concern about the government bond spread and pledged reforms. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro spiked early on a report Italian Deputy Prime Minister Matteo Salvini may be open to reviewing the fiscal plan for 2019. Salvini later said he was not open to negotiations over Italy\\u2019s deficit target of 2.4 percent of gross domestic product, though other aspects of the budget could be discussed.   \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cEven if Italy becomes subject to the Excessive Deficit Procedure it may be several weeks before that procedure begins, and Italy will have several months to respond to the concerns raised by the European Union,\\u201d said Nick Bennenbroek, currency strategist at Wells Fargo in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cMoreover, at the end of the day, it\\u2019s possible that no financial penalties would be imposed, and that any sanction would be only symbolic,\\u201d he added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro has risen in six out of the last seven sessions but analysts said the currency remained vulnerable to the political risks emanating from the third-largest economy of the 19-country euro zone. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar has also felt some pressure as Federal Reserve officials this week expressed concern about a potential global slowdown, leading some investors to bet the rate-hike cycle was near its end. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The safe-haven Japanese yen fell against the dollar, which rose 0.3 percent to 113.06. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Gertrude Chavez-Dreyfuss in New York; additional reporting by Tom Finn in London; Editing by David Gregorio\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(52,'REUTERS','World stocks try to find feet after tech-driven rout','Sujata Rao','November 21, 2018   12:34 AM','[{\"content\": \"LONDON (Reuters) - World stocks steadied on Wednesday and Wall Street was set to open firmer after the previous session saw $1 trillion wiped off the value of leading tech shares, while oil prices staged a modest rebound after slumping to one-year lows. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Equity futures for all three U.S. indexes were up 0.4 to 0.7 percent, after two days of losses that wiped out the S&P500\\u2019s gains for the year and left the tech-heavy Nasdaq benchmark teetering on the brink of falling into the red . \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Tuesday\\u2019s losses were led by the technology sector, as investors lightened holdings of FAANG shares \\u2014 Facebook, Apple, Amazon, Netflix and Google \\u2014 the group that had propelled the Wall Street\\u2019s decade-long bull market.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But sentiment appeared to recover slightly as Brent crude rebounded almost 2 percent after a six percent slide, MSCI\\u2019s Asia ex-Japan index closed flat and the main all-country equity benchmark attempted to snap two days of falls. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Apple and Amazon shares rose 1.0-1.5 percent in pre-market trades. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"European equities rose 0.4 percent, with the battered tech and bank sectors both up around 0.8 percent. The dollar, which had jumped 0.7 percent on Tuesday, slipped 0.2 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"David Vickers, senior portfolio manager at Russell Investments, noted however that gloom has tended to deepen in volatile markets as the Wall Street session progresses and more company earnings emerge. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cHigh-flying momentum stocks have come off in a fairly spectacular fashion. At one point Apple and Amazon accounted for 40 percent of U.S. equity gains and people were just recycling money into the winners,\\u201d Vickers said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThat\\u2019s come off the boil and set the cat among the pigeons... We\\u2019ve seen a lot of reflexivity, when selling begets selling, the market starts to turn over, people take profits, it leads to another leg down and so on.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Markets also appear to be preparing for a loss of momentum in global economic growth as China takes a hit from Washington\\u2019s trade tariffs and the United States comes off the sugar-high of President Donald Trump\\u2019s tax cuts.    \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Graphic: Third-quarter earnings as of Nov 20 - tmsnrt.rs/2PDCn30 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Vickers said that after 20 percent-plus earnings growth at U.S. companies, some investors were disappointed with signs this would slow to single digits as the stimulus effect wore off. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIf you have a market like the S&P500, which is two standard deviations expensive, it becomes difficult if you don\\u2019t think you will get the same kinds of earnings growth in future,\\u201d he added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Growth worries have also been revived by comments from U.S. Federal Reserve officials who suggested economic outlook concerns could slow the pace of its monetary policy tightening cycle, or even end it.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The comments knocked U.S. 10-year bond yields to near two-month lows around 3.03 percent, down from 3.25 percent in early- November, but yields rose around 3 bps on Wednesday to around 3.07 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Jonas David, a strategist at UBS Global Wealth Management, said a G20 meeting between Trump and Chinese President Xi Jinping at the end of the month could determine the course of bond markets and euro/dollar rates. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIf we don\\u2019t get a relaxation of trade tensions after the G20, markets may start questioning the prospect of another Fed rate hike in December,\\u201d he said.     \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro rose 0.3 percent after a 0.75 percent drop on Tuesday, buoyed by promises of reform from Italy\\u2019s prime minister and hopes that Rome and the European Commission would reach a compromise in a dispute over the deficit in the  draft 2019 Italian budget. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy\\u2019s two-year bond yield fell 17 bps at 1.22 percent while 10-year yields tumbled as much as nine bps to 3.53 percent, and were set for their biggest daily drop in over three weeks. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The European Commission has rejected the draft plan but UBS Wealth\\u2019s David said markets were right to be optimistic about the eventual outcome of the row between Brussels and Rome. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe have to keep an eye on these dynamics but factors related to economic momentum in the euro zone and the Fed (interest rate) outlook are far more important (for the euro),\\u201d he added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Graphic: Italy\'s 10-year bond yield tumbles - tmsnrt.rs/2QV3WRL \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Sujata Rao; additional reporting Shinichi Saoshiro in Tokyo; Editing by David Stamp\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(53,'REUTERS','FOREX-Euro rallies on hopes of Italy budget compromise','Tom Finn','November 21, 2018   12:07 PM','[{\"content\": \"* Euro rallies despite European Commission rejecting Italy budget \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Italy Deputy PM denies being open to reviewing fiscal plans \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Dollar looks bid amid fears of global growth \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Yen down, sterling up as investors await Brexit developments \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Graphic: World FX rates in 2018 tmsnrt.rs/2egbfVh (Adds Salvini comments, updates prices) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By Tom Finn \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"LONDON, Nov 21 (Reuters) - The euro strengthened on Wednesday on hopes for a compromise in the row over Italy\\u2019s budget, though the European Union rejected Rome\\u2019s fiscal plans for failing to comply with euro zone rules. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The European Commission took its first step on Wednesday towards disciplining Italy over its draft budget and said that the government should face action from the EU to reduce its deficit. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"That did not stop the single currency from rallying to a day\\u2019s high of $1.1418, up 0.4 percent, after Italian Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte said he was worried about the government bond spread and would respond with reforms. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro spiked earlier in the session on a report that Deputy Prime Minister Matteo Salvini may be open to reviewing the fiscal plan for 2019. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Salvini later said he was not open to negotiations over Italy\\u2019s deficit target of 2.4 percent of gross domestic product, though other aspects of the budget could be discussed. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro has risen in six out of the last seven sessions but analysts said the currency remained vulnerable to the political risks emanating from the third-largest economy of the 19-country euro zone. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe potential for a further tussle between Rome and Brussels can have an impact on the overall euro zone economic growth, which will keep the euro under pressure,\\u201d said Michael McCarthy, chief markets strategist at CMC Markets. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro\\u2019s strength weighed on the dollar index, a measure of performance against six major currencies, which fell 0.2 percent to 96.557. The index gained 0.65 percent the day before. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar has been supported by investors seeking out the safe haven currency on mounting concern about global growth and a U.S.-China trade war. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"However, the currency felt some downward pressure this week from comments by Federal Reserve officials expressing concern about a potential global slowdown. Those comments led some investors to bet the rate-hike cycle was near its end. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Japanese yen fell 0.4 percent to trade at 112.71. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Despite its safe-haven status, the yen\\u2019s strength has been muted. Analysts suspect this is because Japanese investors have kept their money in U.S. and foreign markets, rather than bring it home. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The British pound traded up 0.2 percent at $1.2808 after losing 0.5 percent against the dollar on Tuesday. The pound is expected to trade sideways until the market gets more clarity on progress in the Brexit deal. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Canadian dollar dropped to a four-month low versus the dollar to trade at 1.3305 as the price of crude fell to its lowest level in more than a year. Canada is one of the world\\u2019s top oil exporters. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Elsewhere, the Australian dollar, often considered a barometer of risk appetite, gained 0.4 percent to trade at $0.7245. The Aussie dollar lost more than 1 percent on Tuesday as global risk sentiment worsened. (Additional reporting by Vatsal Srivastava; Editing by Toby Chopra)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(54,'REUTERS','GLOBAL MARKETS-World stocks struggle to find feet after tech-driven rout','Sujata Rao','November 21, 2018   10:00 AM','[{\"content\": \"* World stocks flat after big falls; Wall Street set for bounce \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Oil bounces modestly after big slide, but market still shaky \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* European shares and bonds firm; focus on Italy and European Commission \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Graphic: World FX rates in 2018 tmsnrt.rs/2egbfVh (Updates throughout, changes dateline, byline, adds charts) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By Sujata Rao \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"LONDON, Nov 21 (Reuters) - World stocks attempted to steady on Wednesday following a bruising Wall Street session that wiped $1 trillion off the value of leading U.S. tech shares, while oil prices staged a modest rebound after slumping to one-year lows. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. shares were set to open sharply firmer, futures indicated , after two days of losses that wiped out the S&P500\\u2019s gains for the year and left the tech-heavy Nasdaq index teetering on the brink of falling into the red. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Losses have been concentrated in the technology sector, as investors lightened holdings of FAANG shares \\u2014 Facebook, Apple, Amazon, Netflix and Google \\u2014 the group that had propelled the Wall Street\\u2019s decade-long bull market. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The falls saw the Nasdaq index touch seven-month lows and energy shares too had dropped in line with a 6 percent oil price slump S&P 500 . \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"That fed through to Asia on Wednesday, taking MSCI\\u2019s index of ex-Japan Asia-Pacific shares almost half a percent lower, but it clawed back some of those falls to trade flat by 0900 GMT. MSCI\\u2019s all-country benchmark was flat too, attempting to snap two days of falls. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"That, alongside a 1.5 percent bounce in Brent crude futures and some optimism over Italy\\u2019s budget stance, helped European equities open 0.4 percent higher, with a tech index up half a percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"David Vickers, senior portfolio manager at Russell Investments, noted however that gloom has tended to deepen as the Wall Street session progresses and more company earnings emerge. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cHigh-flying momentum stocks have come off in a fairly spectacular fashion. At one point Apple and Amazon accounted for 40 percent of U.S. equity gains and people were just recycling money into the winners,\\u201d Vickers said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThat\\u2019s come off the boil and set the cat among the pigeons... We\\u2019ve seen a lot of reflexivity, when selling begets selling, the market starts to turn over, people take profits, it leads to another leg down and so on.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Markets also appear to be preparing for a loss of momentum in global economic growth as China takes a hit from Washington\\u2019s trade tariffs and the United States comes off the sugar-high of President Donald Trump\\u2019s tax cuts. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Vickers said that after 20 percent-plus earnings growth at U.S. companies, some investors were disappointed with signs this would slow to single digits as the stimulus effect wore off. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIf you have a market like the S&P500, which is two standard deviations expensive, it becomes difficult if you don\\u2019t think you will get the same kinds of earnings growth in future,\\u201d he added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The growth concerns have also been revived by comments from U.S. Federal Reserve officials who suggested economic outlook concerns could slow the pace of its monetary policy tightening cycle or even end it. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The comments have knocked U.S. 10-year bond yields to near two-month lows around 3.03 percent, after trading above 3.25 percent at the start of November. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But the recovery in global sentiment allowed yields to rise around three bps to 3.08 percent while the dollar\\u2019s index, which had jumped 0.7 percent on Tuesday, slipped 0.2 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro rose after a 0.75 percent drop on Tuesday , buoyed by reports that Italy may be open to reviewing its draft budget for 2019, possibly easing a confrontation with the European Union. The League party, part of the ruling coalition, later denied the report. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italians bond yields fell up to 16 basis points initially, putting 10-year yields on track for their biggest daily drop in almost a month but the market gave up some of its gains after the denials. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italian bank shares too eased off session highs but were still up 2 percent on the day after sinking to two-year lows on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Focus is now on the European Commission which should take the first step on Wednesday towards disciplining Italy over its draft fiscal plan. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThis procedure will take several months, but stands to keep (government bonds) and the Italian banking sector under pressure. Favour euro underperformance in Europe and probably further choppy euro-dollar trading in a $1.1350-$1.1450 range,\\u201d ING Bank analysts told clients. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Oil\\u2019s bounce helped commodity currencies such as the Australian dollar and Norwegian crown, which recovered around 0.4 percent  versus the dollar after heavy recent slides. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Sujata Rao; additional reporting Shinichi\\nSaoshiro in Tokyo; Editing by David Stamp\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(55,'REUTERS','EMERGING MARKETS-Emerging currencies, stocks stabilise after dive','Susan Mathew','November 21, 2018   9:40 AM','[{\"content\": \"* China stocks recovery buoys markets \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Sri Lankan rupee hits record low \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Oil recovery helps Russian rouble \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By Susan Mathew \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Nov 21 (Reuters) - Emerging markets steadied on Wednesday, with shares flat after their worst day in more than a week, while Russia\\u2019s rouble and South Africa\\u2019s rand led a rebound in currencies. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A recovery in mainland China  and Hong Kong from more than 2 percent declines on Tuesday helped the MSCI index of EM stocks to rise marginally. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"South African blue chips gained half a percent and Turkey\\u2019s BIST index inched higher, adding to the gains. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This week\\u2019s shock to global markets has stemmed chiefly from the United States, where concerns over the big technology companies which have led a decade-long rally drove the tech-heavy Nasdaq index to a 7-month low on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Stephen Innes, head of Asia-Pacific trading at Oanda said that while two days of falls on Wall Street had administered a shock to markets worldwide, there was little sign so far of a lasting effect. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cRisk sentiment has stabilised ... at least for the time being,\\u201d he said. \\u201cLocal investors are viewing last night\\u2019s market meltdown as a broader U.S. equity correction on the back of early warning signals from the Federal Reserve Board, who are advising the US economy could struggle in 2019.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Poor holiday forecasts from major U.S. retailers, added to Fed policymakers\\u2019 softer comments in recent days, spurred Tuesday\\u2019s losses while concern about fading iPhone sales continues to hurt Apple Inc. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Most other emerging Asian bourses, which include a number of major Apple suppliers and many companies dependent on exports to the United States, fell as investors jettisoned riskier assets in the developing world. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Washington\\u2019s suggestion that China had failed to alter its \\u201cunfair\\u201d trade practices also had investors worrying about the chances of a positive outcome from a meeting between the leaders of the two countries later this month. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Most developing market currencies eked out gains against the dollar, which weakened as the euro gained traction on reports Italy may be open to reviewing its draft budget for 2019. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Turkish lira firmed 0.3 percent, and South Africa\\u2019s rand climbed 0.5 percent, while a rebound in oil from a 6 percent plunge overnight helped the rouble. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Sri Lankan rupee plummeted to an all-time low against the dollar. This followed the first credit downgrade of Sri Lanka by Moody\\u2019s since it started rating the country in 2010. The agency blamed a political crisis for aggravating already problematic finances. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The political situation also prompted the International Monetary Fund to delay discussions on its next loan tranche. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Hungary\\u2019s forint firmed as some investors bet on the central bank heading towards monetary tightening in the face of significant upside surprises in economic growth and inflation. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Poland\\u2019s zloty rose 0.2 percent after data on Tuesday showed robust industrial output. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For GRAPHIC on emerging market FX performance 2018, see tmsnrt.rs/2egbfVh For GRAPHIC on MSCI emerging index performance 2018, see tmsnrt.rs/2OusNdX \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For TOP NEWS across emerging markets \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For CENTRAL EUROPE market report, see \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For TURKISH market report, see \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For RUSSIAN market report, see (Reporting by Susan Mathew and Agamoni Ghosh in Bengaluru; editing by David Stamp)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(56,'REUTERS','FOREX-Euro rises on hopes of Italian budget compromise','Tom Finn','November 21, 2018   9:00 AM','[{\"content\": \"* Euro rises before European Commission responds to Italy budget \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Italy Deputy PM open to reviewing fiscal plans, newspaper says \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Dollar falls amid fears of global growth \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Yen down, sterling up as investors await Brexit developments \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Graphic: World FX rates in 2018 tmsnrt.rs/2egbfVh \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By Tom Finn \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"LONDON, Nov 21 (Reuters) - The euro rose on Wednesday, buoyed by reports that Italy may be open to reviewing its draft budget for 2019, potentially easing a confrontation with the European Union. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The European Commission is set to take the first step on Wednesday towards disciplining Italy over its draft fiscal plan. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But a report that Italian Deputy Prime Minister Matteo Salvini may be open to reviewing the government\\u2019s 2019 budget helped support Italian government bond markets and the euro on Wednesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The newspaper La Stampa said Salvini was ready to reduce the planned spending on a citizen\\u2019s income and the unwinding of a previous pension reform. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"At 0830 GMT, the euro traded up 0.3 percent at $1.14. . The single currency has risen in six out of the last seven sessions. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe potential for a further tussle between Rome and Brussels can have an impact on the overall Eurozone economic growth, which will keep the euro under pressure,\\u201d said Michael McCarthy, chief markets strategist at CMC Markets. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro\\u2019s strength weighed on the dollar index, a measure of performance against six major currencies, which fell 0.2 percent to 96.621. The index gained 0.65 percent the day before. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar has been supported by investors seeking out the safe haven currency on mounting concern about global growth and a U.S.-China trade war. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"With another rout in global equities on Tuesday, risk-averse traders sought shelter in the dollar, which climbed from a two-week low hit earlier on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar has been under pressure this week partly from comments by Federal Reserve officials expressing concern about a potential global slowdown. Those comments led some investors to bet the rate-hike cycle was near its end. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Japanese yen fell 0.15 percent to trade at 112.86. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Despite its safe-haven status, the yen\\u2019s strength has been muted. Analysts suspect this is because Japanese investors have kept their money in U.S. and foreign markets, rather than bring it home. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The British pound traded up 0.2 percent at $1.2808 after losing 0.5 percent against the dollar on Tuesday. The pound is expected to trade sideways until the market gets more clarity on progress in the Brexit deal. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Canadian dollar dropped to a four-month low versus the dollar to trade at 1.3305 as the price of crude fell to its lowest level in more than a year. Canada is one of the world\\u2019s top oil exporters. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Elsewhere, the Australian dollar, often considered a barometer of risk appetite, gained 0.3 percent to trade at $0.7236. The Aussie dollar lost more than 1 percent on Tuesday as global risk sentiment worsened. (Additional reporting by Vatsal Srivastava, editing by Larry King)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(57,'REUTERS','GLOBAL MARKETS-Asia stocks slip as growth worries grip global markets','Shinichi Saoshiro','November 21, 2018   6:20 AM','[{\"content\": \"* MSCI Asia-Pacific index down 0.45 pct, Nikkei loses 0.35 pct \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Spreadbetters expect European stocks to open slightly higher \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Safe haven bids amid broader risk aversion push up dollar \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Oil bounces modestly after big slide, but market still shaky \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Graphic: World FX rates in 2018 tmsnrt.rs/2egbfVh \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By Shinichi Saoshiro \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"TOKYO, Nov 21 (Reuters) - Asian stocks slipped on Wednesday as intensifying concerns about global economic growth gripped financial markets, sending Wall Street shares tumbling and driving the safe haven dollar up from a two-week low. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Spreadbetters expected European stocks to open slightly higher on bargain hunting after several days of losses, with Britain\\u2019s FTSE edging up 0.15 percent, Germany\\u2019s DAX gaining 0.3 percent and France\\u2019s CAC rising 0.25 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"MSCI\\u2019s broadest index of Asia-Pacific shares outside Japan fell 0.45 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Shanghai Composite Index swerved in and out of the red and was last down 0.05 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Australian stocks lost 0.5 percent, South Korea\\u2019s KOSPI retreated 0.4 percent and Japan\\u2019s Nikkei fell 0.35 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. stocks sold off for a second day on Tuesday as energy shares dropped with oil prices, while retailers including Target and Kohl\\u2019s sank after weak earnings and forecasts, fuelling worries about economic growth. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Nasdaq closed at its lowest in more than seven months on Tuesday while the S&P 500 and Dow ended at their weakest since late October. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt is difficult to pinpoint a single factor driving the global risk aversion. Apple and trade tensions seem to be touted as factors every other day, but it is difficult to blame them for all the woes,\\u201d said Soichiro Monji, senior economist at Daiwa SB Investments. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe markets appear to be starting to prepare for a loss of momentum in the global economy, although it is doing quite well at the moment.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The recent downturn in global equities has been led in part by a decline in U.S. technology shares, a group which had helped propel Wall Street\\u2019s long bull market. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe are anticipating more weakness in China, and a sharp slowdown in the United States next year. Given the highly-cyclical nature of the information technology (IT) sector, we have been arguing for a while that growth in its earnings would be hit especially hard in these circumstances,\\u201d wrote economists at Capital Economics. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar index against a basket of six major currencies was little changed at 96.776 after rallying 0.7 percent overnight, when it pulled away from a two-week trough of 96.042. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Earlier in the week, cautious comments by Federal Reserve officials about the global economic outlook knocked the dollar to two-week troughs as they suggested the central bank could slow the pace of or even end its monetary policy tightening cycle. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro was a shade higher at $1.1378 after sinking 0.75 percent the previous day. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar rose 0.1 percent to 112.87 yen. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Australian dollar, sensitive to shifts in risk sentiment, crawled up 0.25 percent to $0.7231 following a 1 percent slide the previous day. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Commodity currencies such as the Canadian dollar struggled in the wake of tumbling crude prices. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Canadian dollar was stuck near a five-month low of C$1.3318 per dollar plumbed on Tuesday, when it shed more than 1 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Oil prices managed to stabilise after Tuesday\\u2019s slump. But the market remained shaky, with the International Energy Agency (IEA) warning of unprecedented uncertainty in oil markets due to the economic environment and political risk. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. crude futures were up 1.45 percent at $54.21 per barrel after retreating roughly 6 percent to $52.77 on Tuesday, its lowest since late October 2017, caught in a broader Wall Street selloff fed by mounting concerns about a slowdown in global economic growth. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Brent crude bounced 1.3 percent to $63.35 per barrel after sliding more than 6 percent on Tuesday, when it plumbed a near one-year low of $61.71. The contracts had reached a four-year high above $86.00 at the start of October. (Reporting by Shinichi Saoshiro; Editing by Eric Meijer and Sam Holmes)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(58,'REUTERS','FOREX-Safe haven dollar firms on global slowdown fears, trade tensions','Vatsal Srivastava','November 21, 2018   4:10 AM','[{\"content\": \"* Dollar rebounds from 2-week lows \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Euro under pressure over Italian budget uncertainty \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Canadian dollar hits 4-month low as oil rout worsens \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Graphic: World FX rates in 2018 tmsnrt.rs/2egbfVh \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By Vatsal Srivastava \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"SINGAPORE, Nov 21 (Reuters) - The dollar traded firm against major peers on Wednesday, extending overnight gains as investors shunned riskier assets in favour of safe haven currencies on escalating worries about slowing global growth and the U.S.-Sino trade war. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"With sentiment souring and a global equities rout on Tuesday, risk averse traders sought shelter in the liquid dollar, which climbed from a two-week low hit earlier on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWhat\\u2019s driving currency markets right now are fears of a slowdown in economic growth with safe haven currencies like the dollar and yen likely to benefit,\\u201d said Michael McCarthy, chief markets strategist at CMC Markets. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The greenback had been under pressure for most of this week as cautious comments by Federal Reserve officials and surprisingly weak U.S. economic data suggested the central bank could slow the pace of monetary policy tightening. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar index, measuring performance against six major peers, was steady at 96.82 on Wednesday. The index gained 0.65 percent in the previous trading session. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cFor now, the dollar has retained its safe haven attributes outperforming across the board in the overnight session,\\u201d said Rodrigo Catril, senior currency strategist at NAB, in a note. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"With the Federal Reserve widely expected to raise interest rates by 25 basis points in December, analysts think the greenback could trade with a positive bias in the short term, despite lowering their longer-term rate hike expectations. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The yen traded at 112.91, with the greenback gaining 0.14 percent. The yen hit its highest level this month on Tuesday at 112.29 per dollar before losing steam as dollar bulls took charge. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Despite its safe haven status, the yen\\u2019s strength has been muted. Analysts suspect this is because Japanese investors have kept their money in U.S. and foreign markets, rather than bring it home. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro traded with a weak bias at $1.1372. The single currency lost 0.7 percent of its value on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Wider confidence retreated on Tuesday as Italian bank shares hit a two-year low and the spread between German and Italian bond yields widened. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Italy is at loggerheads with the European Commission and many fellow euro zone governments over its expansionary 2019 budget, which breaks EU\\u2019s fiscal rules. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe potential for the a further tussle between Rome and Brussels can have an impact on the overall Eurozone economic growth, which will keep the euro under pressure,\\u201d added Michael McCarthy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The British pound was little changed at $1.2786, having lost 0.5 percent versus the greenback on Tuesday. The pound is seen likely to trade sideways until the market gets more clarity on progress in the Brexit deal. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Canadian dollar dropped to a four-month low versus the dollar to trade at 1.3305 as the price of crude fell to its lowest level in more than a year ahead of next month\\u2019s OPEC meeting. Canada is one of the world\\u2019s top oil exporters. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Elsewhere, the Australian dollar, often considered a barometer of risk appetite, staged a slight recovery along with U.S. equity futures, gaining 0.2 percent to trade at $0.7230. The Aussie dollar lost more than 1 percent on Tuesday as global risk sentiment worsened. (Reporting by Vatsal Srivastava; Editing by Simon Cameron-Moore)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(60,'REUTERS','GLOBAL MARKETS-Asia stocks fall, oil stymied as growth worries grip global markets','Shinichi Saoshiro','November 21, 2018   2:59 AM','[{\"content\": \"* MSCI Asia-Pacific index down 0.6 pct, Nikkei loses 0.7 pct \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Safe haven bids amid broader risk aversion push up dollar \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Oil bounces modestly after big slide, but market still shaky \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"* Graphic: World FX rates in 2018 tmsnrt.rs/2egbfVh \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By Shinichi Saoshiro \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"TOKYO, Nov 21 (Reuters) - Asian stocks slid on Wednesday as intensifying concerns about global economic growth gripped financial markets, sending Wall Street shares and crude oil prices tumbling and driving the safe haven dollar up from a two-week low. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"MSCI\\u2019s broadest index of Asia-Pacific shares outside Japan fell 0.6 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Shanghai Composite Index swerved in and out of the red and was last down 0.2 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Australian stocks lost 0.6 percent, South Korea\\u2019s KOSPI retreated 0.85 percent and Japan\\u2019s Nikkei fell 0.7 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. stocks sold off for a second day on Tuesday as energy shares dropped with oil prices, while retailers including Target and Kohl\\u2019s sank after weak earnings and forecasts, fuelling worries about economic growth. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Nasdaq closed at its lowest in more than seven months on Tuesday while the S&P 500 and Dow ended at their weakest since late October. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt is difficult to pinpoint a single factor driving the global risk aversion. Apple and trade tensions seem to be touted as factors every other day, but it is difficult to blame them for all the woes,\\u201d said Soichiro Monji, senior economist at Daiwa SB Investments. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe markets appear to be starting to prepare for a loss of momentum in the global economy, although it is doing quite well at the moment.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The recent downturn in global equities has been led in part by a decline in U.S. technology shares, a group which had helped propel Wall Street\\u2019s long bull market. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe are anticipating more weakness in China, and a sharp slowdown in the United States next year. Given the highly-cyclical nature of the information technology (IT) sector, we have been arguing for a while that growth in its earnings would be hit especially hard in these circumstances,\\u201d wrote economists at Capital Economics. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar index against a basket of six major currencies was little changed at 96.838 after rallying 0.7 percent overnight, when it pulled away from a two-week trough of 96.042. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Earlier in the week, cautious comments by Federal Reserve officials about the global economic outlook knocked the dollar to two-week troughs as they suggested the central bank could slow the pace of or even end its monetary policy tightening cycle. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The euro was effectively flat at $1.1369 after sinking 0.75 percent the previous day. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The dollar rose 0.25 percent to 112.92 yen. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Australian dollar, sensitive to shifts in risk sentiment, crawled up 0.2 percent to $0.7229 following a 1 percent slide the previous day. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Commodity currencies such as the Canadian dollar struggled in the wake of tumbling crude prices. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Canadian dollar was stuck near a five-month low of C$1.3318 per dollar plumbed on Tuesday, when it shed more than 1 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Oil prices managed to stabilise after Tuesday\\u2019s slump. But the market remained shaky, with the International Energy Agency (IEA) warning of unprecedented uncertainty in oil markets due to the economic environment and political risk. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. crude futures were up 1.2 percent at $54.08 per barrel after retreating roughly 6 percent to $52.77 on Tuesday, its lowest since late October 2017, caught in a broader Wall Street selloff fed by mounting concerns about a slowdown in global economic growth. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Brent crude bounced 1.2 percent to $63.28 per barrel after sliding more than 6 percent on Tuesday, when it plumbed a near one-year low of $61.71. The contracts had reached a four-year high above $86.00 at the start of October. (Reporting by Shinichi Saoshiro; Editing by Eric Meijer and Sam Holmes)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(62,'REUTERS','European CLO market hits post-crisis high','Kristen Haunss','November 21, 2018   5:11 PM','[{\"content\": \"NEW YORK, Nov 21 (LPC) - Issuance of European Collateralized Loan Obligation (CLO) funds has hit a post-crisis high and is on track to set a new annual record as more new managers enter the market. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"More than \\u20ac26bn (US$29.6bn) of European CLOs have been printed in 2018 so far, beating the previous post-crisis record of \\u20ac19.2bn set in 2017, according to LPC Collateral data. An all-time record annual tally of \\u20ac32.9bn was arranged in 2006 at the peak of the market prior to the financial crisis of 2008. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Wells Fargo increased its 2018 new-issue forecast for European CLOs to \\u20ac30bn from \\u20ac25bn in October. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThis is going to be a near-record breaking year, if not a record-breaking year,\\u201d said Jeremy Ghose, head of Investcorp Credit Management in London. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe market is growing, the leveraged loan market is growing. I\\u2019m encouraged by the fact that global investors are looking much more positively and taking a longer term view in Europe than they have done before,\\u201d he added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Europe has \\u20ac93.1bn of CLO funds outstanding, which is set to rise as more credit managers raise new CLOs. The funds buy leveraged loans that companies including Danish telecom company TDC Group and global tea and coffee company Jacobs Douwe Egberts depend on to fund operations and back acquisitions. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"CLOs have been buoyed by increasing global investor demand for senior debt and floating-rate loans, which offer some protection against rising interest rates. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"More new managers have entered the European CLO market and are trying to grow their platforms, which has boosted issuance this year, according to Rishad Ahluwalia, JP Morgan\\u2019s London-based head of CLO research. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Anchorage Capital is among firms that issued their first European CLO this year, according to LPC Collateral data. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Monthly volume has picked up in the last two months with \\u20ac2.4bn of European CLOs arranged in October, up from \\u20ac1.6bn in September and \\u20ac1.3bn in August, according to LPC Collateral data. Monthly issuance in 2018 peaked in July when \\u20ac4.2bn of deals were arranged. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"More than \\u20ac3.2bn of European CLOs have been arranged in November so far, just behind the larger US market, which has seen US$3.7bn of the funds priced in the same time, according to the data. More than US$120bn of US CLOs have been arranged this year as of November 16. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt\\u2019s a year-end rush to get deals done,\\u201d Ahluwalia said. \\u201cYou\\u2019ve seen some slowdown in collateral \\u2013 there\\u2019s been less loan origination \\u2013 and arbitrage has gotten a little weaker, which makes dealflow a little harder to do. Managers are trying to get deals done in case widen out more year end.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Spreads on the most senior tranche of European CLOs range from 96bp-103bp. Average spreads of 98.6bp increased 5bp in October from September, according to LPC Collateral data. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"While European CLO issuance is increasing, European loan volume is falling, which is leaving less for new funds to buy and fewer assets for arranging banks to put in warehouses. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In the third quarter, \\u20ac29.4bn of Western European leveraged loans were issued, roughly half of the \\u20ac60.8bn arranged in the second quarter, according to LPC data. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Bank of England\\u2019s Financial Policy Committee warned about the global leveraged loan market in October, saying lending standards were falling and drew a comparison with the US sub-prime mortgage market that triggered the financial crisis. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"While more regulatory changes for structured credit are expected in the New Year, the European CLO market has settled into risk-retention rules, which require managers to keep skin-in-the-game in an attempt to better align investor and manager interests. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThere are no legal roadblocks \\u2013 people are comfortable with structures and have figured how to do deals in this regulatory environment,\\u201d said James Warbey, head of the alternative investments group in London at law firm Milbank, Tweed, Hadley & McCloy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cPeople \\u2026 want to squeeze in deals before year-end because we know there are legislative changes coming in the New Year,\\u201d he said. \\u201cThere is a new legislative environment and that will inevitably mean that there is a certain hesitancy. It will be more time consuming to get deals done in the first few weeks of the New Year as people [get used] to the new environment.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Despite spread widening and potential regulatory changes, deals are continuing to price and market participants are optimistic about 2019. JP Morgan on Tuesday said it expects \\u20ac30bn of new European CLO issuance next year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cI feel really comfortable about the European CLO landscape getting stronger and stronger, and deeper in terms of liquidity and in terms of the number of overall participants,\\u201d Ghose said. (Reporting by Kristen Haunss Editing by Tessa Walsh)\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(63,'REUTERS','Federal Reserve proposes new 9 percent capital leverage ratio for small banks','Anonymous','November 21, 2018   5:17 PM','[{\"content\": \"WASHINGTON (Reuters) - U.S. banking regulators said on Wednesday that they will seek public comment on a proposed rule that introduce a small-bank capital leverage ratio of 9 percent. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Federal Reserve said that the new leverage ratio, which would apply to banks with $10 billion in assets, aims to simplify capital requirements for small banks. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The proposal, which was issued in conjunction with the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, is required by a law passed by Congress in May to ease banking regulations.  \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Reporting by Katanga Johnson\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(172,'MarketWatch','Will this buy, cry, die chart pattern signal a stock-market bottom?','William Watts','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:17 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/21/Photos/ZH/MW-GY922_comp_1_20181121121242_ZH.png?uuid=a84c7152-edb0-11e8-867a-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Have stock-market bulls thrown in the towel, capitulating to the tech-led selloff that this week saw the S&P 500 and Dow Jones Industrial Average erase their 2018 gains while pushing the Nasdaq Composite deeper into correction territory? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"That\\u2019s an important question because identifying the bottom of a market washout is a contrarian process. And Tuesday\\u2019s damage, and the growing alarm around the selloff in the media, has some investors ready to argue that the worst of the carnage may be done.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Opinion: Here\\u2019s how to tell if stocks will enter a bear market or rise to new highs \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In a Wednesday note, Andrew Adams, analyst at Raymond James, pointed to a string of alarming headlines across financial news sites (including a couple from MarketWatch), and a host of other observations that he said offer \\u201cpromising signs that have prevented us from losing all hope.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"These include the fact that most major indexes, including the S&P 500 SPX, +0.94% and the Dow DJIA, +0.80% have yet to take out their late October intraday lows, former tech leaders bouncing off their recent nadir Tuesday, the Nasdaq Composite\\u2019s COMP, +1.51% \\u00a0bounce Tuesday off a long-term support trendline that stretches back to 2009, and a similar move by Apple Inc. AAPL, +0.64% \\u00a0shares. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Stock-market investors are sending the Fed\\u2019s Jerome Powell a crystal-clear message \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Of particular note to Adams, however, is a chart pattern dubbed \\u201cbuy, cry, die\\u201d by author Jesse Stine in his book, \\u201cInsider Buy Superstocks.\\u201d Adams quotes Stine\\u2019s description:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A favorable risk/reward setup can occur when a stock in a multi-month uptrend declines and makes three lower lows within a short period of time (usually within 4 to 5 weeks). My rule of thumb is to look for a stock (or the market) to make three lower lows with the third low ideally even slightly below the trend of the first two. This is my \\u201cBCD (Buy, Cry, Die) setup\\u201d From a sentiment standpoint, \\u201cbottom picking\\u201d investors trying to time the stock\\u2019s bottom BUY the first spike lower. At the second lower spike, these new investors CRY in anguish. At the third and final lower spike, they DIE and sell their shares in exasperation. The third spike lower is precisely where you want to be waiting with open arms. I\\u2019ve seen hundreds of stocks rocket out of such triple oversold conditions. Things in life tend to come in threes. Stock patterns are no different.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Pointing to the chart below (as it appears in the research note), Adams said it appears that a \\u2018BCD\\u2019 pattern has emerged in the Nasdaq, accompanied by a \\u201csense of exasperation and resignation present across pundits and the media alike.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe index has now made three consecutive lows in a little over a month and has done so with less downside momentum on each low based on the relative strength index (RSI in lower panel),\\u201d Adams said. \\u201cThis trading action all seems to support a bottom, and if the tech-heavy Nasdaq marks a major low that should be a bottom for the broad market.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"He acknowledged that stocks do need to rally \\u201cvery soon\\u201d to prevent further chart technical damage that would be much more difficult to recover from.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Indeed, Chris Kimble of Kimble Charting Solutions, in a blog post, highlights the downside danger in the chart below:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The monthly chart, going back 38 years, shows the Nasdaq has spent most of the past 25 years inside a rising channel.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cEven though many feel tech has been a wreck of late, its done nothing more than decline to test rising support,\\u201d he said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"According to Kimble\\u2019s analysis, if the Nasdaq and its relative momentum index both break nine-year support, stock-market bulls could have a lot more crying to do.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" William Watts is MarketWatch\'s deputy markets editor, based in New York. Follow him on Twitter @wlwatts. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(173,'MarketWatch','Stock-market investors are sending Feds Jerome Powell a crystal-clear message','Mark DeCambre','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:21 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/02/23/Photos/ZH/MW-GE309_fed_po_20180223151250_ZH.jpg?uuid=ec54bc3e-18d5-11e8-b1c5-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"The Federal Reserve is bent on normalizing interest rates from crisis-era levels. Who can blame policy makers for wanting to reassert policy order in an economy that no longer appears to require easy-money programs and is enjoying its lowest unemployment rate since 1969? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"However, Wall Street investors appear to be signaling that it can\\u2019t withstand an unabated pace of rate increases from Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe market is saying that the pace is a little too fast,\\u201d said Jeremy Siegel, professor of finance at University of Pennsylvania\\u2019s Wharton School of Business, and the man who forecast the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.78% would soon see 20,000 at the end of 2015.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"During an episode of CNBC\\u2019s Closing Bell segment, Siegel Tuesday afternoon said \\u201cthe market is clearly worried about over-tightening of the Fed.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Indeed, the Dow has shed about 950 points over the past two sessions, the S&P 500\\u2019s SPX, +0.93% \\u00a0 skid on Tuesday marked its worst start to a Thanksgiving week of trade since 1982 and the Nasdaq Composite Index COMP, +1.49% \\u00a0 is down 14.8% from its Aug. 29 closing record.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Fed is widely expected to lift interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point at the conclusion of its two-day, rate-setting meeting on Dec. 19. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"However, a number of other prominent market participants have warned that the Fed\\u2019s agenda is hurting asset values: \\u201cWe\\u2019re in a situation right now that the Fed will have to look at asset prices before they look at economic activity,\\u201d Ray Dalio, founder of Bridgewater Associates, the world\\u2019s largest hedge fund, told CNBC last week in an interview. \\u201cIt\\u2019s a difficult position.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"MarketWatch columnist Nigam Arora wrote in a recent article that the big question going forward for markets is: \\u201cDoes the Fed relent or stay on its present course? If the Fed stays on its present course, expect P/Es to shrink.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In other words, prices are likely to retreat as Fed tightening pushes borrowing costs higher for corporations. weighing on equity valuations. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Other market experts are predicting that evidence of sluggish growth abroad\\u2014for example, Germany economic growth skidded in the third quarter, producing its lowest rate of expansion since 2013\\u2014will force the Fed to pause its plans to lift rates aggressively in 2019. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Ikea to slash 7,500 jobs in restructuring\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"David Bianco, the chief investment officer for the Americas at DWS, said that the \\u201cFed should slow pace of hikes, given contained inflation & slower growth ahead,\\u201d in a Nov. 20 note. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Still, The Wall Street Journal\\u2019s Nick Timiraos and Gregory Zuckerman on Tuesday wrote that policy makers aren\\u2019t likely to comply with the market\\u2019s demand. \\u201cSpeaking in Dallas last week, Fed Chairman Jerome Powell acknowledged the recent market selloff could reduce growth by tightening financial conditions, but he did not suggest it had been enough for the Fed to change its policy plans,\\u201d they wrote.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Trump wants Fed to cut interest rates after stock-market wipeout, but history is not on his side \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"To be sure there are a litany of factors that have contributed to stocks getting knocked around in October and November, but many also have pointed to Powell\\u2019s early October remark that the Fed was a \\u201clong way\\u201d from a neutral rate as at least part of the cause for the current slide. The neutral rate is the theoretical rate at which the economy is neither boosted nor impeded. It is the point at which investors think that the Fed may cool its rate-hike pace. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"MarketWatch\\u2019s Steve Goldstein writes that Powell may be signaling a more dovish, or accommodative, stance around neutral, with the Fed seeing the so-called neutral rate at around 3%, with the current federal-funds rate at a range between 2% and 2.25%. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile, the benchmark 10-year Treasury rate TMUBMUSD10Y, +0.30% \\u00a0has been hanging below 3.10%, perhaps signaling that bond investors aren\\u2019t expecting a heightened pace of rate increases, even if a flight to safety has provided a floor for Treasurys. Bond prices fall as yields rise. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Perhaps the most vocal and influential critic of rate increases has been President Donald Trump, who has blamed Powell & Co., for undermining a business-friendly agenda that had led to repeated records for equity benchmarks. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Powell will get a chance to communicate where he stands on Nov. 28 when he speaks at the Economic Club of New York at 11:30 a.m. Eastern Time, and again he appears on Capitol Hill on Dec. 5, before the Federal Open Market Committee\\u2019s final convention of 2018. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some Fed watchers have warned that Trump\\u2019s aggressive criticism could backfire, making policy makers reluctant to ease up out of fear it would appear they were cowing to criticism, undercutting their independence. But investors may not be satisfied until a course of a slackened pace is set.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Providing critical information for the U.S. trading day. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Need to Know newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Mark DeCambre is MarketWatch\'s markets editor. He is based in New York. Follow him on Twitter @mdecambre. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(174,'MarketWatch','Johnson & Johnson\'s stock drops to pace Dow decliners after appeals court ruling on Zytiga disappoints','Tomi Kilgore','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:19 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"Shares of Johnson & Johnson JNJ, -3.24% fell 3.3% in afternoon trade, enough to pace declines among its health care peers and among the Dow Jones Industrial Average\'s DJIA, +0.79% components, after reports that an appeals court ruled that J&J can\'t block sales of generic Zytiga while the company appeals the overturning of a Zytiga patent. In J&J\'s third-quarter ended Sept. 30, Zytiga sales rose 43.2% from a year ago to $958 million, making it the company\'s third-highest selling drug. Jennifer Taubert, worldwide chairman of pharmaceuticals at J&J, said in the company\'s post-earnings conference call with analysts while the company was \\\"pleased\\\" with Zytiga, \\\"we\'re absolutely not dependent on it,\\\" according to a transcript provided by FactSet. The company said total pharmaceutical operational sales growth was 8.2%, but if Zytiga was removed, growth would have still been a \\\"really strong\\\" 6.6%. The stock has still gained 4.6% over the past three months, while the SPDR Health Care Select Sector ETF XLV, -0.18% has slipped 1.7% and the Dow has lost 4.6%.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Have breaking news sent to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Bulletin emails. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(175,'MarketWatch','Mortgage rates slide the fastest in four years, but it may be too late for the housing market','Andrea Riquier','Published: Nov 21, 2018 10:21 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/19/Photos/MG/MW-GY779_mortga_20181119143042_MG.jpg?uuid=9aac5c5e-ec31-11e8-9a90-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Rates for home loans tumbled as turmoil rocked global financial markets, but any reprieve in rates may come too late for would-be home buyers or refinancers. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The 30-year fixed-rate mortgage averaged 4.81% in the November 21 week, down 13 basis points, mortgage liquidity provider Freddie Mac said Wednesday. That\\u2019s the biggest weekly decline since January 2015 and the lowest level for the popular product since early October. The 15-year fixed-rate mortgage averaged 4.24%, down 12 basis points during the week. The 5-year Treasury-indexed hybrid adjustable-rate mortgage averaged 4.09%, down from 4.15%. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Those rates don\\u2019t include fees associated with obtaining mortgage loans.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Fixed-rate mortgages follow the U.S. 10-year Treasury note TMUBMUSD10Y, +0.24% \\u00a0, although with a slight delay. As a global stock sell-off has raged over the past week, bonds have been the best house in a bad neighborhood. The yield on the benchmark 10-year bond touched a six-week low Monday. Bond yields decline as prices rise, and vice versa. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: This government mortgage program helps veterans with spotty credit history \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile, this week has brought a raft of fresh information on the housing market, little of it cheery. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Sales of already-owned homes perked up in October, but are still lower than the year-ago selling pace by more than 5%. Home builders broke ground on more \\u2014 but not enough \\u2014 homes. And one fresh data point bears watching: mortgage applications for newly-constructed houses are plunging, according to the Mortgage Bankers Association. As the chart above shows, they\\u2019re now lower than year-ago levels by double digits.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It\\u2019s possible more new-home buyers are making their purchases with cash as interest rates rise. But it\\u2019s just as likely that the tumble in applications is an early warning sign on new-home sales in the coming months. If so, that would mean trouble for the housing market \\u2014 and the economy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Only about 1.86 million Americans now have an \\u201cinterest rate incentive\\u201d to refinance, data provider Black Knight said earlier in November. And refis made up the smallest share of all mortgage applications since December 2000 this past week, the Mortgage Bankers said. Housing market conditions may be easing enough for motivated buyers to catch a break, and there may be brief windows in which some homeowners can grab a refinance. But if Americans aren\\u2019t watching, or aren\\u2019t ready to pounce, those opportunities may slip by. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: We\\u2019re probably at peak housing. Here\\u2019s what that means. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Andrea Riquier reports on housing and banking from MarketWatch\'s New York newsroom. Follow her on Twitter @ARiquier. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(176,'MarketWatch','How bitcoins meltdown is ravaging hedge funds','Aaron Hankin','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:13 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/21/Photos/ZH/MW-GY914_closed_20181121111310_ZH.jpg?uuid=57488f00-eda8-11e8-b963-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"What a difference a year makes in the world of digital currencies. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Bitcoin was flying more than 1,000% higher in 2017, and with venture capital and institutional firms flush with cash, investors deployed funds to tap into what must have seemed like a bottomless pot of gold. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"However, 2018 has been anything but that. Bitcoin BTCUSD, +2.68% \\u00a0is in its fifth-largest drawdown since 2010, losing nearly 80% of its value from its December 2017 high, and that cash that was once plentiful, has dried up for some, while other so-called crypto hedge funds set to close their doors. Since Nov. 1, the price of a single bitcoin has lost 27% in value, compared with 67% from the beginning of the year and 77% since its December 2017 all-time high. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe are seeing some firms now close,\\u201d said Josh Gnaizda, CEO of Crypto Fund Research.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Gnaizda estimates that 35 crypto hedge funds have closed since the beginning on 2018, representing more than 5% of the 633 funds the company tracks. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Moreover, Gnaizda said that tally could have been worse because many investment ventures that raised capital at the peak, in late 2017 and early 2018, didn\\u2019t launch until prices had already begun falling, lessening the blow.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Bitcoin is imploding \\u2014 here\\u2019s where bitcoin bulls and bears see it headed from here \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The rush to allocate capital amidst the crypto-boom began in the second half of 2017, peaking with 44 fund launches in the month of January 2018 \\u2014 the highest month on record, according to data from Crypto Fund Research. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Furthermore, crypto-related funds accounted for 14% of the total number of hedge funds launched in 2017, making it the fastest-growing fund segment, Crypto Fund data show.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Oddly enough, Gnaizda said despite enduring a pounding earlier in the year, hedge funds continued to launch fresh crypto-investment initiatives. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAn interesting trend we noticed was when price were in decline in the first and second-quarter funds were still being launch,\\u201d he said. \\u201cHowever, it feels like this is a lag effect with the initial formation taking longer than many had anticipated.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"However, this lag may be about to catch up. The inability of funds to turn a profit this year means closures are far from over, according to one fund manager.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAs I\\u2019ve thought about this issue more, I keep coming back to a single question: Why haven\\u2019t more crypto fund managers realized this already and shut down?\\u201d wrote Anthony Pompliano, founder and partner at Morgan Creek Digital.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Pompliano said he expects watermark issues\\u2014a contractual clause around the amount a hedge-fund manager can charge\\u2014will heighten the pace of fund closures. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIf true, we could be less than 60 days away from many of the fund managers experiencing the pain of being ineligible for the bulk of their compensation,\\u201d he added. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Opinion: Victims of bitcoin insanity are quickly piling up \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Providing critical information for the U.S. trading day. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Need to Know newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Aaron Hankin is a MarketWatch reporter in New York who covers cryptocurrency and financial markets. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(177,'MarketWatch','Just 52% of Facebook employees are optimistic about the companys future  down from 84% a year ago','Deepa Seetharaman','Published: Nov 21, 2018 9:24 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/07/26/Photos/ZH/MW-GN249_Zucker_20180726152804_ZH.jpg?uuid=042c55ea-910a-11e8-8e66-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Facebook Inc.\\u2019s difficult year is taking a toll on employee morale, with several key measures of internal sentiment taking a sharp turn for the worse over the past year, according to people familiar with the matter and messages reviewed by the Wall Street Journal.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Amid a plunge in the stock price FB, +2.61% , ongoing leadership turmoil and critical media coverage, just over half of employees said they were optimistic about Facebook\\u2019s future, down 32 percentage points from the year earlier, according to the survey, which was taken by nearly 29,000 employees. Fifty-three percent said Facebook was making the world better, down 19 percentage points from a year ago.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Chief Executive Mark Zuckerberg directly addressed the survey results at a question-and-answer session in early November, some of the people said, saying he and other senior officials were taking steps to address the underlying issues.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Zuckerberg says he has no plan to step down as Facebook chairman \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Howard Gold: There\\u2019s a darker message in the FAANG selloff \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The darkening mood within the social-media giant is notable in part because its workforce has been resilient through other difficult patches in the past. That includes the period after the 2016 presidential election, when many critics were blaming Facebook for allowing fabricated news articles to pervade the platform.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But many people inside Facebook say this period feels different, in part because of the unusual turbulence at the top of the company, which has struggled to respond to its various internal and external controversies. The declining stock price has also hurt morale among employees for whom stock options are a large part of their compensation, current and former employees say.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" An expanded version of this report appears at WSJ.com. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Trending at WSJ.com: \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Megyn Kelly looks set to leave NBC with all of her $69 million contract \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Blue wave wiped out Republicans in big Texas county \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(178,'MarketWatch','What time do the stores open on Thanksgiving and Black Friday?','Alessandra Malito','Published: Nov 21, 2018 11:24 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/21/Photos/ZH/MW-GY910_thanks_20181121110036_ZH.jpg?uuid=9581723e-eda6-11e8-81e1-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"One of the newest Thanksgiving traditions: shopping. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Americans are ready to score good deals and spend big money this holiday weekend. Three-quarters of U.S. consumers plan to shop between Thanksgiving and Cyber Monday, according to a Deloitte survey of 1,200 consumers, and 79% of respondents say they plan to shop on Black Friday. They intend to spend an average of $427 this weekend, up from $400 last year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" See: 7 awesome things you can get for free this Thanksgiving and Black Friday \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"There are plenty of options for the people who want to be a part of the craze of late-night shopping. Some stores must stay closed, per state laws, including those in Maine, Massachusetts and Rhode Island. But others are opening even before the turkey would traditionally get to the dinner table. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some store hours may vary depending on location. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Here\\u2019s what time some of the nation\\u2019s major retail chinas open on Thanksgiving and Black Friday:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Bed Bath and Beyond BBBY, +4.36% : Closed on Thanksgiving. Opens 6 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Best Buy BBY, -3.89% : Opens 5 p.m. on Thanksgiving, closes at 1 a.m. and reopens at 8 a.m. on Black Friday. For stores in Maine, Massachusetts and Rhode Island, stores are closed on Thanksgiving and open at 12:01 a.m. in Maine and 1 a.m. in Massachusetts and Rhode Island. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Big Lots BIG, +1.64% : Opens 7 a.m. to midnight on Thanksgiving, and 6 a.m. on Black Friday.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" BJ\\u2019s BJ, +9.83% : Closed Thanksgiving. Opens 7 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Burlington Coat Factory BURL, +0.04% : Closed Thanksgiving. Opens 7 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Costco COST, -0.52% \\u00a0Closed Thanksgiving. Opens 9 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dick\\u2019s Sporting Goods DKS, +2.30% : Opens 6 p.m. to 2 a.m. on Thanksgiving. Reopens at 5 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dollar General DG, +0.60% : Opens 7 a.m. to 10 p.m. on Thanksgiving. Normal operating hours vary by location on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Five Below FIVE, +0.87% : Opens 6 p.m. on Thanksgiving. Opens 8 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" GameStop GME, +11.81% : Opens 3 p.m. until 10 p.m. on Thanksgiving. Opens 7 a.m. on Black Friday.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Home Depot HD, +0.90% : Closed on Thanksgiving. Opens 6 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" JCPenney JCP, +1.16% : Opens 2 p.m. on Thanksgiving and closes at 10 p.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Kmart: Opens 6 a.m. until midnight on Thanksgiving. Reopens at 6 a.m. on Black Friday.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Black Friday: The deeper reason why some of us love it and others positively loathe it \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Kohl\\u2019s KSS, +3.13% ): Opens at 5 p.m. on Thanksgiving, remaining open throughout the night and ending Black Friday deals at 1 p.m. on Black Friday.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Macy\\u2019s M, +1.92% : Opens 5 p.m. until 2 a.m. on Thanksgiving. Reopens at 6 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Michael\\u2019s: Opens 6 p.m. until midnight on Thanksgiving, and 7 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Old Navy GPS, +4.91% : Some stores open at 3 p.m. on Thanksgiving until 10 p.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Petsmart: Closed on Thanksgiving. Opens at 7 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Sam\\u2019s Club: Closed on Thanksgiving. Opens at 7 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Sears SHLDQ, +2.74% : Opens 6 p.m. to midnight on Thanksgiving. Reopens at 5 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Target TGT, +0.49% Opens 5 p.m. until 1 a.m. on Thanksgiving. Reopens at 7 a.m. on Black Friday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Ulta Beauty: Opens 6 p.m. to 2 a.m. on Thanksgiving. Reopens at 6 a.m. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Walmart WMT, -0.09% \\u00a0: Regular operating hours. In-store Black Friday sales beginning at 6 p.m.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Alessandra Malito is a personal finance reporter based in New York. You can follow her on Twitter @malito_ali. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(179,'MarketWatch','L Brands bringing back Victorias Secrets swim business in 2019','Tonya Garcia','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:41 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2017/11/15/Photos/ZH/MW-FY441_victor_20171115180355_ZH.jpg?uuid=410fdb6c-ca59-11e7-9578-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"L Brands Chief Financial Officer Stuart Burgdoerfer said on the company\\u2019s third-quarter earnings call that Victoria\\u2019s Secret swim business is being revived, less than three years after the company said it would exit that \\u201cnon-core\\u201d category.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"When asked what made the company decide to change course, Burgdoerfer declined to go into detail.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe\\u2019ll be back in the swim business in the spring of 2019,\\u201d he said on the call, according to a FactSet transcript. \\u201cNot going to spend a lot of time looking back, frankly. As to why we made the decision that we did, fundamentally, it\\u2019s about what the customer is telling us.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Victoria\\u2019s Secret sells women\\u2019s underwear but has been marketing to men \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Wells Fargo analysts anticipated the category\\u2019s return last week, saying that it drives seasonal sales. Analysts led by Ike Boruchow reiterated that argument in a Tuesday note. Bringing back the business, which, they say, was $525 million when it was discontinued, is \\u201ca move aimed at recapturing their seasonal shopper and bringing incremental traffic back to the store.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In addition to the revival of the swim category, L Brands LB, +6.45% \\u00a0 announced that John Mehas has been named chief executive of the Victoria\\u2019s Secret brand, just days after news broke that Jan Singer resigned from the post.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Mehas was most recently the president of Tory Burch, and was chief executive of the Ralph Lauren Corp. RL, +3.24% \\u00a0 brand Club Monaco for 13 years.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"L Brands also slashed its dividend to $1.20 from $2.40, beginning in March 2019. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"L Brands shares closed down 17.7% on Tuesday.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" See: Target shares take a beating after investments take a toll on margins \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Prior to the earnings, L Brands announced that it would shutter the Henri Bendel brand and is exploring the alternatives for the La Senza brand.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201c[W]e view all of these details from the release as favorable,\\u201d Wells Fargo wrote. \\u201cSimply put, our thesis calling for long-term, structural changes is already taking place and it sets the stock up for meaningful potential re-rating when investors begin to believe that a turnaround play is in the works.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Wells Fargo rates L Brands shares outperform with a $55 price target.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"MKM Partners say it\\u2019s \\u201cunclear\\u201d whether all of the changes are a positive, but they say it \\u201cmay be more likely than not\\u201d that there will be even more of it coming.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIn looking under every rock, there is also risk of too much change and incremental disruption to the business,\\u201d wrote Roxanne Meyer in a note. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"L Brands also raised the possibility of bringing back shoes, which MKM isn\\u2019t so enthusiastic about.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAs expected, swim looks to be making a come back, which should be a positive,\\u201d Meyer wrote. \\u201cThe addition of footwear is another story, unless we are talking flip flops.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"MKM rates L Brands shares neutral.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Victoria\\u2019s Secret and Gap among the retail brands that have reached peak revenue \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"L Brands shares have slumped 50.8% in 2018 while the S&P 500 index SPX, +0.92% \\u00a0 has fallen 0.3% for the period.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Want news about Asia delivered to your inbox? Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Asia Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Tonya Garcia is a MarketWatch reporter covering retail and consumer-oriented companies. You can follow her on Twitter @tgarcianyc. She is based in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(180,'MarketWatch','Apples stock tumble makes it unanimous  the FAANG bull market has ended','Tomi Kilgore','Published: Nov 21, 2018 6:56 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY862_Apple__20181120152002_ZH.jpg?uuid=a922f344-ed01-11e8-8061-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"For the first time, all five FAANG stocks are in bear markets.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Apple Inc.\\u2019s stock AAPL, +0.63% made it unanimous Tuesday, as it tumbled 4.8% to the lowest close since May 3, helped there by a price target cut at Goldman Sachs. The stock closed 23.7% below its Oct. 3 record close of $232.07.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Many on Wall Street define a bear market as a decline of 20% or more from a bull-market peak. On Monday, Apple\\u2019s stock dipped briefly into bear market territory, but pared losses to close 19.9% below its record. Read more about how Apple flirted with a bear market.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Apple\\u2018s last bear market started on Aug. 21, 2015, and didn\\u2019t end until Aug. 9, 2016. The stock fell as much as 32% during that downturn.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Goldman analyst Rod Hall cut his stock price target to $182 from $209, citing concerns over \\u201cdeteriorating demand,\\u201d following the technology giant\\u2019s disappointing holiday season guidance and revenue guidance cuts from multiple smartphone suppliers.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Opinion: When the going gets tough, Apple hides its numbers.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Apple bulls were the last among the FAANG technology darlings to capitulate. Google parent Alphabet Inc.\\u2019s stock GOOGL, +1.89% entered a bull market on Monday, when it closed 20.1% below its July 26 record of $1,285.50. The stock inched up 0.3% on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Alphabet\\u2019s last bear market ended on Oct. 14, 2011, or a little less than three months after it started. During that selloff, the stock lost 21.1% at its bear-market bottom.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also read: Google parent Alphabet\\u2019s stock becomes 2nd FANG to produce \\u2018death cross\\u2019 and Netflix is next.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Amazon.com Inc. shares AMZN, +2.18% had entered a bear market on Oct. 29. With the stock shedding 1.1% Tuesday, it ended the day 26.7% below its Sept. 4 record of $2,039.51. Amazon\\u2019s previous bear market, in which the stock tumbled as much as 30.5%, ended on March 1, 2016, just four weeks after it started.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares of Netflix Inc. FB, +2.55% FB, +2.55% FB, +2.55% have been in a bear market since Oct. 24, which was just about three weeks after the previous one ended. Facebook Inc. FB, +2.55% been in a bear market the longest, since July 30, or only about three months after the preceding bull market started.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" See also: Netflix\\u2019s \\u2018death cross\\u2019 is the third for FAANG stocks and Nasdaq Composite is next.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Facebook\\u2019s stock went public on May 18, 2012, meaning investors have never suffered a bear market at the same time as Alphabet investors.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"What might a unanimous FAANG bear market mean for investors?\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Janney Montgomery Scott technical analyst Dan Wantrobski said the loss of leadership from the technology sector in general, and more specifically the FAANG stocks, which had been a \\u201csignificant driver of the markets\\u201d for the past few years, is one of the reasons the broader U.S. stock market continues to struggle. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cOur analysis continues to suggest that this segment may continue to underperform the broader markets for some time longer,\\u201d Wantrobski wrote in a note to clients.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile, the Nasdaq Composite Index COMP, +1.49% of which all the FAANG stocks are components, has declined 14.8% from its Aug. 29 record close of 8,109.69; the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.79% has lost 8.8% since closing at a record 26,828.39 on Oct. 3 and the S&P 500 index SPX, +0.93% is 9.9% below its Sept. 20 record of 2,930.75.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get the top tech stories of the day delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Tech Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Tomi Kilgore is MarketWatch\'s deputy investing and corporate news editor and is based in New York. You can follow him on Twitter @TomiKilgore. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(181,'MarketWatch','Why falling oil prices are now a net drag on the U.S. economy','William Watts','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:30 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY852_shale__20181120130907_ZH.jpg?uuid=5f8284c8-ecef-11e8-bb52-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"President Donald Trump on Wednesday touted falling oil prices as a \\u201ctax cut for America and the world,\\u201d but economists say the shale revolution, which has turned the U.S. back into a major oil producer, means that declining crude prices are now a small headwind for the economy.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe key point to remember here is that the lower oil prices are now a net drag on the U.S. economy, because the [capital-expenditure] cutbacks triggered in the shale oil business outweigh the gains to consumers\\u2019 spending from cheaper gas prices,\\u201d said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics, in a Monday note.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The drag isn\\u2019t large, but the phenomenon is a \\u201chuge break from the past,\\u201d Shepherdson noted, and it\\u2019s become visible only recently.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: How plummeting oil prices will affect drivers over Thanksgiving \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shale output has risen sharply over the past decade, pushing U.S. oil production to a record above 10 million barrels a day in 2018.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Oil on Tuesday extended a rout that\\u2019s already pushed futures on the U.S. benchmark, West Texas Intermediate crude CLF9, +3.13% , and the global benchmark, Brent crude LCOF9, +2.45% , into bear markets this month. January WTI futures and Brent both dropped nearly 7% in Tuesday\\u2019s session. WTI is down 30% from its bull-market peak on Oct. 3, ending Thursday at a more-than-one-year low. Oil bounced higher on Wednesday, while stocks also attempted to recover from an extended rout that took the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.80% and the S&P 500 SPX, +0.94% into negative territory for the year.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Oil\\u2019s plunge doesn\\u2019t spell doom for the U.S. economy, which was already expected to slow as the boost from tax cuts faded, Shepherdson said, but the slide \\u201cwill make a difference, at the margin.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Archive: Here\\u2019s why oil rout is hurting the global economy instead of helping \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"He pointed to the oil selloff that began in mid-2014, taking crude from around $107 a barrel to a low near $26 in early 2016 \\u2014 a move that was accompanied by a sharp slowdown in U.S. gross-domestic-product growth and an outright contraction in manufacturing activity, triggered by a 60% peak-to-trough collapse in mining capital expenditures.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"That\\u2019s unlikely to be repeated this time around, Shepherdson said, but he warned that investors should expect to see a clear drop in mining capital expenditures, or capex, which include oil, in the first quarter \\u2014 a move likely to be signaled by a decline in the Baker-Hughes oil-rig count \\u2014 before the end of this year. The rig count is viewed as a real-time proxy for capital spending (see chart below).\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shepherdson noted that nonmining capex also slowed sharply as oil prices plunged in 2014 to 2016, a phenomenon he said was likely due to the hit other sectors, including parts and equipment makers, transportation and logistics firms and even real estate and finance in parts of the country heavily dependent on oil output, took as mining capex collapsed.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"That\\u2019s also unlikely to be repeated this time around, he said, because the non-oil economy is in much better shape, with very strong cash flows. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Still, Shepherdson intends to keep a close eye on the capex intentions index in the National Federation of Independent Business\\u2019s monthly survey. It isn\\u2019t a perfectly reliable gauge, he said, but is the single best leading indicator of the rate of growth of nonoil capex, usually signaling turning points a couple quarters in advance. That means a significant decline in the index \\u201cwould be an unambiguous reason to worry about a slowdown in growth next spring.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile, of course, many consumers will directly feel the benefit of lower gasoline prices, which are coming at \\u201cexactly the right time\\u201d for retailers ahead of the start of the holiday shopping season, Shepherdson said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Chain-store sales have been strong in recent months as a result of tax cuts and a delayed response to last year\\u2019s dollar weakness, which raised the cost of imported goods, he said. Now both effects are reversing, putting holiday sales at risk.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But even there the upside is limited, Shepherdson said, warning that while lower gas prices will \\u201cflatter\\u201d sales numbers over the holiday season, consumer cash flow isn\\u2019t strong enough to maintain the near-4% real growth in spending over the second and third quarters.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Providing critical information for the U.S. trading day. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Need to Know newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" William Watts is MarketWatch\'s deputy markets editor, based in New York. Follow him on Twitter @wlwatts. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(182,'MarketWatch','Weekend Sip: A $175 big and bold wine for your Thanksgiving table','Charles Passy','Published: Nov 21, 2018 9:41 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/16/Photos/ZH/MW-GY692_mondav_20181116110030_ZH.jpg?uuid=bde5ba38-e9b8-11e8-b401-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" The bottle: Robert Mondavi Winery Cabernet Sauvignon Reserve To Kalon Vineyard 2015, $175\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" The back story: If you\\u2019re looking for an American wine to pair with the most American of meals \\u2014 the Thanksgiving feast \\u2014 you can hardly go wrong with an offering from Robert Mondavi. This is the California brand, created and led by its namesake vintner (1913-2008), that helped establish American wine as worthy of competing with its European counterpart.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But as with many brands, Mondavi, now owned by Constellation Brands, a wine and spirits conglomerate, makes a distinction between its everyday wines and those that are truly special \\u2014 or \\u201creserve.\\u201d In Mondavi\\u2019s case, that often means wines sourced from its To Kalon vineyard (the name comes from the Greek, meaning \\u201cthe beautiful\\u201d). This piece of Napa Valley land is special, say Mondavi officials, because of the optimum sun exposure and rain it receives and its well-drained soil. Mondavi himself called it a vineyard with \\u201ca magical nature.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"So, in select years, the winery makes a Cabernet Sauvignon, the ever-popular red varietal, sourced from To Kalon. The 2015 is the latest example, having been released in the last few weeks. It\\u2019s a bottle with a limited supply \\u2014 just 7,995 cases have been produced.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What we think about it: This is a Cab for those who like their wines big and bold. The Mondavi team rightly describes it as a sip of \\u201cdark-fruited, dried herb complexity.\\u201d But there\\u2019s finesse there as well and just a hint of nuttiness and sweetness. In all, quite a statement.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" How to enjoy it: This could indeed be a great splurge wine for Thanksgiving. And while it might seemingly not be the ideal pairing for the bland turkey, it will work well with the rich side dishes that are the meal\\u2019s true culinary statement. Gobble, gobble, everyone.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Charles Passy is a Wall Street Journal reporter and frequent MarketWatch contributor based in New York. Follow him on Twitter @CharlesPassy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(183,'MarketWatch','Everything coming to Netflix in December  and whats leaving','Sarah Toy','Published: Nov 21, 2018 12:53 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY855_mowgli_20181120135839_ZH.jpg?uuid=4acd68c0-ecf6-11e8-87d9-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2018Tis the season, and no one knows that better than Netflix Inc. NFLX, -0.34% \\u00a0 The streaming giant has a slew of holiday-themed originals coming in December, like \\u201c5 Star Christmas,\\u201d \\u201cFree Rein: The Twelve Neighs of Christmas\\u201d and a stand-alone \\u201cChilling Adventures of Sabrina\\u201c episode dubbed \\u201cA Midwinter\\u2019s Tale.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For those who are looking to get away from the holiday lights and jingles, there\\u2019s the buzzed-about flick \\u201cDumplin\\u2019,\\u201d based on the young-adult novel of the same name. Starring Jennifer Aniston with music by Dolly Parton, it tells the story of Willowdeen (Danielle Macdonald), a plus-size teenager whose mom (Aniston) is a former beauty queen and local pageant celebrity. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Netflix\\u2019s \\u2018death cross\\u2019 is the third for FAANG stocks and Nasdaq Composite is next\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also: It\\u2019s time to stop lumping Netflix in with the other FAANG stocks, says analyst\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"There\\u2019s also \\u201cMowgli: Legend of the Jungle,\\u201d a remake of Rudyard Kipling\\u2019s \\u201cThe Jungle Book,\\u201d directed by Andy Serkis of \\u201cThe Lord of the Rings\\u201d and \\u201cPlanet of the Apes\\u201d fame. And for those who like arthouse films, there\\u2019s the critical favorite \\u201cRoma,\\u201d directed by Alfanso Cuar\\u00f3n. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In true Netflix form, there\\u2019s plenty of content on its way and there\\u2019s something for everyone. Here\\u2019s what\\u2019s coming to Netflix in December \\u2014 and what\\u2019s leaving.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dec. 1 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201c8 Mile\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAstro Boy\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cBattle\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cBride of Chucky\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cChristine\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cCloudy with a Chance of Meatballs\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cCrossroads: One Two Jaga\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cFriday\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cFriday After Next\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cHellboy\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cMan vs Wild with Sunny Leone,\\u201d Season 1\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cMeet Joe Black\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cMemories of the Alhambra\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cMy Bloody Valentine\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cNext Friday\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cReindeer Games\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cSeven Pounds\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cShaun of the Dead\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTerminator Salvation\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Big Lebowski\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Great British Baking Show: Masterclass,\\u201d Season 5 Masterclasses\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Last Dragon\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Man Who Knew Too Little\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dec. 2 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Lobster\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dec. 3 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cBlue Planet II,\\u201d Season 1\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cHero Mask\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Sound of Your Heart: Reboot,\\\" Season 2 (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dec. 4 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cDistrict 9\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dec. 6 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cHappy!\\u201d Season 1\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dec. 7 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201c5 Star Christmas\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cBad Blood\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cDogs of Berlin\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cDumplin\\u2019\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cFree Rein: The Twelve Neighs of Christmas\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cMowgli: Legend of the Jungle\\u201d (Netflix original) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cNailed It! Holiday!\\u201d (Netflix original)\", \"type\": \"text\"},