": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 4 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAir Bud: Seventh Inning Fetch\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAir Bud: Spikes Back\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAir Bud: World Pup\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAir Buddies\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cCars Toon: Mater\\u2019s Tall Tales\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cSpooky Buddies\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTarzan & Jane\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Brave Little Toaster Goes to Mars\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Brave Little Toaster to the Rescue\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Crimson Wing: Mystery of the Flamingos\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe Search for Santa Paws\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTinker Bell\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTinker Bell and the Great Fairy Rescue\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTinker Bell and the Lost Treasure\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 7 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTrolls\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 10 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cBattle Royale\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cBattle Royale 2\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTeeth\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 15 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cStep Up 2: The Streets\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 16 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 17 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cBeverly Hills Chihuahua 2\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 19 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIp Man: The Final Fight\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 20 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Disney\\u2019s \\u201cMoana\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cFood, Inc.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cI Give It a Year\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 22 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cSpotlight\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 25 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Disney\\u2019s \\u201cPirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leaving Dec. 31 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cTroy\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Sarah Toy reports on the media for MarketWatch. She is based in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(184,'MarketWatch','Food for thought this Thanksgiving: 40% of groceries are thrown out every year','Quentin Fottrell','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:08 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2017/11/22/Photos/ZH/MW-FY871_thanks_20171122094751_ZH.jpg?uuid=1db52a92-cf94-11e7-901f-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Some food for thought this Thanksgiving: There\\u2019s a massive hole in America\\u2019s food chain.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"As much as 40% of food goes uneaten in the U.S. Americans throw away $165 billion in wasted food every year, according to Harvard Law School\\u2019s Food Law and Policy Clinic and the Natural Resources Defense Council, or NRDC, a nonprofit environmental action group. Some 160 billion pounds of discarded food also clogs up landfills. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Why the tail chopped from your Thanksgiving turkey will travel 5,000 miles \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Worldwide, one-third of the world\\u2019s food \\u2014 some 1.3 billion tons \\u2014 is lost or wasted every year, according to the United Nations Environment Program. \\u201cFood waste is responsible for over 7% of the world\\u2019s greenhouse gas emissions, making it a key challenge in tackling climate change,\\u201d the UN says.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The existing \\u201cSell by\\u201d dates are actually for stores to know how much shelf life products have. They are not meant to indicate the food is bad. \\u201cBest before\\u201d and \\u201cuse by\\u201d dates are for consumers, but they are manufacturers\\u2019 estimates as to when food reaches its peak. Manufacturers mostly decide the shelf life for their own products. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In fact, Casey Williams, an editorial fellow at The Huffington Post, ate expired food for a week and didn\\u2019t die, or even get sick. \\u201cTurns out, if you saut\\u00e9 wilted collards, beet greens and leeks with a little oil and salt, they\\u2019ll taste pretty good, no matter how droopy they look,\\u201d he wrote. Most of what he ate tasted OK, with the exception of a \\u201cpurplish, squishy\\u201d peach.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"All those \\u201cbest before\\u201d food labels now have their own expiration date: June 2018. Two major food industry retail and manufacturer associations set that date as a deadline to roll out two simpler standard labels to replace the myriad currently in use. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"These guidelines were recently released by the Food Marketing Institute, an Arlington, Va.-based marketing group specializing in public policy and food safety, and the Grocery Manufacturers Association, a Washington, D.C.-based trade group representing food companies.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cBest if used by\\u201d would be used to communicate quality, where the product is still safe to consume after the date and \\u201cUse by\\u201d would indicate a product that is highly perishable and/or has food safety concerns over time. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: Thanksgiving dinner guests may be even more insufferable this year \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThis is an enormously helpful step in addressing the vast amount of food going to waste in stores and homes across the country,\\u201d the NRDC said in a statement. \\u201cThere are no federal rules that set standard ways to date food labels, with the exception of infant formula. State and local rules vary and in most instances, industry practice has been to print dates based on the manufacturers\\u2019 suggestions for when food is likely to be at its freshest or peak quality.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Over 80% of Americans may be prematurely tossing food because they misinterpret expiration dates, according to Harvard University and the NRDC; the latest label guidance for food manufacturers closely follows the guidance in that report. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Consumers are confused by what is fresh food and what is bad food, and they conflate different supermarket labels. Phrases like \\u201csell by,\\u201d \\u201cuse by,\\u201d and \\u201cbest before\\u201d are poorly regulated and often misinterpreted, the report found: \\u201cIt is time for a well-intended but wildly ineffective food date labeling system to get a makeover.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Supermarkets don\\u2019t like to sell imperfect food, often removing food from the shelves even when it\\u2019s still good and consumers give a lot of weight to expiration dates, according to Roni Neff, assistant professor at the Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health in Baltimore. (In 2016, France banned supermarkets from throwing out food that was nearing its expiration date.) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Nearly 70% of people say throwing away food after the package date reduces the odds of food-borne illness, while nearly 60% said trashing food is necessary to ensure meals taste fresh, a study published in 2016 in the peer-reviewed scientific journal Plos One, published by the Public Library of Science, found.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read also: Why the middle-aged \\u2018dad bod\\u2019 could be deadly instead of sexy \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIf the U.S. is to reach its recently announced goal of reducing food waste by 50% by the year 2030, U.S. consumers must be an integral part of any successful plan,\\u201d the co-authors of the Plos One study, Danyi Qi, a PhD student in the Department of Agriculture at The Ohio State University and Brian Roe, a professor in the same department, wrote. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"They suggest removing \\u201csell by\\u201d dates to avoid disposing of food prematurely and focusing on nitrogen pollution from rotting food waste. What\\u2019s more, iPhone apps like Green Egg Shopper ($3.99) and Food Storage & Shelf Life ($0.99) can also help keep track of perishables.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" (This story was updated on Nov. 21, 2018.) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Quentin Fottrell is MarketWatch\'s personal-finance editor and The Moneyist columnist for MarketWatch. You can follow him on Twitter @quantanamo. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(185,'MarketWatch','Walgreens, Humana may take stakes in each other, expand partnership','Dana Mattioli ','Published: Nov 20, 2018 4:48 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/06/26/Photos/ZH/MW-GL528_Walgre_20180626065108_ZH.jpg?uuid=d543e678-792e-11e8-ab59-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Drugstore owner Walgreens Boots Alliance Inc. and health insurer Humana Inc. are in preliminary discussions to take equity stakes in each other, according to people familiar with the matter, as health-industry players scramble for tie-ups that will help them compete in a rapidly evolving environment.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The companies, which already have a partnership focused on serving seniors from two Walgreens locations, are having wide-ranging talks that also include the possibility of expanding that venture, the people said. Details of the talks couldn\\u2019t be learned and there\\u2019s no guarantee there will be any new deal between the companies.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Drugstore owners and other health providers are looking for ways to diversify, bulk up and insulate themselves against external threats, including from Amazon.com Inc. AMZN, +2.31% \\u00a0 The latest talks come nearly a year after Walgreens rival CVS Health Corp. CVS, +0.30% \\u00a0 announced a $69 billion deal to buy insurer Aetna Inc. AET, +0.95% \\u00a0 The proposed acquisition is aimed at securing new avenues for growth for the pharmacy company and capturing more of what consumers spend on health care.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For Walgreens WBA, +1.15% \\u00a0, a closer connection with Humana HUM, +0.25% \\u00a0 could replicate expected benefits of the CVS-Aetna deal at a much lower cost than a takeover, especially given the strong performance of Humana stock in recent years. Humana\\u2019s market value currently stands at about $42 billion, while Walgreens\\u2019 is $78 billion. Cross shareholdings could increase incentives for the companies to work together and make their partnership work.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also popular on WSJ.com: \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" U.S. stock selloff deepens as tech worries spread. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Outlook for traditional TV goes from bad to worse. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(186,'MarketWatch','Renault appoints interim CEO, chairman after Ghosns arrest','Nick Kostov ','Published: Nov 20, 2018 5:33 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY872_renaul_20181120173047_ZH.jpg?uuid=ed51f1d4-ed13-11e8-a7a7-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"PARIS \\u2014 Renault SA appointed interim leaders to manage the French auto maker after the arrest of Chief Executive Carlos Ghosn in Japan.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"After a meeting late Tuesday, Renault\\u2019s board said it had appointed the firm\\u2019s No. 2 executive, Thierry Bollor\\u00e9, to serve as deputy CEO on a temporary basis and Philippe Lagayette, Renault\\u2019s lead independent director, to act as interim chairman.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Renault RNO, +1.10% \\u00a0 is moving to fill a power vacuum that opened when Japanese prosecutors arrested Ghosn, an auto-industry titan and one of the world\\u2019s best-known business executives, on allegations of financial misconduct.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Nissan Motor Co. 7201, +0.36% \\u00a0, where Ghosn serves as chairman, said Monday that it went to Japanese authorities with details of an internal probe that alleged he incorrectly reported his compensation in filings over many years. The Japanese auto maker, Renault\\u2019s partner, also said it would seek to oust Ghosn from his position. Renault\\u2019s board said that while Ghosn formally retains his posts as chairman and CEO of the car maker, his powers were being delegated to Bollor\\u00e9 and Lagayette.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also popular on WSJ.com: \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" U.S. stock selloff deepens as tech worries spread. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Outlook for traditional TV goes from bad to worse. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Want news about Europe delivered to your inbox? Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Europe Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(187,'MarketWatch','Amazons HQ2 has given New York City to D.C. Amtrak commuters new hope','Leslie Albrecht','Published: Nov 21, 2018 9:17 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY866_amtrak_20181120154702_ZH.jpg?uuid=6f0213b2-ed05-11e8-a0b2-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"As millions of Thanksgiving travelers prep for train trips between Washington, D.C. and New York City this week, Amazon\\u2019s AMZN, +2.29% \\u00a0HQ2 announcement is giving passengers on the delay-ridden route something they haven\\u2019t felt in years: Hope.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"While car and subway commuters in Long Island City, N.Y. and Crystal City, Va. worry their trips to work will get worse, some train travelers between the two cities see reason for some optimism. With 25,000 new Amazon employees headed to each city, there\\u2019s bound to be some travelling back and forth, the reasoning goes. That prospect has train travelers and transportation advocates hoping the route will see long-awaited upgrades as a result. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cRail has always gotten a backseat, and if anyone can do it, it\\u2019s either Amazon \\u2014 or Elon Musk,\\u201d said Oren Eisenberg, a Philadelphia resident who routinely takes Amtrak to New York. \\u201cIt\\u2019s frustrating to a lot of people who need to travel this corridor daily or weekly because the cost of tickets is so high, and yet the value of that high cost is lower and lower as the infrastructure becomes less efficient to use.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"(Tesla TSLA, -1.60% \\u00a0 CEO Elon Musk is planning a high-speed \\u201chyperloop\\u201d between D.C. and NYC. A spokesman declined to comment on whether HQ2 will affect that plan.)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some Amtrak riders hope it will mean cheaper, faster, more modern trains, others are longing for improvements to Wi-Fi connections on trains and station lounges. Some are fantasizing that Amazon founder and CEO Jeff Bezos \\u2014 worth an estimated $123 billion \\u2014 will simply buy the rail line and improve it. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt really could do a lot for the region and help be an accelerant to getting an excellent world-class train transportation up and running throughout the East Coast,\\u201d said Sean Jeans-Gail, vice president of government affairs and policy at the Rail Passengers Association. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But until now, he noted, \\u201cthe near-term track record is one of abject failure in responding to surging demand for rail transportation.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The trek needs all the help it can get. With airports in both cities congested, Amtrak has surged in popularity as a way to travel between the country\\u2019s financial and political capitals.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Amtrak\\u2019s Northeast Corridor \\u2014 the route between D.C. and Boston \\u2014 is the busiest railroad in North America, an Amtrak spokeswoman said, and the number of passengers has climbed steadily since 2014, according to the Rail Passengers Association. But trains are routinely delayed by signal problems, derailments, collisions with vehicles, and even errant tugboats \\u2014 and those are just examples from the last few weeks.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"On top of that, the trip is expensive: Tickets from Washington\\u2019s Union Station to New York\\u2019s Penn Station start at around $100 each way and go up to an average of $202 each way for the fastest train, the Acela, according to the travel site Wanderu.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"One major reason the trip can be so slow: The rickety bridges and tunnels that trains use as they flow \\u2014 or in many cases, crawl \\u2014 in and out of the New York and New Jersey area.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Transportation advocates say Amazon\\u2019s decision to split HQ2 between two hubs on Amtrak\\u2019s Northeast Corridor adds more urgency to its most pressing infrastructure upgrade, the Gateway Program, which will replace or modernize some of those spans and double the number of passenger trains that can run under the Hudson River. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cRight now, the delays that people are feeling in this region on Amtrak, a lot of them are connected to the fact that you have century-old infrastructure that is literally failing before our eyes,\\u201d said Dani Simons, spokeswoman for the New York-based nonprofit Regional Plan Association. \\u201cAmazon provides another reason why this is so urgent.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A coalition of companies \\u2014 including Siemens SIEGY, +2.40% \\u00a0 and real estate developers The Durst Organization and Brookfield Properties \\u2014 have joined the effort to push the Gateway Program forward, and Amazon would be a welcome addition to that list, Simons said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt would be a win-win for Amazon to be involved in the advocacy for it,\\u201d she said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A key part of the Gateway project \\u2014 the replacement of the Portal Bridge \\u2014 can\\u2019t move forward until it gets a federal funding commitment. Transportation advocates told MarketWatch they were hopeful Amazon\\u2019s announcement would spur action on that front from the U.S. Department of Transportation.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But a DOT spokesperson said Amazon\\u2019s HQ2 decision would have no effect on the project\\u2019s timeline. \\u201cTo the extent Amazon may have received financial incentives from state or local governments, no financial commitments of any kind were obtained from USDOT,\\u201d a spokesperson told MarketWatch.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Indeed, HQ2 will bring street and pedestrian improvements to Long Island City and Crystal City, but officials haven\\u2019t announced any plans for improvements on the train route between the two cities.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Another alarming piece of evidence for Amtrak regulars who hope HQ2 will prompt upgrades: Amazon snagged a helipad as part of its deal with New York City and is trying to get one in Northern Virginia. The company will be limited to 120 landings a year in New York City, so perhaps there\\u2019s hope yet that Amazon execs will use the train. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"An Amazon spokesperson declined to comment on whether the company had been in communication with Amtrak about its HQ2 plans. Amtrak wouldn\\u2019t comment on that question either, but an Amtrak spokeswoman noted that riders have some improvements to look forward to in the near future, regardless of Amazon.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cLong-established plans are underway to refresh trains, improve on-time performance, enhance Wi-Fi connectivity, upgrade facilities and expand onboard experience options,\\u201d said Amtrak spokeswoman Kimberly Woods.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Amtrak is modernizing D.C.\\u2019s Union Station to double the amount of passengers it can hold, and a new fleet of Acela Express trains will go into service in 2021. \\u201cThe new fleet will provide customers with world-class accommodations and amenities, along with a smoother and even more comfortable ride,\\u201d Woods said. The new cars will be much roomier, but they won\\u2019t necessarily make the trip any faster, because the trains still have to contend with crumbling bridges and tunnels.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt should be a much more pleasant experience, but if you\\u2019re not moving the trains quickly and efficiently, you\\u2019re just stuck in a prettier shell while you\\u2019re being delayed,\\u201d said the Rail Passengers Association\\u2019s Jeans-Gail.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Leslie Albrecht is a personal finance reporter based in New York. She worked previously as a local news reporter at the New York City neighborhood news website DNAinfo, and as a reporter at the Modesto Bee and Merced Sun-Star, two McClatchy newspapers in California\'s Central Valley. She is a graduate of the Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism. Follow her on Twitter at @ReporterLeslie. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(188,'MarketWatch','Bitcoin on the verge of sliding below $4,000 as crypto collapse resumes','Aaron Hankin','Published: Nov 20, 2018 4:57 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/02/07/Photos/ZH/MW-GD284_bitcoi_20180207133728_ZH.jpg?uuid=f2fe5196-0c35-11e8-9559-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"A brief late-morning rally was as good as it got for the crypto community on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"After popping into positive territory the price of a single bitcoin, BTCUSD, +2.04% the world\\u2019s largest cryptocurrency, did an abrupt U-turn, tumbling to a fresh 13-month low below $4,100, down nearly 15% since 5 p.m. Eastern Time on the Kraken crypto exchange. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Bitcoin traded to an intraday low of $4,067.10, its lowest level since Sept. 27, 2017. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The total value of all cryptocurrencies has slumped to a more than one-year nadir beneath $150 billion, according to data from CoinMarketCap.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Justice Department has intensified its probe into crypto exchange Bitfinex and Tether, a prominent stablecoin, which some allege is artificially inflating bitcoin values, according to reports, including one from Bloomberg. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The report comes after a University of Texas study linked issuance of Tether with increases in the price of bitcoin. In fact, this morning, a prominent Bitfinex skeptic Twitter user noted that the price of bitcoin jumped after an injection of $50 million worth of Tether. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Just another fucking coincidence, I\'m sure. Within minutes of Tether re-injecting $50 million dollars worth of Tethers, the market magically turns around.It\'s just a coincidence. I\'m sure everything is fine. pic.twitter.com/mfMfscnVWy\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Bloomberg had previously reported that the Commodity Futures Trading Commission was investigating both Tether and Bitfinex and had requested documents and material from the entities.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Pressure mounts on Tether as stablecoin proves not so stable \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Despite psychological support at the $6,000 level holding for a prolonged period, the lack of a bounce should have been a red flag for bitcoin bulls, one analyst said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cEnthusiasts may have looked at bitcoin\\u2019s ability to hold above $6,000 as a sign of a market bottoming, but the warning signs were there each time it failed to make a new high on a rebound\\u2014most notably in March, May, July and even September,\\u201d wrote Craig Erlam, senior market analyst at Oanda. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt\\u2019s always difficult to say where the market could stabilize again in such a wild market, but $3,000 looks an interesting level. This time last year, the sky was the limit for bitcoin and all the altcoins that piggybacked a ride, this year the ground below is looking very unsteady,\\u201d he wrote.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Opinion: Bitcoin still fooling buyers into believing those 200%-plus gains are coming back \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Altcoins, those more than 2,000 coins other than bitcoin, are mostly lower on Tuesday. Ether, ETHUSD, +0.27% which has slipped to third on the list of largest digital assets by total value, is down 8.5% at $134.99, Litecoin LTCUSD, +0.76% was down 7% at $35.14, XRP, XRPUSD, +0.28% had lost 9.4% to 44 cents and Bitcoin Cash was bucking the trend, trading up 2.1% to $263.30.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Bitcoin futures finished Tuesday well in the red. The Cboe Global Markets December contract XBTZ8, +0.92% \\u00a0ended the day down 9.2% at $4,365 and the CME Group November contract BTCX8, +4.13% finished Tuesday down 12.3% at $4,240.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Why bitcoin prices are staging a fresh collapse \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Providing critical information for the U.S. trading day. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Need to Know newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Aaron Hankin is a MarketWatch reporter in New York who covers cryptocurrency and financial markets. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(189,'MarketWatch','SpaceX raises $250 million in high-yield loan sale','Sam Goldfarb ','Published: Nov 20, 2018 4:28 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2017/12/13/Photos/ZH/MW-GA141_space__20171213130400_ZH.jpg?uuid=ff0ebdb8-e02f-11e7-9558-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Elon Musk\\u2019s SpaceX raised $250 million from its first-ever high-yield loan sale, shrinking the size of the loan by $500 million after the company encountered a mixed reception from investors and worsening credit-market conditions.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The loan, facilitated by Bank of America Corp. BAC, +0.51% \\u00a0 and slated to fund general corporate purposes, opens a new avenue for fundraising for SpaceX as it looks to pay for massive projects demanding many billions of dollars over the next few years.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Based in Hawthorne, Calif., SpaceX makes money by launching commercial and government satellites but has larger ambitions of sending astronauts into orbit \\u00a0and eventually carrying humans to Mars. It has previously relied on private-equity funding that has valued the company at more than $20 billion.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Formerly known as Space Exploration Technologies Corp., SpaceX marketed its loan only to a select group of investors.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also popular on WSJ.com: \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" U.S. stock selloff deepens as tech worries spread. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Outlook for traditional TV goes from bad to worse. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(190,'MarketWatch','Many diabetics wont be able to get insulin by 2030 unless big changes happen','Emma Court','Published: Nov 21, 2018 11:59 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/21/Photos/ZH/MW-GY916_insuli_20181121111955_ZH.jpg?uuid=483b4542-eda9-11e8-8d46-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"For diabetics, insulin is a lifesaving medication, crucial to controlling the disease and preventing complications. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But access to insulin is already a major problem globally \\u2014 and it\\u2019s likely to get worse over the next decade, according to a new study published in the peer-reviewed medical journal The Lancet Diabetes & Endocrinology. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Global insulin needs are likely to surge by more than 20% by 2030, the study found. But, unless major changes occur, roughly half of the 79 million adults with type 2 diabetes won\\u2019t be able to get insulin, the authors concluded. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The study\\u2019s lead author, Stanford University\\u2019s Dr. Sanjay Basu, described the situation as a \\u201clooming health challenge.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cSubstantial improvements in access to insulin in low-income and middle-income countries are needed in order to reduce inequalities in access and complications of diabetes compared with high-income countries,\\u201d the study\\u2019s authors wrote. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read more: In the age of Uber and Lyft, it\\u2019s still hard for some Americans to get to the doctor \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Diabetes affects the way a person\\u2019s body processes sugar. The most prevalent type is type 2 diabetes, which usually affects adults but is more often seen now in younger individuals as well. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Insulin is crucial for both type 1 and type 2 diabetics. Type 1 diabetics\\u2019 bodies don\\u2019t make blood sugar-regulating insulin; without it, they will \\u201cdie in a matter of weeks,\\u201d according to a 2016 Lancet study. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In type 2 diabetes, insulin helps control the disease and avoid or push back complications like blindness, amputation and stroke. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" See: Non-diabetics are using diabetes technology to track their blood sugar and improve their health \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The diagnosis of both types has become more common over the last 30 years, especially in low-income and middle-income countries. That trend is only expected to continue, with adults with type 2 diabetes expected to rise from 406 million this year to 511 million in 2030. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some of the biggest percentage increases in diabetes over the next several decades are expected in Africa, the Middle East and north Africa and southeast Asia, according to the International Diabetes Federation. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But obtaining insulin has consistently been a problem due to problems with availability and pricing, according to the World Health Organization. (Insulin has also increasingly become out of reach for many in the U.S. due to rising prices.) \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"More insulin will also probably be needed to treat type 2 diabetics in the coming years as the population lives longer. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The study\\u2019s authors based their findings on a microsimulation that modeled the population of type 2 diabetics across the world and estimated how much insulin they would need. Type 2 diabetes incidence in upcoming years could be larger or smaller than expected, one of the study\\u2019s key limitations. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Previous studies have looked at insulin access problems in east and south Asia, but this study, published late Tuesday, came up with a direct estimate of expected global insulin use, the authors noted. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Emma Court covers healthcare for MarketWatch from New York. You can follow her on Twitter @EmmaRCourt. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(191,'MarketWatch','Remember, the IRS will never email you','Kari Paul','Published: Nov 21, 2018 9:08 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY869_laptop_20181120165113_ZH.jpg?uuid=667613fc-ed0e-11e8-8f18-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"If you get an email from the Internal Revenue Service, don\\u2019t open it.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"There has been a surge in fraudulent emails from senders impersonating the IRS, the agency warned this week. The emails often use the subject line \\u201ctax transcripts\\u201d in an attempt to bait people into opening documents that contain malware that then attacks the computer and its network. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The malware used in the attack the IRS warned about is Emotet, a well-known infection that allows hackers to steal sensitive financial data. The United States Computer Emergency Readiness Team has designated it as \\u201camong the most costly and destructive malware affecting state, local, tribal, and territorial (SLTT) governments, and the private and public sectors.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Both individuals and businesses should be on alert for the emails. \\u201cThe scam is especially problematic for businesses whose employees might open the malware because this malware can spread throughout the network and potentially take months to successfully remove,\\u201d the IRS said in a statement.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The IRS, along with tax prep companies and state agencies that it partners with through its Security Summit program, are warning taxpayers to avoid the scam. The IRS will never initiate contact with consumers by email, it said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"People panic when they see the IRS in their email inbox, said Abhishek Iyer, technical marketing manager at Cupertino, Calif.-based provider of security automation Demisto.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThese phishing emails exploit the fear and urgency that\\u2019s usually tied with receiving any financial or tax-related information,\\u201d he said. \\u201cIf people stop and think, they\\u2019ll know that it\\u2019s unusual for the IRS to send sensitive information over email. But the phishing emails bank on them to not spend any time thinking.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If you receive an email from the IRS, do not open any attachments and forward it to the IRS security email: phishing@irs.gov. And if the email has been sent to your work account, alert the company\\u2019s technology professionals of the potential attack.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The attack comes as consumers face IRS fraud on other platforms as well. Consumers reported $905 million lost to robocall fraud in 2017, up $63 million from the year before, according to the Federal Trade Commission.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some groups are at higher risk than others: People in their 20s and early 30s are six times likelier than baby boomers to disclose personal information to phone scammers. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"As is the case with emails, the IRS will never call you to demand repayment for penalties. Call the IRS line directly to verify if you think you may have penalties to pay at 800-829-1040. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Kari Paul is a personal finance reporter based in New York. You can follow her on Twitter @kari_paul. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(192,'MarketWatch','Opinion: The tech-stock selloff is a golden opportunity to buy Amazon, Apple, Netflix and Tesla','Tim Mullaney','Published: Nov 21, 2018 8:02 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2017/12/01/Photos/ZH/MW-FZ364_tesla__20171201081707_ZH.jpg?uuid=ee35ea9c-d699-11e7-907f-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"In America, we\\u2019re in the business of waiting for rationality these days. In politics, it will be delivered in two years, minus two weeks (unless we\\u2019ve all lost our minds). In stocks, the smart course is to figure on it taking six months or even less \\u2014 which means acting relatively soon to take advantage of it.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This is basically the only reaction to a market that continues to slaughter indiscriminately, and not exactly intelligently. Tuesday\\u2019s example is Target TGT, +0.48% down more than 10% after third-quarter earnings missed expectations by 2% while the company raised wages and beat revenue targets. Target, which is still up substantially this year, is no General Electric GE, +2.81% sorting through underperforming businesses and realizing that it wasted so much money on stock buybacks that the ex-icon of America\\u2019s Industrial Might has a negative tangible book value. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Or, put it this way: How much sense did it make when the market\\u2019s reaction to a weak report on home-builder sentiment and foot traffic at new-home communities was to sell off technology stocks?\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But that\\u2019s where we are, with the last of the gains this year in the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.78% \\u00a0and the S&P 500 SPX, +0.92% wiped out.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"And that means it\\u2019s time to follow Uncle Julius.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Julius was Julius Westheimer, who in my own misspent youth was a Baltimore stockbroker and denizen of the Baltimore Sun, where he was a columnist to my cub reporter, and a regular on Wall $treet Week, a public-TV stock-market show produced at Maryland Public TV. Julius was a lovely man, to my 27-year old eye a million years old if he were a day (he was actually 72 when we met) and an uncommonly bright man with a singularly common opinion it would be well to act upon right now.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"He was a nut for, and taught me about, dollar-cost averaging.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Dollar-cost averaging is what its name implies \\u2014 the practice of buying dips to lower the average cost of the shares you own, the better to smooth out rough market rides like we\\u2019ve seen in November. Every month, or every paycheck, put the same amount of money into your investments. That gives you more exposure to shares bought when investors are pessimistic, as they are now, and less exposure to shares purchased at short-term peaks like the one the market hit in August..\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"So how does that apply right now?\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It works best if you couple Julius\\u2019 approach with lessons I\\u2019ve learned in 20 years of tracking tech stocks, the most important of which is to ask yourself whether a company you\\u2019re investing in is driving an important, secular change like the advent of online commerce 20 years ago or the not-so-gradual migration of corporate computing to \\u201ccloud\\u201d services companies like Microsoft MSFT, +2.21% \\u00a0or Amazon.com AMZN, +2.15% today.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Because the one fundamental law of tech investing is that if a technology is fundamentally disruptive enough, that fact will always overwhelm the noise of the day about valuation. And it rarely takes long. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Right now, that basic approach is good news for stocks like Microsoft and Amazon \\u2014 and for Netflix NFLX, -0.47% \\u00a0and Tesla TSLA, -1.80% It\\u2019s a mixed bag for Facebook FB, +2.51% \\u00a0(since social networking, while fun and amusing, actually does little to boost productivity) and AAPL, +0.62% \\u00a0(mobile phones are obviously a big deal, but may be a maturing market). But even for those, the balance of risks points to continuing to treat those stocks pretty much as you have. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If you like them, there\\u2019s not a lot that has happened recently that should change that, especially with the stocks on sale now. (My detailed take on Facebook is another column). And if you didn\\u2019t, you were wrong and have been wrong, literally, for years.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Let\\u2019s review.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Tesla: Electric cars will still be cheaper than internal-combustion vehicles by about 2025, Bloomberg New Energy Finance says. And they\\u2019re faster and much cleaner. CEO Elon Musk will need money for expansion, and is far from the world\\u2019s best executive, but a slightly unstable genius is still a genius.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"You can worry about the stock\\u2019s recent drop from $370 to $340 and wonder if the sky\\u2019s falling \\u2014 if you block out the fundamentals in the last paragraph, and listen to people who thought Tesla wildly overpriced at $100, or have long argued that financial markets that have made Tesla will turn on it with profits at hand. Don\\u2019t.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Tesla short sellers continue to sow doubt, but the numbers back up earnings \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Amazon: If you\\u2019re even thinking the word \\u201cChristmas\\u201d about Amazon, you\\u2019re doing it wrong. Even before the recent bust, two-thirds of Amazon\\u2019s value came from Amazon Web Services. That cloud computing unit\\u2019s market-share gains continue apace, and it\\u2019s far more profitable than the retail business.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Netflix: A little tougher because the valuation is high by any standard \\u2014 it always has been, and the stock still trades for 64 times 2019 estimates even after falling by a third. But the company is revolutionizing the film and TV industries, taking share all over the world, with excellent management and, many analysts think, ample room to raise prices. A less-frantic market will remind itself of those virtues.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: It\\u2019s time to stop lumping Netflix in with the other FAANG stocks, says analyst \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Apple: What is it about the recent hand-wringing over maturing iPhone demand that does not sound exactly like the worries over sales in China that made Apple stock sell off in 2015? Great companies \\u2014 Apple is one \\u2014solve problems all the time that are bigger than whether the new iPhones are too expensive. Apple\\u2019s shares trade for 13 times earnings. Take out Apple\\u2019s cash pile and the rest of the company costs about 10.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Apple is a \\u2018buybuybuy\\u2019 right now, and other FAANG stocks are bargains too \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" And the opposite view: This Apple true believer just sold all of his firm\\u2019s shares \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"At prices like these, your odds are pretty good, I\\u2019m confident Julius would have said. (He died in 2005). And it\\u2019s a much simpler calculation, for investors whose bonus and job security aren\\u2019t measured in three-month increments, than deciphering the latest mumbo jumbo from chartists trying to tell you what will happen next week.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Tim Mullaney is a commentary writer who covers the economy and corporate news. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(193,'MarketWatch','As the stock market and economy are set to skid, Goldman says cash will be king','Mark DeCambre','Published: Nov 21, 2018 12:16 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY838_cash_k_20181120104145_ZH.jpg?uuid=c9304ee2-ecda-11e8-976e-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Cash is king. That is according to Goldman Sachs strategists who predict that 2019 will deliver lackluster, single-digit stock-market returns, making greenbacks the best game in town.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe forecast S&P 500 will generate a modest single-digit absolute return in 2019. The risk-adjusted return will be less than half the long-term average. Cash will represent a competitive asset class to stocks for the first time in many years,\\u201d analysts at Goldman, led by David Kostin, wrote in a research reported dated Nov. 19. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Referencing a bull market approaching its 10th year that has delivered double-digit gains in 2017 and repeated records for the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.81% the S&P 500 index SPX, +0.96% and the Nasdaq Composite Index COMP, +1.54% Goldman said \\u201call good things must eventually come to an end.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The strategists echo a common mantra among market bears: a deceleration in economic expansion and corporate profits will occur in 2019 because 2018 produced stellar GDP and earnings fueled by corporate tax cuts from the Trump administration and other business-favorable policies. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Hedge-fund boss who predicted \\u201887 crash says get ready for some \\u2018really scary moments\\u2019\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"On top of that, adjusting for the risk associated with owning equities, Goldman views cash as a better option. Analysts at the investment bank say that households, mutual funds, foreign investors and pensions funds tend to have an allocation to cash that ranks in the lowest percentile and while equity allocations tend to be in the 89th percentile on a historical basis. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Goldman is forecasting that the Federal Reserve will lift interest rates four times in 2018 and another four times next year, pushing the federal-funds rate to a range of 3.25%-3.5% by the end of 2019 from 2%-2.25% currently. In that environment, the analysts see the 10-year Treasury note TMUBMUSD10Y, +0.24% yielding 3.5% by the second half of 2019, which also translates to richer yields for short-term so-called T-bills and other money-market funding. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Providing critical information for the U.S. trading day. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Need to Know newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Mark DeCambre is MarketWatch\'s markets editor. He is based in New York. Follow him on Twitter @mdecambre. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(194,'MarketWatch','Opinion: Heres how to tell if stocks will enter a bear market or rise to new highs','Nigam Arora','Published: Nov 20, 2018 1:15 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/09/06/Photos/ZH/MW-GP563_bullbe_20180906074258_ZH.jpg?uuid=00d57468-b1ca-11e8-b426-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Many investing gurus are predicting a bear market in U.S. stocks. And many more are predicting new highs. How can you tell who is right? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Let us examine with the help of a chart. Please click here for an annotated chart of the effective federal funds rate (which is set by the Federal Reserve) and S&P 500 Index SPX, +0.96% Please note the following:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 The chart shows that the effective fed funds rate has risen rapidly. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 The fed funds rate is still lower than where it should be, given the strength in the U.S. economy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 The Federal Reserve has indicated that it is on course to raise the rate in December.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 The Fed appears to be on course to raise the rate two to three times in 2019. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 The chart shows that a vast majority of the rise in the stock market over the past several years was primarily due to P/E (price/earnings) expansion stemming from low interest rates.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Now the earnings have risen, and P/Es have fallen. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 According to our work at The Arora Report, earnings growth momentum has peaked.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 We have been sharing with you long before this stock market decline that, according to our work, economic growth in the world outside the United States, especially in China, was slowing. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Lower economic growth often means lower earnings. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Higher interest rates often mean lower P/Es. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 The character of the stock market is changing. What has worked over the last nine years is not likely to work over the coming years. Please see \\u201cThe poster child of bull-market excess just dimmed the prospects of the broader stock market.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Pay attention to the technicals. Please see \\u201cThese two chart patterns tell the real story of the stock market.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Ask Arora: Nigam Arora answers your questions about investing in stocks, ETFs, bonds, gold and silver, oil and currencies. Have a question? Send it to Nigam Arora. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"What happens next in the stock market comes down to two things.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"1. Does the Fed relent or stay on its present course? If the Fed stays on its present course, expect P/Es to shrink. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"2. Will economic growth slow? In part, it depends on the resolution of the trade war.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Watch the Fed. If the Fed were to stop raising rates and the trade war was resolved, expect a rip-roaring rally, potentially to new highs. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If the Fed continues on its present course and the trade war is not resolved, there is a high probability of a bear market.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It is worth remembering Arora\\u2019s Second Law of Investing: \\u201cNobody knows with certainty what is going to happen next.\\u201d Investors should think in terms of probabilities.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Here are some things to consider.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Do not be overly concentrated in mega-cap tech stocks such as Facebook FB, +2.61% Apple AAPL, +0.60% Alphabet GOOG, +1.92% GOOGL, +2.05% Amazon AMZN, +2.32% and Microsoft MSFT, +2.34% \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Do not be overly concentrated in growth stocks such as Netflix NFLX, -0.45% CRM, +3.50% Workday WDAY, +5.01% and Adobe ADBE, +3.35% \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Hold a large amount of cash invested in Treasury bills and hedges. The Arora Report provides a precise level of cash and hedges to hold in these market conditions. Please see \\u201cHow one investor sidestepped this week\\u2019s stock-market decline.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Be extra careful if holding long-term bonds.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Follow an adaptive model with a proven track record in both bull and bear markets. An example is the ZYX Asset Allocation Model with inputs in 10 categories. Please click here to see the 10 categories. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Hold on to good long-term positions.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Focus on buying dips in special situations.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Tilt the portfolio toward value.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Be nimble. These days, market conditions change fast.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u2022 Abandon recency bias. Most investors are suffering from recency bias, meaning they think the market will go up because it has gone up.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Disclosure: Subscribers to The Arora Report may have positions in the securities mentioned in this article or may take positions at any time. Nigam Arora is an investor, engineer and nuclear physicist by background who has founded two Inc. 500 fastest-growing companies. He is the founder of The Arora Report, which publishes four newsletters. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Nigam Arora is an engineer, nuclear physicist, author, and entrepreneur and the founder of two Inc. 500 fastest growing companies. He is also the developer of the ZYX Change Method to profit from change by investing. The premise is that most money is made by predicting change before the crowd. Arora is the chief investment officer at The Arora Report and the editor of four newsletters that track the ZYX Change Method. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(195,'MarketWatch','Jeffrey Gundlach says stocks still havent hit a panic low','Barbara Kollmeyer','Published: Nov 21, 2018 8:46 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/21/Photos/ZH/MW-GY882_stocks_20181121070512_ZH.jpg?uuid=b32d3dca-ed85-11e8-97df-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"A Thanksgiving getaway from this stock market perhaps never sounded so good. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A bit of a bounce looks to be building for Wednesday\\u2019s session. But some investors may be wary of what could be a classic dead-cat howler, especially with many traders out until Monday.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Even Greece and Italy are bouncing (post lower-lows within their respective 2018 crashes) this am pic.twitter.com/EH8HurqHj7\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The topic du jour is where stocks go from now, and everyone has an opinion\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"DoubleLine Capital\\u2019s top dog Jeffrey Gundlach told Reuters that the selloff will continue and we aren\\u2019t yet seeing \\u201canything resembling a panic low.\\u201d Now is the time for \\u201ccapital preservation,\\u201d said Gundlach, adding that investors should steer clear of investment-grade bonds for one. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some credited Gundlach\\u2019s comments with triggering a near 650-point drop at one point for the Dow on Tuesday. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"There\\u2019s an echo of Gundlach\\u2019s advice in our first call of the day from Morgan Stanley\\u2019s chief investment officer Mike Wilson who told CNBC Tuesday that it is too soon to buy into this latest dip.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt all stems back to liquidity and the Fed and the tightening of financial conditions\\u2014that is our thesis all year\\u2014it\\u2019s been this rolling bear market and we finally got to the big tech stocks. I actually think we\\u2019re about 90% of the way done with the valuation damage that is going to happen,\\u201d added Wilson. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The selloff is coming now because some investors are realizing that companies will be delivering some bad earnings news next year, Wilson said. He also wants to see some more dovish Fed comments.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Wilson is a cool cucumber, though saying the asset correction is a \\u201cnormal course of business that is very natural at the end of a bull market that needs to consolidate.\\u201d He\\u2019s got his eye on cyclicals such as utilities, health care, energy and banks, because they\\u2019ve already discounted a lot of bad news. \\u201cThey\\u2019ll be the first to recover,\\u201d he says. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Last word goes to our counter call of the day, from UBS\\u2019s chief investment office, which sent a note to clients late Tuesday. \\u201cWe view the selloff as overdone and a bull market correction, with valuations that have become more compelling,\\u201d said UBS, adding that risk-reward for owning equities is \\u201casymmetric to the upside over the next six months.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But they also hold so-called countercyclical positions, such as an overweight in 10-year U.S. Treasurys to manage market volatility as investors wait around for \\u201cmore clarity on trade, the Fed and growth.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Opinion: Here\\u2019s how to tell if stocks will enter a bear market or rise to new highs \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Dow YMZ8, +0.83% S&P 500 ESZ8, +1.00% \\u00a0and Nasdaq NQZ8, +1.42% \\u00a0futures are pointing higher, though there\\u2019s a way to go to make up for Tuesday\\u2019s brutal session, in which the S&P SPX, +0.97% \\u00a0and Dow DJIA, +0.80% \\u00a0erased 2018 gains, with a nasty fall for the Nasdaq COMP, +1.55% \\u00a0as well.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Crude US:CLU8 is also trying to recoup some of Tuesday\\u2019s sharp drop, while the dollar DXY, -0.12% is down and gold US:GCU8 is barely higher.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: A death cross is forming in U.S. oil and Why plunging oil prices are bad for the economy\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Check out the Market Snapshot column for the latest action.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A bounce has extended to Europe SXXP, +1.14% while Asia had a mixed session, with some green for China SHCOMP, +0.21% \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Putting crude\\u2019s 7% drop on Tuesday and miserable week in context is our chart of the day, which comes from Pension Partner\\u2019s director Charlie Bilello. He tweeted this chart out that shows the biggest oil declines in history\\u2014a 77% drop between 2011 and 2016 so far is the winner: \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Largest Crude Oil Declines in History...2011-16: -77% 2008-09: -76%1985-86: -66%1990-94: -66%1996-98: -59%2000-01: -54% pic.twitter.com/EUnK88Lt3y\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Deere DE, +4.05% \\u00a0is slumping after earnings fell short, and the tractor maker said it would lift prices and cut costs. And there was more bad news on the retail front with Gap GPS, +4.99% \\u00a0posting a 7% fall in comparable sales and exploring closure of hundreds of stores.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Red Tuesday for retailers as Target\\u2019s stock suffers worst stretch since financial crisis \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Apple\\u2019s AAPL, +0.66% \\u00a0iPhone assembler Foxconn 2354, -0.97% is reportedly planning $2.9 billion in cost cuts as it faces a \\u201cvery difficult and competitive year.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Despite a rocky year for the social-media group, Facebook FB, +2.64% \\u00a0CEO Mark Zuckerberg says he won\\u2019t step down as chairman and threw his support behind COO Sheryl Sandberg amid criticism of her handling of the Cambridge Analytica scandal.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Back by popular demand, the Victoria Secret\\u2019s swimwear business that L Brands LB, +6.58% \\u00a0left nearly three years ago. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. trade rep Robert Lighthizer slams China for \\u201cunfair, unreasonable and market-distorting\\u201d trade practices in a 50-page report on that country\\u2019s trade practices.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The EU has rejected Italy\\u2019s rule-busting budget proposal and says it is ready to slap down sanctions. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Cybershopping next Monday? Avoid buying this stuff. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It\\u2019s the pre-Thanksgiving data dump, with weekly jobless claims climbing to a 4 1/2 month high, durable goods orders dropping 4.4% and business investment flat. Existing-home sales, consumer sentiment and leading economic indicators are still to come.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"On the central-bank beat, Minneapolis Fed president and super dove Neil Kashkari said it is time to stop hiking rates. And Jeremy Siegel, Wharton School finance professor, expects the Fed to definitely cut back on its hiking plans next year.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Civil war has left 85,000 under five\\u2019s dead from malnutrition in Yemen \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Jailed women\\u2019s-rights activists reportedly tortured in Saudi Arabia \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Interpol rejects Russian, picks South Korean as chief instead\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dozens killed after suicide bomber attacks Afghanistan religious meeting\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"And more than 1,000 pieces of plastic were found in a dead sperm whale in Indonesia\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" A reminder to keep romaine lettuce off the Thanksgiving menu\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" But a hot-Cheetos turkey? Maybe\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Be sure to check the Need to Know item. The emailed version will be sent out at about 7:30 a.m. Eastern. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Follow MarketWatch on Twitter, Instagram, Facebook.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Providing critical information for the U.S. trading day. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Need to Know newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Barbara Kollmeyer is an editor for MarketWatch in Madrid. Follow her on Twitter @bkollmeyer. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(196,'MarketWatch','Trump wants Fed to cut interest rates after stock-market wipeout, but history not on his side','Jeffry Bartash','Published: Nov 20, 2018 5:06 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/02/23/Photos/MG/MW-GE309_fed_po_20180223151250_MG.jpg?uuid=ec4e9a02-18d5-11e8-ac88-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"After the latest stock-market drubbing, President Donald Trump said Tuesday he\\u2019d like the Federal Reserve to cut interest rates. But that may be wishful thinking.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The U.S. is on track to grow 3% annually in 2018 for the first time in 13 years and the unemployment rate has fallen to a 48-year low of 3.7%. The Fed has cut rates a few times when gross domestic product appeared strong, albeit it briefly, but almost never when both growth was stable and unemployment low. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"There\\u2019s no example of the Fed doing since the end of World War II.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shortly before flying to Florida for Thanksgiving, the president told reporters the Fed was somewhat to blame when asked about the plunging stock market and overall health of the economy. He\\u2019s been critical of the Fed for months because of its policy to gradually raise U.S. interest rates.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Dow finishes down 550 points as stocks erase 2018 gains \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cI\\u2019d like to see the Fed with a lower interest rate. I think the rate\\u2019s too high. I think we have much more of a Fed problem than we have a problem with anyone else,\\u201d Trump said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The central bank has lifted a key short-term interest rate known as fed funds three times this year, with a fourth hike expected next month. The Fed wants to make sure a strong U.S. economy and tight labor market don\\u2019t cause prices and wages to rise so fast they trigger a damaging bout of inflation.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. interest rates are still extremely low by historical standards, however, and there\\u2019s little evidence the economy is about to stumble.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The fed funds rate now ranges from 2% to 2.25%. By contrast, the rate reached as high as 5.25% during the last economic expansion from 2001 to 2007.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The economy, for its part, is likely to grow close to 3% in the fourth quarter after gains of 3.5% and 4.2% in the prior two quarters.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Inflation, meanwhile, appears stable. The Fed\\u2019s preferred PCE price gauge rose 2% from September 2017 to September 2018 \\u2014 exactly the central bank\\u2019s official target.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Fed might change its plans if the stock market continues to tank and the economy slows, but the central bank is unlikely to do so absent the evidence. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Jeffry Bartash is a reporter for MarketWatch in Washington. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(197,'MarketWatch','Stocks rise as S&P, Dow attempt to recover from worst start to Thanksgiving week in 45 years','Mark DeCambre','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:08 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/21/Photos/ZH/MW-GY880_turkey_20181121061223_ZH.jpg?uuid=5210e458-ed7e-11e8-b040-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. stock indexes rose Wednesday, as they look to recapture some of the ugly losses accumulated over the past two sessions on the back of a persistent rout in once-highflying tech stocks and declines in oil.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. financial markets will be closed Thursday for the Thanksgiving Day holiday and see an early close Friday.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.79% \\u00a0rose 176 points, or 0.7%, to 24,642. The S&P 500 SPX, +0.93% advanced 26 points, or 1%, to 2,667, while The Nasdaq Composite Index NQZ8, +1.41% gained 112 points to reach 7,021, a rise of 1.6%. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Tuesday\\u2019s decline erased year-to-date gains for both the Dow and S&P 500, while the Nasdaq now clings to a 1.1% advance for 2018. Month to date, the Nasdaq has fallen 3.9%, the S&P has slid 1.6%, and the Dow has retreated 1.9% in November.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Why share buybacks aren\\u2019t the stock market\\u2019s safety net \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"According to Dow Jones Market Data, the Monday-to-Tuesday descent for the S&P 500 and Dow mark their worst starts to the Thanksgiving week since 1973, and the steepest for the Nasdaq since 2000. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"U.S. investors were hoping for a respite to counter the worst start to Thanksgiving week in 45 years, with fears about valuations of technology and internet-related stocks, sluggish growth, policy errors by the Federal Reserve and uncertainty about trade relations between the U.S. and China swirling in investors\\u2019 minds. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Contributing some early upward momentum to the energy sector were gains in crude-oil prices, with data released Tuesday momentarily alleviating growing worries about global oversupply, which has driven U.S. benchmark oil CLF9, +3.14% deep into bear-market territory, defined as a decline of a at least 20% from a recent peak.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"New data on orders for American-manufactured goods were released before the bell Wednesday, showing the largest decline in durable-goods orders in 15 months. More important, the report from Census Bureau showed orders for capital goods falling for the third month in a row, adding to fears that U.S. business investment is decelerating.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Investors also received some good news on the housing front, as existing-home sales rose for the first time in six months. That\\u2019s after a series of reports of the housing market has reinforced the view that increases to benchmark interest rates are eroding confidence in the housing industry. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cToday is clearly about buying on the recent weakness,\\u201d Kevin Divney, senior portfolio manager at Russell Investments, told MarketWatch.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWe don\\u2019t see a broad, systemic reason why the market has been selling off, and so we expect to continue to see stock-specific buyers out there, taking advantage of compressed valuations,\\u201d he said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Going forward, Divney sees data released by companies like Amazon on vacation sales figures as a potential catalyst for the return of more positive sentiment. \\u201cHoliday sales growth above 5% would be encouraging,\\u201d he said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cI know better than to declare bottoms in markets,\\u201d Tom Essaye, president of the Sevens Report, wrote in a note to clients. \\u201cBut yesterday had some of what we look for when trying to identify selling capitulation, including: an initial morning plunge that market the low for the day, stabilization of recent laggards, and a lack of a spike in the VIX.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cAmerica\\u2019s battered equity markets are limping towards the Thanksgiving holiday with precious little to be thankful for,\\u201d wrote J.R. Zhou, chief market strategist at broker Infinox, in a Wednesday note.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"He said the realization that the strength of America\\u2019s domestic economy is being rendered increasingly irrelevant by the continued weakness of its trading partners, and fears that \\u201cthe Federal Reserve\\u2019s hawks risk becoming an albatross\\u201d are weighing on market sentiment and contributing to volatile markets. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Deere & Co. DE, +3.79% \\u00a0shares are rising Wednesday, even after the farm-equipment maker reported disappointing quarterly profits. Shares were up 4.5% in morning trade, though the stock remains down more than 6% year-to-date. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares of Footlocker Inc. FL, +13.89% are surging more than 16% Wednesday, following a Tuesday-evening earnings release that showed the company beating Wall Street estimates for third-quarter profits.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Autodesk Inc. ADSK, +9.44% stock is rising 9% Wednesday, after the company reported earnings, sales and outlook beats, Tuesday evening.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares of Mylan NV MYL, -1.92% traded lower Wednesday, one day after the FDA issued a warning letter summarizing violations of manufacturing regulations, related to its inspection of a facility in West Virginia. The stock is down 1.9%.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Growth technology stocks are rising Wednesday, during a month when these erstwhile market leaders have otherwise fallen sharply. Facebook Inc. FB, +2.54% shares are up 2.8%, Amazon Inc. AMZN, +2.19% was up 2%, and Microsoft Corp. MSFT, +2.23% shares are 2.6% higher.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Shares of Best Buy Co., Inc. are continuing their yearlong slide on Wednesday, as earnings and revenue beats announced yesterday couldn\\u2019t prevent Credit Suisse and Raymond James analysts lowering their price targets for the big-box retailer. The stock is down 3.1% Wednesday and is more than 10% lower on the year.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Asian markets traded mixed Wednesday, with most of the region\\u2019s major indexes recovering from session lows into the close. Japan\\u2019s Nikkei NIK, -0.35% fell by 0.4%, while Australia\\u2019s ASX XJO, -0.51% \\u00a0fell by 0.5%. Hong Kong\\u2019s Hang Seng Index HSI, +0.51% recovered from early losses to end the day up 0.5%, while China\\u2019s Shanghai Composite Index SHCOMP, +0.21% edged 0.2% higher.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"European markets ended the trading day broadly higher, with the Stoxx Europe 600 SXXP, +1.14% rising 1% and the FTSE 100 UKX, +1.47% up 1.5%. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Crude oil CLF9, +3.14% is staging a relief rally Wednesday, up 3.5% during a November where its price has fallen more than 15%. Gold prices GCZ8, +0.55% were edging up 0.5%, while the U.S. dollar DXY, -0.11% is virtually unchanged.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Providing critical information for the U.S. trading day. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Need to Know newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(198,'MarketWatch','South African assets rally on risk appetite, but there are plenty of worries for their future','Anneken Tappe','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:46 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/08/23/Photos/ZH/MW-GO791_rand_20180823053420_ZH.jpg?uuid=b66f1c66-a6b7-11e8-9522-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"South Africa\\u2019s rand outperformed other emerging market currencies against the U.S. dollar on Wednesday thanks to improving risk appetite, but there are plenty reasons to be cautious.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The rand USDZAR, -1.2508% \\u00a0rallied ahead of its emerging market peers versus the buck, with one dollar last buying 13.9030 rand, down 1.4%. Over the past three months, the dollar has slipped 3.5% against the rand, but in the year-to-date its still up against it by more than 12%, according to FactSet.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"So what\\u2019s going on?\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" South Africa\\u2019s assets weren\\u2019t spared during the emerging markets selloff in the summer, shining a bright spotlight on its already weak economy. In the second quarter, the country slipped into a recession, and last month Finance Minister Tito Mboweni downgraded the economic forecast.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" See: Why emerging markets haven\\u2019t really recovered since the summer selloff \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"As an exporter of many commodities, but a net oil importer, South Africa is at the mercy of global growth and swings in commodity prices. As market folks downgrade their outlook for the world economy, things might get scary for Johannesburg.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"October\\u2019s consumer price inflation soared to a one-year higher of 5.1% year-over-year Wednesday, marking the fourth month in a row that CPI exceeds the midpoint of the South African Reserve Bank\\u2019s target range of 3%-6%. And this tale is far from over.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"SARB already voiced concerns about rising inflation, but the rand\\u2019s weakness this year has helped suggest the only way is up. The central bank could raise interest rates on Thursday, from 6.5% to 6.75%, to stem the inflationary pressure, which would likely give the rand another boost while dollar traders are busy eating Turkey. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Of course, when it rains it pours, and South Africa is also at risk for a further credit downgrade. Last year, the country lost its investment grade ratings with major credit ratings firms, putting it at risk to get kicked out of certain indexes. Having investors turn their back on South African assets would spark a selloff.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Since then, former President Jacob Zuma \\u2014 not the market\\u2019s favorite due to his penchant for public spending and corruption allegations \\u2014 was replaced by market and reform-friendlyCyril Ramaphosa. But a general election is scheduled for next year and the economy looks shaky.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The iShares MSCI South Africa EZA, +2.14% \\u00a0was up 2.2% on Wednesday, while still looking at a more than 25% drop in the year so far. The FTSE/JSE Large Cap Index J205, +0.61% \\u00a0finished Wednesday\\u2019s session up 0.6% but is down nearly 14% this year.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Providing critical information for the U.S. trading day. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Need to Know newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Anneken Tappe is a markets reporter for MarketWatch. She is based in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(199,'MarketWatch','Lowes completes business review and the verdict is: There are a lot of problems','Tonya Garcia','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:41 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/MG/MW-GY858_lowes__20181120143613_MG.jpg?uuid=8a628254-ecfb-11e8-83db-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Among the many announcements Lowe\\u2019s Corp. made with its third-quarter earnings, Chief Executive Marvin Ellison said the home repair retailer \\u201csubstantially completed\\u201d a review of the business, and then listed all of the problems facing the company.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201c[O]ut-of-stocks continue to pressure sales,\\u201d Ellison said on the Tuesday earnings call, according to a FactSet transcript. \\u201c[O]ur inefficient reset process continued to create disruption in our stores and contributed to out-of-stocks. In fact, all of our categories with negative comps, millwork, paint, fashion fixtures and flooring, were pressured by poorly-executed resets.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"And that\\u2019s not all.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201c[O]ur store processes are too complex, our labor management system is primitive, and our associates are burdened with too many tasks,\\u201d Ellison said. \\u201cThese distractions are preventing our associates from spending adequate time with the customer to provide assistance.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Red Tuesday for retailers, as Target\\u2019s stock suffers worst stretch since the financial crisis \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Also affecting customer service are the complications in the project specialist and installation business.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Lowe\\u2019s LOW, +2.68% shares fell 5.7% in Tuesday trading after the company reported 1.5% same-store sales growth, below the FactSet consensus for 2.8% growth. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Optimistically, Ellison said the company has plans for correcting the issues.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"He\\u2019s not the only one who\\u2019s upbeat.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWhile disappointing Q3 results reinforce the view that considerable issues remain, we are still encouraged that the new leadership is setting the stage for a multi-year turnaround,\\u201d wrote Wells Fargo analysts led by Zachary Fadem. \\u201cThus, we are reducing our price target to $105 [from $125] accordingly, but continue to view Lowe\\u2019s among the most compelling turnaround opportunities in retail, and see potential improving as quickly as FY19.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Wells Fargo rates Lowe\\u2019s shares outperform.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" See: Target shares take a beating after investments take a toll on margins \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Lowe\\u2019s also said it would be exiting the Mexican market, its contracting service, Alacrity Renovation Services, and the Iris Smart Home business in the U.S.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This after the company announced that it would be shuttering dozens of underperforming stores, including 20 in the U.S.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Lowe\\u2019s latest store closures aren\\u2019t the first in Marvin Ellison\\u2019s short CEO tenure, and might not be the last \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWhile these actions reflect a sizeable amount of portfolio changes within a short time period, they appear directly in line (at least in our view) with new CEO Marvin Ellison\\u2019s desire to drive increased focus on its core home improvement business and improve profitability (which is well below its primary competitor),\\u201d wrote Raymond James analysts in a note.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Lowe\\u2019s primary competitor is Home Depot Inc. HD, +0.74% which reported third-quarter sales of $26.3 billion and same-store sales growth of 4.8%.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Raymond James rates Lowe\\u2019s stock outperform.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Lowe\\u2019s shares are down 4.7% for the year to date while the S&P 500 index SPX, +0.88% \\u00a0 is down 0.3% for the period.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Tonya Garcia is a MarketWatch reporter covering retail and consumer-oriented companies. You can follow her on Twitter @tgarcianyc. She is based in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(200,'MarketWatch','Opinion: Why the bad news on Apple keeps on coming','Mark Hulbert','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:28 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/08/01/Photos/ZH/MW-GN621_rotten_20180801170928_ZH.jpg?uuid=2d3beef4-95cf-11e8-9dab-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"It\\u2019s not just your perception that Apple can\\u2019t catch a break in this unforgiving market. It really has been the case that bad news has kept coming \\u2014 and coming.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If history is any guide, this stream of bad news is likely to continue before the outlook for Apple AAPL, +0.66% \\u00a0 turns up. That\\u2019s because analyst revisions tend to come in waves. A downward revision is more likely than not to be followed by another downward revision \\u2014 and vice versa. (See accompanying chart.)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Investors who pay attention to analyst behavior caution against being trigger-happy with buy orders. They instead suggest waiting until analyst revisions start turning back up. Though such caution doesn\\u2019t always pay off, it often does. Consider a column on this subject that I wrote late last July about Facebook FB, +2.57% \\u00a0, headlined \\u201cWatch out for analysts\\u2019 avalanche of price-target cuts on Facebook\\u2019s stock.\\u201d Facebook\\u2019s stock had already dropped more than $40 when that column appeared; since then it has dropped another $40.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Why do analyst revisions tend to come in waves? Researchers have identified several factors:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The net impact of these various factors? One widely-cited academic study found that analyst forecasts typically reflect just 66% of the information that the market itself has already taken into account.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This idiosyncrasy of analyst behavior would be of little more than academic interest if it didn\\u2019t have further consequences of its own. But it does: When analysts do get around to downgrading their forecasts, their actions typically cause the stock\\u2019s price to fall even further. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Another consequence is that downtrends often last longer, and cause stocks to decline further, than they would otherwise. A reverse \\u201cupward spiral\\u201d works when a stock is an uptrend.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"One thing that this focus on analyst behavior doesn\\u2019t help us do is determine when Apple\\u2019s downward spiral will come to an end. But you don\\u2019t necessarily need to engage in that guessing game. Instead, watch and wait until the analyst downgrade wave begins to turn into an upgrade wave.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It will happen eventually, even if many beleaguered Apple investors have already given up and dumped their shares.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" For more information, including descriptions of the Hulbert Sentiment Indices, go to The Hulbert Financial Digest or email mark@hulbertratings.com . \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read:\\u00a0 Ray Dalio says it\\u2019s just like the 1930s for investors right now\\u2019 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Mark Hulbert has been tracking the advice of more than 160 financial newsletters since 1980. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(201,'MarketWatch','Opinion: Santa Claus Rally is just another Christmas story','Mark Hulbert','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:27 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2017/12/28/Photos/ZH/MW-GA837_santa__20171228101532_ZH.jpg?uuid=f224c882-ebe1-11e7-b229-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Can Santa Claus save this stock market? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Many are certainly hoping so, since nothing else appears able to stem the market\\u2019s carnage. The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.81% \\u00a0fell sharply again on Monday, shedding nearly 400 points.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Its doubtful that even Santa can help. An analysis of the past century reveals that the stock market in the weeks prior to Christmas is no more likely to rally than at other times of the year.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"To be sure, hardly any of the many advisers and commentators who base their hopes on a Santa Claus Rally ever bother to define exactly when it begins and ends. But, according to Google Trends, references to it begin to pick up every year around Thanksgiving and reach a peak around Christmas. So, for purposes of subjecting the Santa Claus Rally to statistical scrutiny, I am measuring it as the gain from where the stock market closes on the Wednesday prior to Thanksgiving to its highest close between then and the end of December.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"To illustrate, consider last year. The Dow closed at 23,516.18 on the Wednesday before Thanksgiving, and between then and the end of 2017 its highest close was 24,837.51 \\u2014 5.6% higher. That represents the maximum rally potential for the Santa Claus Rally period for a trader with perfect timing.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A 5.6% one-month gain certainly appears mouthwatering. But how does it compare to the other months\\u2019 rally potential?\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"To find out, I calculated a comparable gain for each other month. Specifically, for each month I measured the Dow\\u2019s gain from its fourth Thursday (analogous to Thanksgiving) to its highest close in the subsequent month. Each month\\u2019s average since 1896 (when the Dow was created) is plotted in the accompanying chart.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Notice that there is nothing special about the period that begins this week and lasts until Christmas, with an average rally potential of 3.42%. In fact, it is below average. There are no fewer than seven other months with rally potentials that are larger; the average rally potential for all 11 other months is 3.74%, or 0.3 percentage points greater than the Santa Claus Rally.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Note carefully that none of the differences in the chart is significant at the 95% confidence level that statisticians often use when assessing whether a pattern is genuine. So you shouldn\\u2019t conclude from the chart that there is now a reason to avoid the Santa Claus Rally period.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Instead, the proper conclusion is to ignore any arguments based on an alleged Santa Claus Rally. And if you want to have some fun at Thanksgiving dinner, ask anyone who mentions such a Rally to define it and defend it.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" For more information, including descriptions of the Hulbert Sentiment Indices, go to The Hulbert Financial Digest or email mark@hulbertratings.com . \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u00a0\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Mark Hulbert has been tracking the advice of more than 160 financial newsletters since 1980. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(202,'MarketWatch','Opinion: How to protect your money like the Forbes 400-richest Americans','Mark Hulbert','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:26 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2017/12/04/Photos/ZH/MW-FZ508_safe_m_20171204100200_ZH.jpg?uuid=143cedfa-d904-11e7-81b6-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Want to invest like the 400 richest Americans? Of course you do. Their average net worth is $7.2 billion, according to Forbes Magazine.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But that doesn\\u2019t mean getting shoot-the-lights out returns. In fact, only a handful of those on the Forbes list got there through investing. They instead made their fortunes elsewhere, and then went to Wall Street in an effort to preserve the purchasing power of their wealth.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Indeed, outperforming the 400 richest Americans over the past year wasn\\u2019t particularly difficult. Between Sep. 22, 2017 (the data cutoff for Forbes\\u2019 list last year) and Sep. 7 of this year (the cutoff for this year\\u2019s list), the net worth of those on this year\\u2019s Forbes 400 list grew by 7%. The S&P 500 SPX, +0.93% meanwhile,\\u00a0more than doubled that return, gaining 14.8% over the same period.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Even this 7% average gain overstates the case, since it reflects the increase among those on 2018\\u2019s list. Fifteen members of 2017\\u2019s list didn\\u2019t perform well enough over the subsequent 12 months to be in the top 400, and including their returns would no doubt bring the average down. (Forbes doesn\\u2019t report that figure.)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"To put the Forbes 400\\u2019s average gain into further perspective, consider that the average investment newsletter portfolio monitored by my Hulbert Financial Digest did even better, gaining 8.1%. (See accompanying chart.)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"To be sure, it\\u2019s unrealistic to expect any group of advisers to hit a home run every year. So you could dismiss this result over the last year as little more than the exception that proves the rule. But my eyeballing of past Forbes 400 lists suggests to me that the last year\\u2019s experience is not atypical.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The key is to understand what\\u2019s realistic through investing. Na\\u00efve investors mistakenly believe that the super-wealthy are bigger than life, possessing some magical sauce that is the secret to their investment success. And though the 400 individuals on the Forbes list may well be bigger than life in other ways, there is no magic to what they achieve through their investments.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If there is any investment magic, it\\u2019s that the wealthy have learned to be realistic about what\\u2019s attainable and so do not incur exorbitant investment risks.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Another way of understanding the investment significance of the Forbes 400 list is to imagine what your rate of return would need to be to make it onto the list at age 65, assuming you started at age 30 with $1 million. The net worth of the individual in 400th place on the latest list is $2.1 billion, and your investment return would need to be 24.4% annualized to turn $1 million into $2.1 billion over a 35-year period.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I can confidently say that no one has produced that return over a 35-year period. Consider Warren Buffett\\u2019s performance; he of course is CEO of Berkshire Hathaway BRK.A, +1.03% BRK.B, +1.00% \\u00a0and widely considered to be the most successful investor alive. Over the last 35 years, Berkshire Hathaway\\u2019s net asset value has appreciated at a 17.6% annualized rate.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The bottom line? You can invest like the 400 richest Americans. All you need to do is refocus your investment efforts on preserving the purchasing power of your portfolio over long periods.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" For more information, including descriptions of the Hulbert Sentiment Indices, go to The Hulbert Financial Digest or email mark@hulbertratings.com . \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Ray Dalio says it\\u2019s just like the 1930s for investors right now\\u2019 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Mark Hulbert has been tracking the advice of more than 160 financial newsletters since 1980. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(203,'MarketWatch','The market right now doesnt care how fantastic your stocks are','Vitaliy Katsenelson','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:25 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2017/06/15/Photos/ZH/MW-FO602_garbag_20170615173334_ZH.jpg?uuid=4940ce46-5212-11e7-9008-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"The Roman philosopher Seneca wasn\\u2019t talking about the stock market when he wrote that \\u201cTime discovers truth,\\u201d but he could have been. In the long run a stock price will reflect a company\\u2019s (true) intrinsic value. In the short run the pricing is basically random. Here are two real-life examples.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Let\\u2019s say you had the smarts to buy Microsoft MSFT, +2.32% \\u00a0in November 1992. It would have been a brilliant decision in the long run \\u2014 the software giant\\u2019s stock has gone up manyfold since. But nine months later, in August 1993, that call did not look so brilliant: Microsoft shares had declined 25% in less than a year. In fact, it would have taken you 18 months, until May 1994, for this purchase to break even. Eighteen months of dumbness?\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In the early 1990s, the PC industry was still in its infancy. Microsoft\\u2019s DOS and Windows operating systems were de facto standards. Outside of Apple AAPL, +0.68% \\u00a0Macs and a tiny fraction of IBM, +1.86% \\u00a0computers, every computer came preinstalled with DOS and Windows. Microsoft had a pristine balance sheet and a brilliant co-founder and CEO in Bill Gates who would turn mountains upside-down to make sure the company succeeded. The above sentence is infested with hindsight \\u2014 after all, that was almost 30 years ago. But Microsoft clearly had an incredible moat, which became wider with every new PC sold and every new software program written to run on Windows.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Here is another example: GoPro GPRO, +2.86% \\u00a0 is a maker of video cameras used by surfers, skiers, and other extreme sports enthusiasts. If you had bought the stock soon after it went public, in 2014, you would have paid $40 a share for a $5.5 billion\\u2013market-cap company earning about $100 million a year \\u2014 a price-earnings ratio of about 55. Your impatience would, however, have been rewarded: The stock more than doubled in just a few short months, hitting $90.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Would it have been a good decision to buy GoPro? The company makes a great product \\u2014 I own one. But GoPro has no protective \\u201cmoat\\u201d around its business. None. Most components that go into its cameras are commodities. There are no barriers to entry into the specialized video camera segment. Most important, there are no switching costs for consumers. Investors who bought GoPro after its IPO paid a huge premium for the promise of much higher earnings from a company that might or might not be around five years later.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"What is even more interesting is that some of those buyers were then selling to even bigger fools who bought at double the price a few months later. GoPro was a momentum stock that was riding a wave about to break. Fast-forward a few years and GoPro sales have been on decline; nowadays its stock trades below $6.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"These two examples bring us to the nontrivial topics of complex systems and nonlinearity. My favorite thinker, Nassim Taleb, wrote the following in his book\\u00a0\\u201cAntifragile: Things That Gain from Disorder\\u201d: \\u201cComplex systems are full of interdependencies \\u2014 hard to detect \\u2014 and nonlinear responses.\\u00a0Nonlinear\\u00a0means that when you double the dose of, say, a medication, or when you double the number of employees in a factory, you don\\u2019t get twice the initial effect, but rather a lot more or a lot less.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The stock market is a complex system where in the short term there are few if any interdependencies between decisions and outcomes. In the short run, stock prices are driven by thousands of random variables. Stock market participants have different risk tolerances and emotional aptitudes, and diverse time horizons ranging from milliseconds (for high-speed traders) to years (for long-term investors).\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In other words, predicting where a stock price will be in a day, a month or even a year is not much different from prognosticating whether the ball on a roulette wheel will land on red or black. In the longer run, good decisions should pay off because fundamentals will shine through \\u2014 as was the case with buying Microsoft in 1992 and not buying GoPro in 2014. But in the short run there is no correlation between good decisions and results. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Whenever you look at your portfolio, think of Microsoft and GoPro. The performance of your stocks in the short run tells you absolutely nothing about what you own or about the quality of your decisions. You may own a portfolio of Microsofts, and its value is going down because at this juncture the market doesn\\u2019t care about Microsofts. Or maybe you stuffed your retirement fund with overpriced fads that may not be around a year from now. But in the longer run, remember what Seneca knew: Time discovers truth.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" So, how does one invest in this overvalued market? Our strategy is spelled out\\u00a0in this fairly lengthy\\u00a0article. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Vitaliy N. Katsenelson is chief investment officer at\\u00a0Investment Management Associates\\u00a0in Denver, Colo. He is the author of\\u00a0\\u201cActive Value Investing\\u201d\\u00a0(Wiley) and\\u00a0\\u201cThe Little Book of Sideways Markets\\u201d\\u00a0(Wiley). \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: These people have been buying up stocks faster than anyone since 1989 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also: Hedge-fund boss who predicted \\u201887 crash says get ready for some \\u2018really scary moments\\u2019 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Vitaliy Katsenelson is chief investment officer at\\u00a0Investment Management Associates\\u00a0in Denver, Colo. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(204,'MarketWatch','Doing a background check on your financial adviser is getting tougher','Jean Eaglesham','Published: Nov 20, 2018 10:01 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY832_fbiage_20181120095516_ZH.jpg?uuid=4abf1c4c-ecd4-11e8-b759-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Thousands of brokers have scrubbed their records clean of complaints by customers and employers, allowing them to hide information from potential investors, according to a new study.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"These brokers were more likely than other ones to receive additional complaints or other allegations of misconduct after their records were cleaned, according to the academic paper, which analyzed public regulatory records from 2007 to 2016.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The scrubbing process, known as expungement, is overseen by the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority, the industry-funded brokerage regulator. Under Finra rules, arbitrators are expected to allow a record to be deleted from the public \\u201cBrokerCheck\\u201d website only if an allegation against a broker is factually impossible, \\u201cclearly erroneous\\u201d or the broker wasn\\u2019t involved in an alleged misconduct.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Expungement is meant to be a rare event, regulators say. But the study, which analyzed BrokerCheck records and other regulatory information, found that arbitrators granted requests nearly 70% of the time.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" See an expanded version of this story at WSJ.com. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(205,'MarketWatch','Existing-home sales stage their first increase in six months in October','Andrea Riquier','Published: Nov 21, 2018 11:44 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/MG/MW-GY831_realto_20181120095515_MG.jpg?uuid=4a61e8ce-ecd4-11e8-8957-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" The numbers: Existing-home sales ran at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.22 million in October, the National Association of Realtors said Wednesday. That was up 1.4% for the month, marking the first monthly increase in six months.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What happened: Sales of previously owned homes finally perked up, beating the MarketWatch consensus forecast of a 5.18 million selling pace. Still, October\\u2019s rate of sales was 5.1% lower than a year ago. The median sales price in October was $255,400, up 3.8% versus a year ago, one of the lowest yearly increases in a long time. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Homes stayed on the market an average of 33 days in October, and first-time buyers made up 31% of all purchases, still below the long-term average of 40%. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Sales in the Northeast increased 1.5%, while sales in the South rose 1.9%. In the West, sales jumped 2.8%. The Midwest was the only region to pull back in October, with a 0.8% decline. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Big picture: At the current pace of sales, it would take 4.3 months to exhaust available supply, a tick lower than the 4.4 months\\u2019 worth of unsold inventory notched last month, but still better than the conditions that likely caused many buyers to give up and exit the market late last year and early in 2018. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For some context, the long-term average that\\u2019s considered a sign of a \\u201cbalanced\\u201d market is six months\\u2019 worth of inventory; in February, there were 3.4 months\\u2019 worth of unsold homes. With so much demand, it\\u2019s not clear that any easing of the supply crunch won\\u2019t be met with a massive wave of buying that could even push prices to reaccelerate. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also read: This chart shows the haves and have-nots of the housing market, and it\\u2019s getting worse \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What they\\u2019re saying: \\u201cDon\\u2019t get me wrong; I\\u2019m thankful for positive economic data but I wouldn\\u2019t mind another helping,\\u201d said Jennifer Lee, senior economist for BMO Capital Markets. Even though the details of the October report were better, they still weren\\u2019t great, Lee noted.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cPrices are not rising as quickly as they once were but they are rising (~4% y/y) and, coupled with climbing interest rates, are hurting affordability.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Stephens analyst John Campbell, who\\u2019s been a notable bull on housing stocks like Realogy RLGY, +1.07% \\u00a0 and Zillow ZG, +2.40% \\u00a0, wrote the following on Wednesday: \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWhile market trends remain challenged, we do think that the October existing-home sales clip represents some stabilization of trends and, perhaps, offers up some hope for the start of a modest recovery. We remain upbeat on several of our housing-related stocks given our view that estimates have reset/baked in current conditions and valuations remain very attractive relative to historical averages.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Market reaction: The 10-year U.S. Treasury note TMUBMUSD10Y, +0.24% \\u00a0 has rallied over the past week, offering a brief respite to anyone applying for a mortgage. But if global stock markets continue to churn, that may take a toll on Americans\\u2019 confidence and make them less likely to make a major purchase like a home. The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.80% \\u00a0 is down about 1% in the year-to-date, but that measurement masks a lot of volatility. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: As the housing market stagnates, American homeowners are staying put for the longest stretches ever \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Andrea Riquier reports on housing and banking from MarketWatch\'s New York newsroom. Follow her on Twitter @ARiquier. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(206,'MarketWatch','U.S. durable-goods orders sink 4.4% in October and business investment is flat','Jeffry Bartash','Published: Nov 21, 2018 11:04 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/03/22/Photos/MG/MW-GG070_Durabl_20180322155258_MG.jpg?uuid=9ee3f380-2e0a-11e8-90fd-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" The numbers: Orders for American-made durable goods sank in October, but it was mostly due to a dropoff in demand for airplanes of all types. More notably, business investment was weak for the third month in a row. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Orders fell 4.4% to mark the biggest decline in 15 months, the government said Wednesday. Economists surveyed by MarketWatch had forecast a 3.4% decline in orders for durable goods, or products made to last at least three years.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Bookings for commercial jets slid 21.4% and they shrank 59% for fighter jets and other military aircraft. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Stripping out planes and cars, orders rose a slight 0.1%. Transportation often exaggerates the ups and downs in orders because of lumpy demand from one month to the next.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What happened: The pullback in aircraft orders was not surprising. Boeing BA, +1.51% \\u00a0 tends to receive fewer orders late in the year after a summer bonanza. Orders for defense aircraft, what\\u2019s more, posted the biggest monthly increase in September in 17 years. So a reversal was expected. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Aside from aircraft, orders also declined for machinery and primary metals.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Existing-home sales stage their first increase in six months in October \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Orders rose for computers, networking gear and electrical equipment.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The biggest takeaway from the October report was another soft reading on business investment. So-called core orders fell slightly last month following small declines in September and August. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Although the closely followed measure has risen 3.2% in the past 12 months, it was increasing at a 8% pace earlier in the year.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also Read: Huge U.S. trade deficit with China may prevent Trump and Xi from deal \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Big picture: Business investment has cooled off in the fall, adding to fresh worries about the economy. Stronger corporate spending has buoyed the economy over the past year and a half.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some economists contend the slowdown is likely to be temporary. They say companies need to invest more in equipment and automation to counter rising wages and a growing shortage of skilled workers. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Yet others suggest that businesses might be more hesitant because of a slowing global economy and rising trade tensions with China that appear to have no easy resolution.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Global growth will slow from here \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What they are saying?: \\u201cLooking ahead, we expect momentum to continue to fade as reduced tailwinds from fiscal stimulus dissipate and rising headwinds from slower global growth, reduced energy investment and heightened trade tensions start weighing on capex plans,\\u201d economists at Oxford Economics said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Market reaction: The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.83% and the S&P 500 SPX, +0.97% rose in Wednesday trades after a pair of brutal selloffs this week erased all stock-market gains for 2018. Yet a mediocre durable-goods report, an increase in jobless claims and a softer sentiment survey could limit the gains. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The 10-year Treasury yield TMUBMUSD10Y, +0.27% has retreated from a seven-year high to stand just above 3%, reflecting fresh worries about the strength of a U.S. economy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Jeffry Bartash is a reporter for MarketWatch in Washington. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(207,'MarketWatch','Jobless claims climb to 4-month high of 224,000','Jeffry Bartash','Published: Nov 21, 2018 11:01 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/MG/MW-GY867_jobles_20181120161315_MG.jpg?uuid=185d465e-ed09-11e8-b651-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" The numbers: The number of Americans who applied for unemployment benefits in the week before Thanksgiving rose to the highest level in 4\\u00bd months, potentially adding to fresh worries about the U.S. economy.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Initial jobless claims, a rough way to measure layoffs, rose by 3,000 to 224,000 in the seven days ended Nov. 17. That was well above than the 215,000 forecast of economists polled by MarketWatch.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"In an unusual twist, the prior week\\u2019s estimate of new claims was raised by 5,000 to 221,000. Rarely is the weekly number revised so sharply. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The monthly average of new claims also increased by 2,000 to 218,500.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What happened: New jobless claims hit the highest level since June 30 and broke a string of 18 straight weeks below 220,000. An official at the Labor Department could not cite any specific factors for the recent increase, though claims do get erratic during the holiday season.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Layoffs are still quite low, however.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The number of people already collecting unemployment benefits, meanwhile, dipped by 2,000 to 1.67 million. These so-called continuing claims are at the lowest level since the early 1970s.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Huge U.S. trade deficit with China may prevent Trump and Xi from year-end deal \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Big picture: The shocking decline in the stock market this weeks suggests investors are more worried about the future of the economy. The rise in jobless claims and a soft reading on business investment in October are likely to add to the worries.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By most measures, though, the economy still appears to be in good shape. The U.S. labor market is the strongest in decades and most households are in the best financial shape in years. Unless they dramatically cut spending, the economy should continue to grow well into next year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Global growth will slow from here \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What they are saying?: \\u201cBroadly, the economy remains on a solid footing in the final weeks of 2018, but some relative weakness in recent data has not been lost on investors,\\u201d said Jim Baird, chief investment officer at Plante Moran Financial Advisors\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Market reaction: The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.82% and the S&P 500 SPX, +0.96% opened higher in Wednesday trades after a pair of brutal selloffs this week erased all stock-market gains for 2018. Yet a mediocre durable-goods report, an increase in jobless claims and a softer sentiment survey could limit the gains. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The 10-year Treasury yield TMUBMUSD10Y, +0.27% has retreated from a seven-year high to stand just above 3%, reflecting fresh worries about the strength of a U.S. economy.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(208,'MarketWatch','U.S. economy still on growth path, leading indicators show, but expansion likely to moderate','Victor Reklaitis','Published: Nov 21, 2018 10:53 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY861_shoppi_20181120151434_ZH.jpg?uuid=e5ec4f2e-ed00-11e8-858d-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" The numbers: The U.S. economy remains on a growth path, according to an index that measures the nation\\u2019s economic health, though the country\\u2019s expansion is likely to moderate.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The leading economic index rose 0.1% in October after 0.6% and 0.5% gains in the prior two months, the Conference Board said Wednesday. Economists polled by FactSet had forecast a 0.1% rise.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The LEI is a weighted gauge of 10 indicators designed to signal business-cycle peaks and valleys.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What they are saying? The leading index \\u201cincreased slightly in October, and the pace of improvement slowed for the first time since May,\\u201d said Ataman Ozyildirim, economist at the board. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe index still points to robust economic growth in early 2019, but the rapid pace of growth may already have peaked. While near-term economic growth should remain strong, longer-term growth is likely to moderate to about 2.5% by mid- to late 2019,\\u201d Ozyildirim added.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What happened: Five of the 10 components of the LEI showed expansion in October, with the biggest positive contribution coming from average consumer expectations for business conditions.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The biggest negative contributors were stock prices, average weekly initial claims for unemployment insurance and building permits.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The LEI is a weighted gauge of 10 indicators designed to signal business-cycle peaks and valleys.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Big picture: The leading index is the latest in a slew of economic signposts that show growth remains steady, if perhaps a bit slower than in early 2018. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"With job openings at a record high and unemployment at a 48-year low, Americans feel secure in their jobs and have money to spend. That will keep the economy growing in the near future, even as U.S. interest rates rise.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: World\\u2019s \\u2018most competitive\\u2019 economy \\u2014 U.S. regains the crown \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Market reaction: The S&P 500 SPX, +0.91% on Wednesday was largely maintaining its early gains, but still down sharply for the holiday-shortened week. The stock-market gauge has been in a slump for the past two months, weighed down in part by forecasts that say economic growth is cooling off.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile, the 10-year Treasury note yield TMUBMUSD10Y, +0.30% rose to 3.07%. Earlier this month, the yield reached a seven-year high above 3.23% in anticipation of rising U.S. interest rates.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Jeffry Bartash contributed to this report.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Victor Reklaitis is MarketWatch\'s Money & Politics reporter and is based in Washington, D.C. Follow him on Twitter @VicRek. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(209,'MarketWatch','Richer Americans less optimistic after stock plunge, consumer sentiment poll shows','Jeffry Bartash','Published: Nov 21, 2018 10:22 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2016/11/28/Photos/OR/MW-FA904_bf_sho_20161128121149_OR.jpg?uuid=bfcaef28-b58d-11e6-bfcd-001cc448aede\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" The numbers: Most Americans are still optimistic about the U.S. economy, but a recent slide in the stock market has made wealthier household more anxious about their incomes, a survey of consumers shows. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The University of Michigan\\u2019s consumer-sentiment index fell to 97.5 in November from 98.6, according to the second and final reading for the month. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It\\u2019s the second straight decline and a bit more negative than the preliminary reading of 98.3.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Huge U.S. trade deficit with China may prevent Trump and Xi from year-end deal \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What happened: The biggest decline in sentiment occurred among the richest one-third of U.S. households. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Wealthier Americans have more money in the stock market. The recent decline in prices appears to have made them more anxious, even before the big slide this week that virtually wiped out all of 2018\\u2019s gains.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By contrast, sentiment rose sharply among Americans whose incomes put them in the bottom third of the country, the survey shows. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Existing-home sales stage their first increase in six months in October \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The 2018 elections didn\\u2019t appear to have any impact on how consumers view their well-being. Neither Democrats nor Republicans were swayed by the results. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Big picture: The shocking decline in the stock market this weeks suggests investors are more worried about the future of the economy. The rise in jobless claims and a soft reading on business investment in October are likely to add to the worries.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By most measures, though, the economy seems to be in good shape. The U.S. labor market is the strongest in decades and most households are in the best financial shape in years. Falling gas prices are also offering a helping hand and helping to easing inflationary pressures.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If stocks keep falling, however, the optimism is sure to diminish. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: There\\u2019s still more jobs available than unemployed Americans \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" What they are saying? \\u201cWhile there is no reason to anticipate a sudden change in interest rate expectations in the net few months, it is still an important task for the Federal Reserve to avoid hitting the threshold that causes widespread postponement of purchases,\\u201d said Richard Curtin, chief economist of the survey.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Market reaction: The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.71% and the S&P 500 SPX, +0.90% opened higher in Wednesday trades after a pair of brutal selloffs this week erased all stock-market gains for 2018. Yet a mediocre durable-goods report, an increase in jobless claims and a softer sentiment survey could limit the gains. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The 10-year Treasury yield TMUBMUSD10Y, +0.21% has retreated from a seven-year high to stand just above 3%, reflecting fresh worries about the strength of a U.S. economy.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Jeffry Bartash is a reporter for MarketWatch in Washington. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(210,'MarketWatch','Mississippi senator apologies for hanging remark | Navarro reportedly will be excluded from Trump-Xi event','Victor Reklaitis','Published: Nov 21, 2018 9:32 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/12/Photos/ZH/MW-GY348_hyde_s_20181112093814_ZH.jpg?uuid=9649f5a8-e688-11e8-880f-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" Mississippi senator facing runoff apologizes for joke about public hanging: Sen. Cindy Hyde-Smith, a Mississippi Republican, has apologized after a video surfaced showing her praising someone by saying: \\u201cIf he invited me to a public hanging, I\\u2019d be on the front row.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cFor anyone that was offended by my comments, I certainly apologize. There was no ill will,\\u201d she said during a debate Tuesday night ahead of a runoff election on Nov. 27. She also accused her opponents of using her words as a \\u201cpolitical weapon,\\u201d a Wall Street Journal report noted.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Mike Espy, her Democratic opponent, responded during the debate that \\u201cno one twisted your comments,\\u201d adding: \\u201cI don\\u2019t know what\\u2019s in your heart but we all know what came out of your mouth.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Hyde-Smith has faced a backlash after her comments went viral, with Walmart Inc. WMT, -0.10% asking for its campaign donation back.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Navarro reportedly will be excluded from Trump-Xi event: Peter Navarro, the Trump adviser known for his hawkish views on China, will not take part in a dinner meeting between the president and his Chinese counterpart Xi Jinping in Argentina on Dec. 1, according to a South China Morning Post report citing a source with knowledge of the matter.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Trump administration\\u2019s decision to exclude Navarro from the event comes amid signs that both sides want to make progress on the U.S.-China trade fight, the report said. Navarro has been a key figure in the battle that has weighed on stocks worldwide VT, +1.42% \\u00a0. If his exclusion is confirmed, it is bullish for equities, said Ole Hansen, a Saxo Bank strategist, in a tweet.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Meet Peter Navarro, the man who pushed Gary Cohn out of the White House \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Graham, other Republicans disagree with Trump\\u2019s move to stand with Saudis: Sen. Lindsey Graham, who is close to President Donald Trump, is disagreeing with the president\\u2019s decision not to further punish Saudi Arabia over the death of Washington Post columnist Jamal Khashoggi, an Associated Press report said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The South Carolina Republican sided with Sen. Rand Paul, a Kentucky Republican, and Democratic colleagues in Congress in denouncing the president\\u2019s move to stand with the Saudis, saying its not in U.S. national security interests to \\u201clook the other way when it comes to the brutal murder\\u201d of the Saudi citizen who lived in the U.S.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Sens. Bob Corker, a Tennessee Republican, and Bob Menendez, a New Jersey Democrat, have written a letter to Trump on Tuesday, asking for an investigation under the Global Magnitsky Human Rights Accountability Act, the AP report added. The Senate Foreign Relations Committee\\u2019s chairman and ranking member are demanding the Trump administration \\u201cmake a determination\\u201d about whether Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman was responsible for the killing.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Utah GOP Rep. Mia Love reportedly fails to win re-election: Rep. Mia Love, a Utah Republican, has become the latest GOP incumbent to fall in the midterm election, according to multiple published reports. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Ben McAdams, a Democratic mayor of Salt Lake County, defeated Love by fewer than 700 votes in a back and forth race that took two weeks to sort out in deep-red Utah, a CBS News report said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Trump had chided Love on the morning after Election Day for losing, but the result just became official this week, a USA Today story said. Love, who was the first black Republican woman elected to Congress, has said she was calling McAdams, but didn\\u2019t indicate if she would concede or congratulate him.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Victor Reklaitis is MarketWatch\'s Money & Politics reporter and is based in Washington, D.C. Follow him on Twitter @VicRek. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(211,'MarketWatch','5 ways to save money on Thanksgiving dinner (and get a free turkey)','Jacob Passy','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:39 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/19/Photos/ZH/MW-GY788_thanks_20181119162406_ZH.jpg?uuid=720b8756-ec41-11e8-89e1-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"That plate of turkey, mashed potatoes, stuffing, green-bean casserole, cranberry sauce and pumpkin pie doesn\\u2019t come cheap.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"More than one in four hosts say that Thanksgiving represents a financial strain, according to a survey by LendingTree TREE, +1.58% That shouldn\\u2019t come as a surprise given how expensive hosting a feast for the annual holiday can be. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"On average, Americans said they expect to spend $334 to host 11 people this year, including $251 on food and $83 for housewares. Given that the average consumer is expected to spend more than $1,000 during the holiday season on gifts, d\\u00e9cor and food, Thanksgiving can be a budget-buster. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: 7 things NOT to buy on Cyber Monday \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Here are some tips from savings experts on how to make the holiday less of a financial strain:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Create a menu so you don\\u2019t overshop. Check out promotional giveaways at grocery stores, said Mark Hamrick, senior economic analyst at personal-finance website Bankrate. Some stores, including ShopRite, gift shoppers a free turkey if they spend enough money by a certain date. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Consider making as many dishes from scratch as possible. While premade sides like mashed potatoes or green bean casserole can be time savers, they can quickly blow past one\\u2019s budget. Canned pumpkin is cheaper than fresh, and it can be just as tasty when used for a pie.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Supermarket circulars will promise discounts on popular ingredients like cranberries or sweet potatoes, and that will include name brands. Don\\u2019t be afraid of going generic. \\u201cIt\\u2019s likely the store brand is cheaper,\\u201d said Jen Smith, personal-finance expert at the savings website The Penny Hoarder.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Turkey, the centerpiece on most Thanksgiving tables, accounts for nearly half of the average family\\u2019s food-related costs on Thanksgiving, according to the American Farm Bureau Federation. The average price of a turkey fell 3% from last year to roughly $1.36 per pound for a 16-pound bird. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIf you are having a smaller gathering of, say, six or fewer people, you are probably better off buying turkey breasts or legs instead of a whole turkey,\\u201d said Jon Lal, founder and CEO of coupons and cash-back website BeFrugal. (The average turkey costs around $21.71.)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Another option for people who need to save a few bucks: Cook a whole chicken instead. In New York, a whole chicken costs as little as 99 cents per pound, while a whole turkey may cost double that, according to prices available on Instacart.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read more: These stores will have the biggest bargains on Black Friday \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Along similar lines, Thanksgiving hosts shouldn\\u2019t go into the holiday with leftovers in mind. While leftovers help to spread out the cost of the Thanksgiving meal, they also run the risk of going to waste if they\\u2019re not eaten in time. One solution: Limit the number of sides and desserts. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cYou don\\u2019t have to have the entire gamut to have a lavish Thanksgiving,\\u201d Smith said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This is especially true for the perennial host. \\u201cIf you are not taking turns hosting, and find yourself always hosting Thanksgiving dinner, a potluck might be a good way to share the hosting responsibility,\\u201d Lal said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Make it a family affair, even among friends. Splitting up the food means that guests can spend as little or as much as they can afford. The potluck does not need to be limited to food. Beverages, paper plates and decorations can also split up among guests. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Jacob Passy is a personal-finance reporter for MarketWatch and is based in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(212,'MarketWatch','Opinion: Black Friday: The deeper reason why some of us love it and others positively loathe it','Michael Breazeale','Published: Nov 21, 2018 8:04 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/19/Photos/ZH/MW-GY785_black__20181119154524_ZH.jpg?uuid=09eb8fea-ec3c-11e8-a9c2-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"If the thought of taking part in the annual ritual of Black Friday gives you cold chills rather than a rush of excitement, you\\u2019re not alone. For every avid bargain hunter who plans for the day as if training for a marathon, there\\u2019s someone else who stays home, secure in the knowledge that no one will trample them, shove them or invade their personal space just to get this season\\u2019s hottest deals.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It\\u2019s not just a lack of appreciation for bargains that drives this disconnect. Psychology research indicates that several factors determine which side of the shop-\\u2018til-you-drop divide you land on. Some people just aren\\u2019t wired to enjoy the more social aspects of shopping.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Psychology researchers divide the world into two groups: those who tend to focus more on achieving tasks versus those who focus more on making connections with others. This idea is encapsulated in what\\u2019s known as goal theory.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Task-oriented shoppers typically focus on finding the things they need as quickly as possible and with the least amount of effort. Socially oriented shoppers, on the other hand, enjoy the presence of others while they shop.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"There is experimental evidence that task-oriented shoppers are more likely to find even a handful of other shoppers nearby to be a crowd and an obstacle to a successful shopping trip. The same research suggests that social shoppers are actually energized by the presence of other consumers. These folks enjoy the experience more when there are others nearby, even if they don\\u2019t directly interact.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Another aspect of this shopping divide comes down to individual expectations regarding personal space. Psychology researchers talk about this preference in what they call field theory. If you\\u2019ve ever been bothered by a \\u201cclose-talker\\u201d who leans in too close or touches your arm as they tell you a story, then you are likely someone who requires a little more personal space than that storyteller does.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The presence of other shoppers in a store is psychologically arousing for people on both ends of the personal space spectrum, but in different ways. People who don\\u2019t require much personal space feel excitement when others are around. That same arousal feels instead like stress to the person who requires a little more space to call their own. And stress is something everyone tries to minimize. Almost everything we do as consumers is an attempt to reduce stress \\u2014 from eating when we feel hungry to buying that bigger TV you just have to have.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Taken together, these two theories explain a lot about the way you feel about Black Friday-style shopping.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The five-day period that starts on Thanksgiving Day and ends on Cyber Monday will bring about two-thirds of Americans out to shop. Black Friday remains the busiest shopping day of the year, with roughly half Americans leaving their homes to take part in this consumer ritual.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If you read those statistics and think, \\u201cBring it on!\\u201d then you are likely a social shopper who enjoys the thrill of the hunt and finds crowds energizing.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If instead, you react to those numbers by booking a root canal so you don\\u2019t have to hit the stores, then you\\u2019re more likely a task-oriented shopper who prefers to get in and get out with the items you need. You are also more likely to be annoyed by the physical closeness of strangers that is a hallmark of competitive shopping. But don\\u2019t call the dentist just yet \\u2014 there may still be ways for you to comfortably participate in Black Friday and its bargains.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"First, make a list of everyone for whom you would like to find a gift. Then do your research on the sales that might help you achieve your goals. Both of those tasks should appeal to the need for organization that task-oriented shoppers tend to exhibit.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Next, recognize that the majority of Black Friday devotees are going for the big bargains first, and that means that they\\u2019ll head for the big box and department stores. Instead make your first stops the local boutiques and smaller shops that won\\u2019t get as much traffic early in the day.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By the time you\\u2019ve taken care of those items on your list, the larger stores will begin to clear out and you can head in. Try avoiding malls and go where you can park close to the store you actually want to visit. Doing this will allow you to feel some degree of control and alleviate some of the stress you feel when you don\\u2019t have direction.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"By the end of the day, you can check some things off your shopping list and feel good about the bargains you were able to find, all while maintaining your sanity.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"And if you\\u2019ve read this far merely to better understand why your significant other doesn\\u2019t want to join you on this most special of consumer holidays, just acknowledge your psychological differences. You go ahead and tackle Black Friday with the enthusiasm of a natural-born social shopper. Don\\u2019t worry about those who resist \\u2014 they can always snag Cyber Monday bargains from the comfort of home.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Michael Breazeale is an associate professor of marketing at Mississippi State University. This was first published on The Conversation \\u2014 \\u201cThe psychological differences between those who love and those who loathe Black Friday shopping.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Love or loathe it, will you be shopping on Black Friday?\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(213,'MarketWatch','Follow these credit-card hacks to rack up major savings while holiday shopping','Jacob Passy','Published: Nov 21, 2018 6:36 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY873_money1_20181120182944_ZH.jpg?uuid=29539b12-ed1c-11e8-9407-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Last year, Americans racked up more than $1,000 in debt during the Christmas season, a 5% increase from the year prior, and this year looks to be no different. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But savvy consumers who employ the right credit-card strategy stand to save big bucks. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIf you\\u2019re worried about overspending, stick to cash or debit so you can\\u2019t go over budget,\\u201d said Ted Rossman, industry analyst at CreditCards.com. \\u201cFor card holders who can pay their balances in full and avoid interest, credit cards are an awesome tool to earn extra money around the holidays via cash back and/or travel rewards.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Here are some tips on how to use credit cards wisely this holiday season:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read more: 7 things NOT to buy on Cyber Monday \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Many credit cards come with introductory offers that will grant new card holders extra rewards points or cash back if they spend a certain amount of money in the first three months. This is the \\u201cmost lucrative\\u201d way to take advantage of holiday spending, said Brian Karimzad, co-founder of personal-finance website MagnifyMoney TREE, +1.64% \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The relaunched Capital One Venture card COF, +1.41% \\u00a0currently comes with a sign-up bonus of 75,000 additional miles if new card holders spend $3,000 in the first three months. Similarly, consumers can earn a 70,000-mile sign-up bonus if they spend $5,000 in the first 90 days after opening the Barclaycard Arrival Plus World Elite Mastercard MA, +1.17% \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some credit cards\\u2019 rewards programs are structured so that they rotate rewards.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Discover it Card DFS, +1.70% \\u00a0is currently offering 5% back on Amazon AMZN, +2.01% \\u00a0purchases and spending at wholesale clubs such as Costco COST, -0.59% Sam\\u2019s Club WMT, +0.01% \\u00a0and BJ\\u2019s Wholesale BJ, +11.25% (Discover cards can only be used for online purchases with Costco.) Similarly, the Chase Freedom card is offering 5% back at wholesale clubs and department stores such as Macy\\u2019s M, +2.16% \\u00a0and JCPenney\\u2019s JCP, +1.16% \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Therefore, people who exclusively shop at those retailers with these two cards stand to save an additional 5% on all their purchases in the form of cash back. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Hackers will impersonate your favorite brands this holiday season \\u2014 tips for safe shopping \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"When shopping online, pair credit-card rewards with online rebates through companies like Ebates to get extra savings, Karimzad said. To find the best rebate program, check out rebate portals such as Evreward.com and Cashback Monitor. By punching in the name of a retailer, compare the savings rates offered by different rebate programs.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Similarly, explore whether your credit-card issuer has its own shopping portal, Rossman said. \\u201cThat simple extra step which takes a few seconds can earn you a lot of extra cash back, anywhere from 2% to about 30% extra, depending on the issuer and the merchant,\\u201d he said. Chase JPM, +0.42% Citi C, +1.46% Barclays BCS, +3.71% \\u00a0and Wells Fargo WFC, +0.15% \\u00a0all offer these.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some people will save up their rewards points or airline miles over the course of the year to convert into gift cards for holiday gifts come Christmastime. That could be a mistake. Take the American Express Membership Rewards AXP, +1.02% \\u00a0program: Members can get a $100 Nike NKE, +1.48% \\u00a0gift card for 10,000 points, since one point is equal to one cent. But it takes the same amount in points to get a Walmart gift card worth only $70.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt\\u2019s tricky,\\u201d Karimzad said. \\u201cUsually with rewards you\\u2019re going to get the best rate by using it for travel or cash back as a statement credit.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: This is the best day to buy a Christmas tree \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Many credit-card issuers offer consumer protection guarantees that can come in very handy this time of year. Citi, for instance, offers a \\u201cPrice Rewind\\u201d policy for its credit products. That allows customers to save up to $200 per item and $1,000 total per year when retailers drop prices. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Additionally, the Citi Double Cash, Chase Ink Business, American Express Gold and United MileagePlus Club UAL, +1.35% \\u00a0 cards all come with competitive purchase protection plans, which covers up to $10,000 in losses if a recent purchase is broken or stolen.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"While it\\u2019s tempting to earn as much in rewards points or miles as possible this time of year, be careful about overspending. \\u201cYour utilization ratio \\u2014 how much you owe over your available credit \\u2014 is a big part of your credit score, so avoid carrying high balances relative to your credit limits,\\u201d said Adam West, credit strategist at Cardrates.com.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Especially for a first-time credit-card gamer, the holidays can be a dangerous time to spend significant chunks of money with a credit card. \\u201cUndisciplined spending during the holiday season can undo much or all of the financial progress you\\u2019ve made throughout the year in terms of debt repayment,\\u201d said Greg McBride, chief financial analyst at Bankrate.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It takes five years to pay off $1,000 in holiday-shopping debt if you only make the minimum monthly payment, and you will be charged more than $500 in interest. All told, that financial hit could easily outweigh the benefits derived through credit card rewards. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If debt repayment is a concern, consider the 0% interest offers for balance transfer cards that banks advertise in the New Year, Karimzad added.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Jacob Passy is a personal-finance reporter for MarketWatch and is based in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(214,'MarketWatch','7 things NOT to buy on Cyber Monday','Jacob Passy','Published: Nov 20, 2018 9:23 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2017/09/15/Photos/ZH/MW-FU385_missio_20170915103642_ZH.jpg?uuid=4aab2af2-9a23-11e7-8540-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Cyber Monday is now giving Black Friday a run for its money in terms of consumer interest, but that doesn\\u2019t mean the deals are worth shopping.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This year, Americans plan to spend $803 on average between Black Friday and Cyber Monday, an increase from $743 last year, according to a survey conducted by deals website RetailMeNot.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: These stores will have the biggest bargains on Black Friday \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"And nearly as many consumers plan to shop for holiday gifts at online-only retailers (60%) as department stores (67%), making the web-based bargains from Cyber Monday an even bigger draw. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But not all sales are created equal. Here is what experts suggest consumers avoid buying on Cyber Monday:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Small electronics, including smartphones, were No. 1 for the majority of holiday wish lists, according to RetailMeNot. But consumers hunting for a bargain on a new smartphone should either plan to shop the Black Friday sales or wait until December, said Brent Shelton, online shipping expert with PR firm Bospar. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: What tastes better \\u2014 pumpkin pie made fresh or from a can? We have the answer \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cGenerally speaking, the incentivized deals for smartphones we see on Black Friday do not carry over\\u201d to Cyber Monday, he said. Consumers may benefit from holding off until the first weekend in December, when carriers begin their final holiday sales push. Apple AAPL, +0.61% \\u00a0doesn\\u2019t discount new iPhones, but wireless companies offer deals.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Door-buster prices on 4K TVs and streaming devices are more likely to be found on Black Friday, Shelton said. But any sales that do come around on Cyber Monday won\\u2019t last long. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Smart-home devices may see major deals on Cyber Monday, but experts say consumers should still steer clear. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: 5 unpretentious ways to be an ethical traveler this holiday season \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cWhile some older versions of connected home devices will be sale-priced on Cyber Monday, buyers should keep in mind that more dated models, particularly from less established brands, may be subject to a lack of customer support and security updates in the coming years,\\u201d said Harold Li, vice president at ExpressVPN.com, a company that offers a virtual private network services. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThis is especially important for devices where security is critical, like smart speakers, smart locks, and internet-connected cameras,\\u201d he added.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" As with Black Friday, discounts for winter coats and sweaters will abound on Cyber Monday. But that doesn\\u2019t mean the deals are worth buying. The best time to buy winter clothing is in January, when retailers will reduce prices in an effort to clear shelves for the new spring clothing lines, said Phillip Dengler, co-owner of savings website BestBlackFriday.com.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" The sales on jewelry will be less sterling than clothing discounts, said Sara Skirboll, shopping and trends expert at RetailMeNot. In fact, consumers should hold off on buying those diamond earrings until the New Year. \\u201cEverything gets deeply discounted in time for Valentine\\u2019s Day, so January is going to be when you find all of those big bargains,\\u201d Skirboll said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Retailers often run out of the most popular toys and video gaming systems of the season \\u2014 such as Hatchimals and the Nintendo Switch \\u2014 so consumers may not be able to get these at a discount if they\\u2019re must-have. The best time to buy most toys though is mid-December, when stores are looking to unload remaining inventory ahead of Christmas, Dengler said. \\u201cDo not wait too long, however,\\u201d he said. \\u201cYou will see great prices after Dec. 17, but the inventory and selection may no longer be desirable.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Retailers like to hype their sales on home furnishings and d\\u00e9cor this time of year. But chances are the deals aren\\u2019t all that special. As BlackFriday.com notes, these items go on sale regularly throughout the year. So unless consumers have their heart set on a particular item, they won\\u2019t miss out on much by prioritizing other purchases come Cyber Monday.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: This father flew to Spain to buy his son a Hatchimal \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile, big-box retailers and department stores like Target TGT, +0.49% \\u00a0 or Sears SHLDQ, +4.48% \\u00a0are likely to run promotions on Black Friday for kitchen items such as stand-mixers and waffle irons. But those deals are likely to be one-day-only affairs, Shelton said.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Your friend or family member may be mulling that New Year\\u2019s resolution to get in shape \\u2014 but you\\u2019re better off waiting until January to buy them that new set of weights. People really decide to follow through on their New Year\\u2019s resolutions in January even if they have forgotten them by February. \\u201cRetailers understand that, so that\\u2019s when they\\u2019re offering their big promotions to compete and drive traffic to their stores,\\u201d Skirboll said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Jacob Passy is a personal-finance reporter for MarketWatch and is based in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(215,'MarketWatch','How to tell your in-laws to stay somewhere else over the holidays','Quentin Fottrell','Published: Nov 21, 2018 1:14 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/01/29/Photos/MG/MW-GC652_moneyi_20180129161027_MG.jpg?uuid=d43aa146-0538-11e8-99f2-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" Dear Moneyist, \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I live in a two-bedroom apartment with my husband, and for the last couple of years we have hosted my husband\\u2019s parents for Thanksgiving and Christmas, and have been glad to do so. They are wonderful guests. They clean up after themselves, they don\\u2019t lie in bed all day or sit around watching TV, and they always come bearing gifts and send a thank-you card. When we bought our apartment, we did set up our second bedroom as a guest room, and we have had a steady stream of guests over the last year. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"We intend to have a child in a year or two and are happy to share our home with friends and family, in the meantime. This year, we were hoping to celebrate the holidays quietly and take a trip to the Caribbean between Christmas and New Year. I don\\u2019t feel like guests. My husband is afraid of offending his parents, as they\\u2019re expecting to go. But we\\u2019ve hosted them for three years in a row and he has two other siblings. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"We have a constant stream of guests who come all year, and it\\u2019s exhausting and expensive. Any suggestions on how to let our in-laws down gently? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Margaret in New York\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dear Margaret, \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Tell them the truth. Take them into your confidence. It\\u2019s better to do it sooner rather than later. Find out what alternative plans they have. It may be too late in the day to change your plans now. This is a conversation you needed to have a month or two ago. If they expect to stay with you, then make it shorter. It is a stressful and tiring time of year for both guests and hosts. It may be that you could both shorten the time they spend there.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"There is another problem that you year-round. You live in one of the most heavily visited cities in America (second only to Orlando, Fla.). New York tourists are expected to hit 67 million in 2021, up from 60.3 million last year, according to the mayor\\u2019s office. That\\u2019s a lot of extra chocolates on pillows. The High Line is one of the most popular attractions in New York. I don\\u2019t quite get this landscaped former railway line.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"New Yorkers (and anyone who lives near Disney World) have more than their fair share of house guests. Last year, I had five weeks of (delightful) guests. But I\\u2019ve also gone through three air mattresses, and they\\u2019re not cheap either. A few days here and there add up for the beleaguered host, but save a bundle on New York hotel bills for the guest, so you can\\u2019t blame them for trying. Good luck getting a hotel for less than $170 per night in this town.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Designating your spare room as a guest bedroom sends out a worldwide beacon that your home is a 24/7 alternative to an Airbnb for the price of a basket of potpourri, soap-on-a-rope and bath salts. New Yorkers tend to toughen up after a few years: Some have a flat \\u201cno guest\\u201d policy, especially those who live in one-bedrooms or studios, while others assess each request on merit and have a stricter policy for \\u201ccrashers\\u201d \\u2014 that is, people who are visiting the city rather than visiting you. In this day of AirBnB, there\\u2019s no reason why guests can\\u2019t stay comfortably in their own home-away-from-home (although maybe not in New York).\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: 10 things your houseguest won\\u2019t tell you \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cPeople wrongly assume that they have to make all kinds of excuses when they don\\u2019t want a house guest,\\u201d says Kathy Bertone, author of \\u201cThe Art of the Visit: Being the Perfect Host; Becoming the Perfect Guest.\\u201d \\u201cDon\\u2019t say it\\u2019s because you are redoing the kitchen or that the dog has taken ill.\\u201d Excuses, like a sick dog or a Caribbean vacation should you decide to cancel it, could come back to bite you. But whatever you do, act now. Don\\u2019t let invitations linger like curdled milk before refusing them. Plus, your in-laws need to make other plans.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"You don\\u2019t need to manage other people\\u2019s expectations \\u2014 that\\u2019s co-dependent behavior \\u2014 you just need to manage your own comfort zone. The less information you give, the better. \\u201cNever contradict. Never explain. Never apologize. (Those are the secrets of a happy life!),\\u201d British admiral Lord John Arbuthnot Fisher wrote in a letter to The Times of London on Sept. 5, 1919. John Wayne also said something similar (\\u201cNever apologize, Mister, it\\u2019s a sign of weakness\\u201d) in this clip (1:49) from the 1949 Western, \\u201cShe Wore a Yellow Ribbon.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For your beloved in-laws, I suggest, \\u201cWe\\u2019ve decided to have a quiet Christmas this year, just the two of us,\\u201d if they have other back-up plans. If they are relying on you, suck it up this year and set your expectations for Christmas 2018 by Summer 2018. Perhaps make plans to see them at an alternative time, and tell them that you love them, too. For friends and acquaintances try, \\u201cSorry, it\\u2019s not convenient.\\u201d For frenemies, try a particular favorite of mine, \\u201cAlas, no.\\u201d If you are dealing with a professional couch-surfer who won\\u2019t take no for answer, drop the \\u201calas.\\u201d \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If you set your table for four this year, do it without resentment. You don\\u2019t have to host your in-laws every year, but if it\\u2019s going to the last for a while, make it a good memory.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Do you have questions about inheritance, tipping, weddings, family feuds, friends or any tricky issues relating to manners and money? Send them to MarketWatch\\u2019s Moneyist and please include the state where you live (no full names will be used). \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Would you like to sign up to an email alert when a new Moneyist column has been published? If so, click on this link. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Hello there, MarketWatchers. Check out the Moneyist Facebook group, where we look for answers to life\\u2019s thorniest money issues. Readers write in to me with all sorts of dilemmas: inheritance, wills, divorce, tipping, gifting. I often talk to lawyers, accountants, financial advisers and other experts, in addition to offering my own thoughts. I receive more letters than I could ever answer, so I\\u2019ll be bringing all of that guidance \\u2014 including some you might not see in these columns \\u2014 to this group. Post your questions, tell me what you want to know more about, or weigh in on the latest Moneyist columns. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Quentin Fottrell is MarketWatch\'s personal-finance editor and The Moneyist columnist for MarketWatch. You can follow him on Twitter @quantanamo. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"How do you handle unwanted guests?\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(216,'MarketWatch','My mother left her entire estate to my stepfather  what can I do about it?','Quentin Fottrell','Published: Nov 21, 2018 9:42 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/01/29/Photos/MG/MW-GC652_moneyi_20180129161027_MG.jpg?uuid=d43aa146-0538-11e8-99f2-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" Dear Moneyist, \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"My late mother remarried in 1954. My biological father \\u2014 the only father my other brothers and sisters have known \\u2014 died in 2005. I found out recently that my stepfather has a will and left everything to our half-sister. However, our half-sister died six months ago leaving behind a husband. What are your recommendations for when my stepfather dies? I am planning on retaining a lawyer to petition the court to be named executor of his estate. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: This woman\\u2019s husband gave $600,000 to a cult \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I saw a bank statement once and he had about $100,000 in the account. I was amazed that he had that much, but I know he has been investing some. The house is probably worth between $50,000 and $75,000. A couple of family members (aunts on my mother\\u2019s side) have told me that the social security checks my mom received for each of her children until they turned 18 was used to finance their buying the current house.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Gale\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dear Gale, \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"You have one thing in your favor and it\\u2019s something that went against many other people who have written into this column in recent times: Your stepfather is still alive.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"And, I trust, he is also well and is not planning to slip this mortal coil anytime soon. Talk to him, and explain how he may know wish to rewrite his will given that his heir is dead. (You may want to put it a little more delicately than that.) You\\u2019re more influential and helpful now as a stepdaughter when he is alive than you will be as an executor when he is dead. This is the time to help him get his affairs in order, make plans for what happens to his estate after he\\u2019s gone and, yes, make a case for his stepchildren. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read also: How do I cancel 10 credit cards without damaging my credit score? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This is all the more important if your mother brought assets into the marriage and left them to your stepfather in her will. If your mother did not leave a will, then your stepfather is not necessarily in line to inherit 100% of her estate. In California, for instance, your stepfather would inherit all of the deceased spouse\\u2019s community property. That\\u2019s the wealth they accumulated during their marriage. But you and your siblings would under California law inherit between one-half and one-third of your mother\\u2019s separate property. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: My stepmother inherited my late father\\u2019s estate \\u2014 I want my fair share \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It is all the more important for stepchildren to make such a case. Stepchildren are not legal heirs. Even if you break bread on Thanksgiving and have known each other for most of your lives, you are not considered his child under the eyes of the law. If your stepfather wants to make sure you and your siblings are taken care of after he\\u2019s gone, or even if he wants to leave you something of sentimental value \\u2014 anything from a diamond ring to an empty jewelry box \\u2014 he will have to make those provisions in his will. An alternative: Your stepfather could adopt you and your siblings. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"You\\u2019re not entitled to his estate. But you could give him a gentle reminder that you wouldn\\u2019t mind a few bob either.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Do you have questions about inheritance, tipping, weddings, family feuds, friends or any tricky issues relating to manners and money? Send them to MarketWatch\\u2019s Moneyist and please include the state where you live (no full names will be used). \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Would you like to sign up to an email alert when a new Moneyist column has been published? If so, click on this link. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Hello there, MarketWatchers. Check out the Moneyist private Facebook group, where we look for answers to life\\u2019s thorniest money issues. Readers write in to me with all sorts of dilemmas: inheritance, wills, divorce, tipping, gifting. I often talk to lawyers, accountants, financial advisers and other experts, in addition to offering my own thoughts. I receive more letters than I could ever answer, so I\\u2019ll be bringing all of that guidance \\u2014 including some you might not see in these columns \\u2014 to this group. Post your questions, tell me what you want to know more about, or weigh in on the latest Moneyist columns. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Quentin Fottrell is MarketWatch\'s personal-finance editor and The Moneyist columnist for MarketWatch. You can follow him on Twitter @quantanamo. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(217,'MarketWatch','My wife drinks too much, drives with our 7-year-old son and now wants a divorce','Quentin Fottrell','Published: Nov 20, 2018 9:22 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/01/29/Photos/MG/MW-GC652_moneyi_20180129161027_MG.jpg?uuid=d43aa146-0538-11e8-99f2-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" Dear Moneyist, \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"My wife wants a divorce after 13 years of marriage.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"She drinks too much and won\\u2019t stop for me and our child. She wants to wait three months before filing for divorce because she wants to record herself being the best mother she could be. Our child is seven and not one time did she ever get up to make him breakfast, dress him, bathe him, etc.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I have been there since Day 1 getting up all hours to take care of our child and I still do it. She changed her phone and blocked me on her social media. I\\u2019m worried if she drives drunk with my child. There\\u2019s no way I can call to see where my child is. Is that legal for her to do that?\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Getting divorced? Time is running out to lock in that tax deduction on alimony payments \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"We both work and she complains she had to watch our child after school until I get home. Why would a mother complain about watching her own child? She takes Adderall for ADHD. I never wanted divorce for the sake of my child and I didn\\u2019t want to give up on the marriage.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"We live in Rhode Island. I want to know where my child is and if he is OK when she leaves the house.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"What should I do?\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Broken Hearted\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dear Broken, \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I\\u2019m sorry that you\\u2019re going through this. Any divorce lawyer or judge in a child-custody case will want to see evidence of irresponsible behavior. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"You should know where your child is at all times and, assuming you\\u2019re now separated, your first priority should be to make sure your son is in a safe environment. Without an arrest record for drunken driving or some other conviction, it can be difficult to prove that your estranged spouse has a drinking problem. Witnesses (neighbors, child-care providers) may help.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Most states have a mechanism for parties to seek child custody on a permanent and/or emergency basis, says Andrew Brendle, a partner with Hull & Chandler law firm in Charlotte, N.C. \\u201cEmergency child custody typically arises when the child is exposed to a substantial and immediate risk of physical harm, sexual abuse, or at risk of being removed from the state\\u2019s jurisdiction.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: My cheating husband just inherited $3 million from his father\\u2019s estate\\u2014should I still divorce him? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It\\u2019s difficult to prove alcohol abuse, however, even when a parent is a heavy drinker. In this 2017 case, Fessler vs. McGovern, the mother alleged that the father of her child drank too much. However, the court ruled that there was no evidence that the father in this case drank while the child was with him, even though he drank nightly.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Brendle often advises parents to keep a record of anything and everything that relates to their child\\u2019s well being. \\u201cIf you are taking the child to the doctor, taking the child to school, making arrangements for developmental milestones, etc., write it down somewhere,\\u201d he says. \\u201cIf there is a confrontation with the other parent make a note of it as soon as it is safe to do so.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThese notes, pictures, and documents will become important pieces of evidence in a custody trial if the parties are unable to reach an amicable resolution,\\u201d he adds. \\u201cIn situations where there are allegations of alcohol abuse document the alcohol abuse as best you can to help prove the allegations/concerns when the time comes.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Your estranged wife may wish to delay the divorce, but you can file for divorce anytime. It does not have to be by mutual agreement. What\\u2019s more you can state the grounds on which you are filing. If you do present evidence of your wife\\u2019s alcohol abuse, a judge may ask for regular blood tests or request your spouse undergo a psychiatric evaluation.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Recommended: I paid off my wife\\u2019s student loans\\u2014then she filed for divorce after two years of marriage \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Unfortunately, the holidays and the New Year is a popular time for people to initiate divorce proceedings. In fact, some divorce lawyers refer to the first Monday of the year as \\u201cDivorce Mondays,\\u201d and say there are 33% more divorce filings at that time. Many families decide to wait until after the holidays to pull the plug. They don\\u2019t want to spoil the holidays for the family. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I\\u2019m sure this has been on your mind. The best home for a child is a safe and happy home, and that can be achieved just as easily with one parent as two. Ultimately, any divorce or child-custody case will put both the safety and needs of your child first. I\\u2019m sure that\\u2019s what you want too. I hope you muster up the strength to take those first, difficult steps.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Do you have questions about inheritance, tipping, weddings, family feuds, friends or any tricky issues relating to manners and money? Send them to MarketWatch\\u2019s Moneyist and please include the state where you live (no full names will be used). \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Would you like to sign up to an email alert when a new Moneyist column has been published? If so, click on this link. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Hello there, MarketWatchers. Check out the Moneyist private Facebook group, where we look for answers to life\\u2019s thorniest money issues. Readers write in to me with all sorts of dilemmas: inheritance, wills, divorce, tipping, gifting. I often talk to lawyers, accountants, financial advisers and other experts, in addition to offering my own thoughts. I receive more letters than I could ever answer, so I\\u2019ll be bringing all of that guidance \\u2014 including some you might not see in these columns \\u2014 to this group. Post your questions, tell me what you want to know more about, or weigh in on the latest Moneyist columns. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Quentin Fottrell is MarketWatch\'s personal-finance editor and The Moneyist columnist for MarketWatch. You can follow him on Twitter @quantanamo. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(218,'MarketWatch','I love my girlfriend, but she spends all her money on vacations and clothes','Quentin Fottrell','Published: Nov 19, 2018 1:06 p.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/01/29/Photos/MG/MW-GC652_moneyi_20180129161027_MG.jpg?uuid=d43aa146-0538-11e8-99f2-9c8e992d421e\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \" Dear Moneyist, \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I am 22 years old and just graduated from college in May with a bachelor\\u2019s degree. I recently started my first full-time job and am making decent money. Now that I am on my own, I am excited to start slashing away at my $10,000 in student-loan debt so that I can start saving and investing my money appropriately. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I was raised in a financially \\u201cwell-off\\u201d home until the 2008 financial crisis that cost my mother her job, savings and, eventually, her house. Though she always made ends meet and ensured I was taken care of, I witnessed what it was like to go from having more than enough money to living paycheck to paycheck and, ultimately, to having everything literally taken from you. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Therefore, I was able to learn firsthand how important financial responsibility truly is. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This leads me to my motive for this letter: My girlfriend. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I have been dating a wonderful girl for nearly a year now and she brings me lots of joy. She is sweet, caring and loyal. She has a year left of school and then will start her career as a kindergarten teacher. Not long after, she wants to start a family. She is everything I could ask for. I love her very much. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Don\\u2019t miss: Americans who were \\u2018scarred\\u2019 by the Great Recession changed the way they spend \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"However, there is just one flaw that I need help with: Her spending habits. They drive me ****ing crazy. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Being that she is still in college, she has no immediate expenses of her own. Daddy takes care of everything. She literally treats him like an ATM and knows it. She is constantly buying clothes she doesn\\u2019t need and always saving items in her e-shopping carts. If her friends invite her on a vacation, Daddy will cover it and, if not, it would be doomsday. She\\u2019s entitled. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This worries me and scares me for our future. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I have brought it up to her, but she acts like it is temporary. She says that she has no reason to save money until she is out of school and treats every dollar she earns at her summer job as disposable income. When I say anything, she acts like I\\u2019m being dramatic. Because of her habits, basically anytime she talks about buying something new, it drives me nuts. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"What do I do? I love her and see a future with her, but I want to ensure a stable and successful financial future for myself and my family. How can I change her ways and make her realize she doesn\\u2019t need to participate in every sale that her favorite women\\u2019s clothing designer has to offer? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Portland Patrick \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Dear Patrick, \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Congratulations! You have noticed some important patterns in your relationship that could come back to haunt you later. You are among those young people who have watched their parents survive the Great Recession and applied that harrowing experience to your own. While you may not exactly be scarred by it, you probably have a far more cautious approach to your finances as a result. And your choice of partner will be a big part of that. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"You have clearly both had very different life experiences, so it\\u2019s probably no wonder that your girlfriend is one of those lucky folks who has the luxury not to give too much thought about tomorrow. She has her parents\\u2019 income to rely on and, likely, has some kind of sizable inheritance in her future too. That has given her a sense of freedom and, perhaps, folly. Just because she can spend like there\\u2019s no tomorrow does not make it (a) any easier to watch and (b) smart.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: These are the pricey summer camps where wealthy kids go to feel \\u2018normal\\u2019 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Believe it or not, 1 in 3 Americans say their financial stability is dependent on inheritance. That\\u2019s according to a survey released last week by Merrill Edge, an online discount brokerage service provided by Bank of America Merrill Lynch BAC, +0.55% Some 36% of Generation X-ers, 32% of millennials and 20% of baby boomers say they\\u2019re relying on their family fortunes. It\\u2019s hard to read that without feeling something, somewhere in America has gone horribly wrong.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Recommended: My fianc\\u00e9 postponed our wedding, secretly bought a house\\u2014and told me I could pay rent \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"But you have something in your favor. You have some mighty fine feathers in your own cap. You realize the fortunes of one\\u2019s parents don\\u2019t always last and there\\u2019s something satisfying about paying one\\u2019s own way. Tell your girlfriend how your family\\u2019s history changed your outlook and then explain how her profligate spending makes you feel. (Maybe don\\u2019t say \\u201cprofligate.\\u201d) Better to say how it makes you feel rather than attributing any value judgments to her behavior. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"She may inherit a lot of money and/or marry someone who will keep her in the lifestyle to which she has become accustomed. You\\u2019re 22. Don\\u2019t make a down payment on this relationship just yet. Keep your eyes on the prize. For you, that could mean a modest home, a fulfilling job, living within or even below your means, and having peace of mind. Write your budget plan on a piece of paper and show it to her .Your girlfriend\\u2019s idea of happiness might be something quite different. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Whether you wear a Swatch or a Rolex, you will have your answer in good time. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Do you have questions about inheritance, tipping, weddings, family feuds, friends or any tricky issues relating to manners and money? Send them to MarketWatch\\u2019s Moneyist and please include the state where you live (no full names will be used). \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Would you like to sign up to an email alert when a new Moneyist column has been published? If so, click on this link. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Hello there, MarketWatchers. Check out the Moneyist private Facebook group, where we look for answers to life\\u2019s thorniest money issues. Readers write in to me with all sorts of dilemmas: inheritance, wills, divorce, tipping, gifting. I often talk to lawyers, accountants, financial advisers and other experts, in addition to offering my own thoughts. I receive more letters than I could ever answer, so I\\u2019ll be bringing all of that guidance \\u2014 including some you might not see in these columns \\u2014 to this group. Post your questions, tell me what you want to know more about, or weigh in on the latest Moneyist columns. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Quentin Fottrell is MarketWatch\'s personal-finance editor and The Moneyist columnist for MarketWatch. You can follow him on Twitter @quantanamo. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(219,'MarketWatch','What this now-wealthy doctor is thankful for this Thanksgiving','Side Hustle Scrubs','Published: Nov 21, 2018 11:48 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/10/29/Photos/ZH/MW-GS638_ER_doc_20181029115034_ZH.jpg?uuid=5f91d7ca-db92-11e8-adcd-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"I\\u2019ve previously compared a physician\\u2019s income to winning a jackpot. Just by virtue of waking up a physician this morning, I\\u2019m comfortably within the top 5% of American incomes. With a little hustling you can work your way into the top 1% too.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"If you\\u2019ve always been wealthy there are many things you take for granted. My wife and I both grow up broke. We had roofs over our head and food on our plates, but we always watched our parents struggle with money. Eight years into this ridiculous physician income, we\\u2019re still grateful for the little things in life. As Thanksgiving approaches, here are 10 things I\\u2019m grateful for.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"My path to financial security all starts with finding the right mentors at the right time. A retired doctor came to my med school during my first year and gave us an \\u201cIntro to Personal Finance\\u201d lecture. It sparked an interest which led me to discover Bogleheads.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Through their forums I enjoyed the frequent posts by this random ER doc who went by the name White Coat Investor. He happened to create his own blog in 2011 when I became an attending. Through him I discovered a world of other physician bloggers who opened my eyes. Some talked about FIRE, others about burnout, others about multiple income streams, and others shared their wisdom from years of practice. I feel thankful that I discovered these mentors early in my career. I hope in some small way I can pay that forward to the visitors of this site.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"When I was a kid, my definition of \\u201crich\\u201d was being able to afford name-brand orange juice. I have so many memories of my parents sitting around cutting coupons and walking through the grocery store with a calculator to make sure they could afford to pay for the groceries in the cart.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It never gets old when I can put whatever I want in my cart without looking at the price. I\\u2019m still frugal at heart, but I can\\u2019t tell you how much joy I derive from not having to choose between feeding my family and paying my other bills.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I have no use for expensive fancy cars. I don\\u2019t begrudge anyone for driving a luxury vehicle but it does nothing for me. I live in a beach town two minutes from the hospital. My only requirements for a car is that it can drive on the sand and it doesn\\u2019t break down.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"As a kid my family drove some real doozies. My dad was an auto mechanic and usually drove old beaters that no one else wanted. Most of my childhood was spent riding in an old station wagon that my dad got free after the previous owners killed themselves in it (a fact he only told us years later). When that car gave up the ghost he drove a rusted out van that looked like the A Team had fallen on hard times. My first car was a K car with squealing brakes and an annoying tendency to stall at red lights.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"It never ever gets old that I can replace my car by paying cash and get things repaired without breaking the bank. I don\\u2019t worry about breaking down on the side of the road anymore. It\\u2019s such a simple thing to take for granted if you never drove a piece of garbage.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I grew up in a tiny two-bedroom house built in the 1940s. My wife grew up in a trailer. I admit we went overboard when we bought our big, dumb house, but it never gets old that we don\\u2019t have to worry how to pay the mortgage. My parents were always stressed about paying the bills and my wife was accustomed to coming home from school to discover a Sheriff\\u2019s Sale sign posted on her front door.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Having the mortgage set to auto-pay is such a luxury. Furthermore, paying down the principal each year feels like a weight off my chest. Next month I will have the option of paying off the remainder of my mortgage at age 36. I don\\u2019t have the heart to tell my parents I can do it without making any sacrifices.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Did you grow up in a house that played bill roulette? White envelopes = ignore. Yellow envelopes = consider paying. Pink envelopes = final warning. Every once in a while our parents would discover they waited too long when the phone stopped working or the power went off.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I am forever grateful that my bills are paid on time 100% of the time. No waiting for final warnings. No transferring credit card balances to buy more time. Just get a bill, pay the bill and repeat. I still go around the house turning off light switches like any self-respecting dad would do, but I don\\u2019t worry about the electric company shutting off the power.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"My parents realized early on that the best way my brother and I could live a better life was through education. My parents wanted to save for college, but most months there just wasn\\u2019t anything left in the budget to save. Thanks to a couple of well-timed deaths (thanks Nana and Uncle Barry!) a very small inheritance helped fund part of my in-state college tuition. The rest was paid for with student loans my parents cosigned without being sure they would be able to pay back if I defaulted.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I opened a 529 for all three of my kids the day their Social Security cards came in the mail. Their college savings is on autopilot and if I undershoot on savings I will be able to cash flow the difference. That\\u2019s quite a relief considering two of my three kids are still in diapers.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"My wife didn\\u2019t have health insurance until she turned 22 and got her first full-time job. Before I signed him up for Medicare this year, my father in-law hasn\\u2019t had health insurance since the end of the Vietnam War. My father is a type 1 diabetic and lived in constant fear of my mother losing her insurance and not being able to afford his insulin.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"One of the many benefits of having a big benefits package is being insured like a Saudi prince. I\\u2019ve spent the past eight years saving and investing the max in my health savings account and my group reimburses me for any health expenses not covered by our luxurious coverage. I never forget that all of our relatives lost a lot of sleep worrying how to pay for even basic health care.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"My father in-law is a commercial fisherman. His ability to put food on the table is completely dependent on the tide and the fish population. My father was an auto mechanic until modern cars had more technology than he could keep up with.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I work in a health care system that is perfectly designed to make me wealthy. If I ever get sick of my day job I\\u2019ve already found side hustles that would let me completely replace my clinical income. I never worry about people no longer needing emergency physicians. Reimbursement cuts could certainly change my income, but as long as anxiety, alcohol and aging exist I will be able to feed my family.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"When our parents didn\\u2019t work, they didn\\u2019t get paid. I can count on one hand how many times my father and father-in-law called out sick when we were young. There was no paid time off. No FMLA policy. If they got sick or injured they had a FML policy (older readers may have to Google what FML stands for).\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Thanks to a variety of disability insurance policies, I would actually make more money if I become disabled. My total own-occupational disability insurance policies would reimburse 80% of my current income if I am unable to continue being an emergency physician. Since that money would be tax-free and my current effective tax rate is >20%, I would actually get a raise with a disability.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"My in-laws essentially have no retirement savings. They live month-to-month on their Social Security checks. My mom was banking on a pension from her teaching job, but after her school declared bankruptcy a few years ago, the size of her anticipated pension was cut.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"I could probably retire with a frugal lifestyle by age 40 and a really comfortable lifestyle by age 50. Although I love what I do and have no desire to retire early right now, it gives me peace of mind that I will continue to work because I want to rather than because I have to.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"When we get bogged down in the day-to-day drudgery of medicine it is easy to forget just how good we have it. Most people would give their left leg for your paychecks and the security that comes with it. My wife and I feel lucky to have had the childhoods we had. It has given us a true appreciation for our newfound wealth. We\\u2019re still not sure how we\\u2019ll pass that appreciation on to our kids and prevent them from becoming entitled brats.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"During this season of reflection, take some time to appreciate the little things in your financial life that give you peace of mind. Happy Thanksgiving!\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" This column originally appeared on SideHustleScrubs. It was published with permission.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" SideHustleScrubs is an emergency physician practicing medicine on the East Coast and blogging about personal finance, taxes and early retirement.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Do you take your financial security for granted? Are you grateful for the little things in your financial life? Share your thoughts and comments.\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(220,'MarketWatch','Saving enough for a happy retirement may be easier than you think','Alessandra Malito','Published: Nov 21, 2018 10:09 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/20/Photos/ZH/MW-GY843_jetson_20181120115305_ZH.jpg?uuid=c04e73c6-ece4-11e8-87a8-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Want to have a comfortable retirement? Stop focusing on the stock market and focus on yourself instead. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Simple choices \\u2014 putting money aside for retirement, increasing contributions once a year, holding tight during market volatility \\u2014 are what drives investors to success, said Daniel Crosby, author of \\u201cThe Laws of Wealth: Psychology and the secret to investing success\\u201d (Harriman House). \\u201cDespite the unequivocal truth that investor behavior is a better predictor of wealth creation than fund selection or market timing, no one dreams about not panicking, making regular contributions and maintaining a long-term focus,\\u201d he said. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"One example: the S&P 500 SPX, +0.90% \\u00a0 has had an annual total return of 11.1% over the last 30 years, but the average stock mutual-fund investor has earned less than 4%, due to mutual-fund expenses and poor timing. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Enter behavioral finance.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" See: My dad talked me out of the decade\\u2019s best investment, but he wasn\\u2019t wrong \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Behavioral finance is the melding of economic theory and psychological and cognitive theory \\u2014 how and why people make the financial decisions that they make. Crosby earlier this year launched a certificate program in applied behavioral finance with Greene Consulting, which financial advisers can use to help their clients make decisions and follow through on those decisions to meet their goals. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The problem? People are \\u201cpsychologically ill-equipped\\u201d to invest in risk assets, even if they need to do so. They also don\\u2019t save very much for retirement, possibly because they don\\u2019t think they need to yet or because they can\\u2019t afford it. Not all Americans have access to tax-advantageous retirement accounts, either. Companies with employer-sponsored plans are helping more though, with strategies like automatic enrollment and auto-escalation of retirement contributions, concepts Nobel Prize winner Richard Thaler cocreated. Thaler\\u2019s work, which focuses on behavioral economics and getting people to save more money for their futures, could have accumulated billions of dollars in retirement savers\\u2019 accounts in the last decade.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Crosby spoke with MarketWatch about how behavioral finance affects retirement. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" MarketWatch: How important are behavioral finance concepts to retirement planning, and can you give an example? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Daniel Crosby: Behavioral finance is crucial to retirement considerations because so much of our wiring is for immediacy and not for delayed gratification. As recently as a few hundred years ago \\u2014 which is the blink of an eye evolutionarily \\u2014 the average human lifespan was 35 years old. There was no need to plan for the future, you just did the best you could moment to moment. In a very real sense, those who survived to pass on their genes were the ones who were the most concerned about surviving in the moment and a big part of that is risk and loss aversion. Those tendencies, that served our forebears well, are not well suited for the new milieu in which we find ourselves. Today, a lot of those immediate threats have been eliminated through medicine and nutrition, and we need to think about living in retirement for as many years as we worked in many cases. In order to effectively plan for retirement, we need to grasp the reality that there is a \\u201cfuture self\\u201d that is just as real and just as hungry as our current self. This requires a level of projection and extrapolation that doesn\\u2019t come naturally to us.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" MW: At what point might it kick in that we are, essentially, on the hook for our own future (monetarily speaking)? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Crosby: Well, we know that the brain is developing well into the mid-20s with the prefrontal cortex not being full online until about age 25, but that still overestimates how fully tuned in most people are to the realities of retirement. I liken it to dying. Even small children know, cognitively, that they will not live forever. But this isn\\u2019t a very immediate reality and they aren\\u2019t necessarily doing much to prepare for or protect against death. In fact, they can act as though they are invincible even though they have a shallow, cognitive understanding of the reality of death. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Retirement is the same way. Most adults understand at some level that they need to retire and that they won\\u2019t work forever, but whether that realization is visceral enough to translate into action is another story entirely.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" MW: How can we be better about acting on our need to plan our retirements? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Crosby: Step one is around creating a visceral, felt need to act. This will look different for different people but might include spending time with aging relatives to get a good look at what life will be like for us one day, talking to a parent or grandparent about what they wish they had known, or even just reading articles on the financial realities of retirement.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The second step is around automating and making it easy. Maintenance of the status quo is a human tendency that can be co-opted for good. The more we are able to automate good saving and investment behavior, the less we will think about it and the easier it will become. Humans tend to dramatically overestimate their willpower and those planning to save for retirement by choosing to do the right thing themselves, month after month, are likely to be sorely disappointed.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also see: How will the recent elections affect policies on aging? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" MW: The concept of retirement used to be more along the lines of relaxing on a beach, far from an office building, but these days people are working well into those traditional retirement years, sometimes out of necessity. Do you think this new perception of retirement has changed the way people prepare for it? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Crosby: The first thing that is changing our perception of retirement is the scientific study of happiness. Every rigorous examination of happiness and well-being has hard work somewhere squarely in the middle, which runs contrary to some more two dimensional models of happiness. What we\\u2019re finding is that even when people are able to retire from work it may not always be in their best interests to do so entirely inasmuch as work is a create source of relationship building and mental stimulation.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A second consideration is that this \\u201cescape to the beach\\u201d mentality assumes that you hated your job so much that you demand absolute distance from it in retirement and that\\u2019s a sad commentary on how you spent 30 to 40 years of your life. Instead, of working at a soul-sucking job for decades and then escaping, I think that people are increasingly seeking out work that is both personally and professionally fulfilling. This allows for comfortably working longer which is also consistent with the need to work more years to keep up with our expanding longevity.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" MW: How important is it to think of or visualize exactly the type of retirement you want to be successful in achieving it? \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Crosby: Visualization is a part of cultivating an appropriate sense of urgency about retirement, but I\\u2019d say that it\\u2019s about more than just dreaming about the boat that you want. In order to be effective, I think people need to think about not only the life that they want but the one that they want to avoid. Psychologists have shown that we are more motivated to avoid loss than to seek gain and so just as surely as we dream about the boat, we need to also visualize the difficulty of just squeaking by if we aren\\u2019t adequately prepared.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Alessandra Malito is a personal finance reporter based in New York. You can follow her on Twitter @malito_ali. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(221,'MarketWatch','Rethinking turkey: how some have adapted holiday traditions to changing times','Liza Kaufman Hogan','Published: Nov 21, 2018 9:50 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/14/Photos/ZH/MW-GY532_na_tur_20181114111328_ZH.jpg?uuid=38f12c9a-e828-11e8-aeca-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"This article is reprinted by permission from NextAvenue.org.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"As we gather together for Thanksgiving, many will be surrounded by family and friends they\\u2019ve celebrated with for years, sharing the same dishes they wouldn\\u2019t think of leaving off the menu.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"And while many treasure tradition, some have adapted their customs to accommodate changes in their lives.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"We asked Next Avenue readers how they\\u2019ve reinvented the holiday to suit their needs and make the day more meaningful. Here\\u2019s what they said:\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Pamela Hastings from Port Angeles, Wash., says her family tired of the traditional Thanksgiving dinner years ago. Instead, she began hosting themed celebrations for her self-described family of foodies.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A few years ago, it was Thanksgiving-on-a-stick, with a menu that included stuffing muffins on sticks; a cherished family corn casserole made into balls and deep fried; pie folded over Popsicle sticks and the turkey impaled by a large dowel. Another year it was all pies (potato pie, squash pie with pumpernickel bread crust, ricotta pie, artichoke pie, elk mincemeat pie\\u00a0and assorted dessert pies). Hastings once hosted a Mexican Thanksgiving, complete with a turkey pi\\u00f1ata. This year the theme is Mediterranean, inspired by a friend\\u2019s baklava.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Not everyone was as willing to be as creative with their meals as Hastings. Some readers said it was important to prepare a holiday meal that would make their grandmother proud with oven-baked, shiny brown turkeys and comfort food sides. Others traded in the Norman Rockwell-worthy turkey and trimmings for a simpler, low-stress meal.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cI don\\u2019t spend all day preparing food. We have a much simpler meal that includes some food prepared by our wonderful local grocery store and some made by myself or other family members,\\u201d says Elizabeth Y., of Virginia Beach, Va. \\u201cIn addition, I am working at job where I don\\u2019t get the Friday after Thanksgiving off \\u2014 so, the holiday is no longer a four-day schmooze fest. It\\u2019s a simple gathering with those I love.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Susan B. of Hudson, Wis., says: \\u201cI always felt compelled to cook dinner like my mother, which was everything traditional. Now my children just make their favorite dishes. It is always enough.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Let\\u2019s be honest, the average Thanksgiving meal\\u00a0packs a lot of calories. While some are happy to treat Thanksgiving like a $12.99 all-you-can-eat buffet, others prefer to stay on track with their healthful ways. Cooks, in turn, are finding ways to cut calories and fat from the sugary, butter-drenched dishes they grew up with.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cI don\\u2019t make the big feast my grandparents and parents used to, with all the calorie-laden dishes and three different pies!\\u201d writes Judy B. from Escondido, Calif. \\u201cMashed potatoes are now cauliflower mashed \\u2018potatoes.\\u2019 I don\\u2019t make stuffing because no one liked it except me, and I don\\u2019t need the extra calories. During the football games, we have changed from chips and dip to veggies and hummus.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Katherine C. of Grand Rapids, Mich., says: \\u201cPecan pie is no longer served. It should be called sugar pie with nut topping.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"No matter how small the gathering, many hosts will have one or two guests\\u00a0who cannot eat certain foods\\u00a0or who follow a special diet. In the past few years, a lot of us have added gluten-free stuffing, vegan gravy and sugar-free fruit pies to the standard menu.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"While her tofurkey roast may not make the cover of Martha Stewart Living, reader Linda Gonzalez, of Philadelphia, says she\\u2019s thrilled to have it on her table, since she doesn\\u2019t eat meat.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Barbara Hoskins of Mesa, Ariz., says: \\u201cWe have had to change the recipes to accommodate food allergies. Our turkey has to be gluten-free with no additives \\u2026 We have stopped using dairy products because of dairy allergies. We have experimented with dairy-free, egg-free, gluten-free, garlic-free, and many other options.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Of course, at times you do not want to mess with tradition. Families get used to certain dishes, and you change the menu at your peril.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cEvery year we argue about the corn,\\u201d says Janet S. of New Athens, Ill. \\u201cWe had scalloped corn for many years and then along came the corn casserole, the one made with cornbread mix. The first year I brought the \\u2018new recipe,\\u2019 they had a fit. I was told to go back to the old recipe and leave it that way. We are so locked in our traditions.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"At least two readers confessed to liking the canned, jellied cranberry over the various homemade versions that adorn Thanksgiving tables (and tablecloths) this time of year.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"For those who want to add homemade cranberry sauce and a little kick to the meal, reader Dot Dickinson shared her friend Sherry\\u2019s recipe for\\u00a0Bourbon Cranberry Relish. We didn\\u2019t have time to run it through the Next Avenue test kitchen (aka the breakroom), but it looks lovely. Dot adds this helpful hint for the Thanksgiving cook in need of a break: \\u201cThis is best if you taste the bourbon before adding it to the saucepan. It may take a couple of sips to make sure it is OK to add it to the cranberries.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Even if you are not hosting and cooking for a big family with different tastes for Thanksgiving, just getting there can be a stressful experience, as you try to not be trampled at the airport or tailgated on the highway.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Leah Antignas, of Oakland, Calif., figured out how to avoid the Wednesday evening turkey race a while ago. She says: \\u201cInstead of taking off work the day before to travel to family, we take off work the Monday after. My husband and I drive early Thanksgiving Day from the Bay Area to L.A. so we can avoid the Wednesday traffic and arrive in time for the gathering. Long drive but little traffic \\u2014 what a relief. We made this shift years ago and have never turned back.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some readers have decided to have their Thanksgiving meals with special people beyond their family members.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cInstead of inviting people to our home, we bring food to our church where we host a meal for those who have nowhere else to go. We serve and eat there, meeting many remarkable people,\\u201d Doroth Van Haaften of Idaho Falls, Idaho, wrote in to say.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: How couples should handle the sticky business of where to spend the holidays \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Julie Tomlinson of Cary, N.C., says the traditional Thanksgiving family gathering is stressful and she winds up eating too much. Instead, she says, \\u201cI plan to create a family of my choosing, comprised of women in my age group, living with or near one another, helping and caring for each other.\\u00a0\\u2018The Golden Girls\\u2019 dream\\u00a0of women across the country, and beyond. We will create new traditions. My contribution will be healthier meals.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cIt used to be all about the immediate family,\\u201d writes Susan H. of\\u00a0Mahopac, N.Y. \\u201cHowever, with older parents (and) relatives passing away and some other family members who grow up and start their own family traditions, it\\u2019s more difficult to try to organize the traditional Thanksgiving dinner. The last few years, we\\u2019ve spent Thanksgiving with our friends instead of family.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"As families grow and add new members,\\u00a0the menu has inevitably changed. \\u201cWe try to incorporate a special dish that each guest remembers from her family\\u2019s tradition: e.g. kimchi for a Korean-American; Brussels sprouts for our New England friends; mince pie for our English guests, along with our own family recipes,\\u201d says Lynnett Evans of San Francisco, Calif.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cOur son married a New England girl, so squash on our table is a must (though the marriage is over!) One daughter married a fellow from the South, so we added sweet potato casserole to the menu \\u2026 he\\u2019s still with us!\\u201d says HelenMarie M. of Fort Washington, Penn.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Even with crustless pumpkin pies and cauliflower mashed potatoes on the menu, our tendency is to eat beyond our recommended daily calorie intake. Many readers say they have added nature walks and hikes to their Thanksgiving Day traditions, for exercise and to enjoy the outdoors together.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Also read: Follow these tips to travel in style\\u2014for less \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"We always walk after the meal. Well, most of us!\\u201d writes Leanna from Lewes, Del.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some traditions die hard: Many people wrote in to defend spending time on the couch watching the Macy\\u2019s Thanksgiving Day Parade, football and\\u00a0holiday movies. But Deborah R. of Churchville, Md., wrote poignantly of the change her family has made to make the day enjoyable for her mother-in-law who has dementia. \\u201cInstead of a more adult movie we might prefer, we watch \\u2018Peanuts\\u2019 cartoons she can understand and that we enjoy as well.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"And lest the meaning of the day get lost under all that food, many readers said they take time to focus on giving thanks.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Claudia Skelton, of Seattle, says her family uses the holiday to\\u00a0recall happy memories thinking \\u201cabout previous family Thanksgiving events and (writing) a few words about those memories. Those memories are what I am thankful for.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"\\u201cThe one tradition we will never change is having each person at the table tell something he or she is especially thankful for,\\u201d says HelenMarie of Fort Washington, Penn. \\u201cThis will probably be my dad\\u2019s last Thanksgiving. He is 97 and is having more difficulty negotiating the travel from his personal care community. So it will be special in that way. Future family celebrations will evolve.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Liza Kaufman Hogan is a freelance writer. @lizakhogan\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"This article was originally published Nov. 26, 2015. It is reprinted by permission from NextAvenue.org, \\u00a9 2018 Twin Cities Public Television, Inc. All rights reserved.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',1,-2),(222,'MarketWatch','Watch out for these 10 retirement killers','Brett Arends','Published: Nov 20, 2018 9:04 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/12/Photos/ZH/MW-GY412_cruise_20181112201952_ZH.jpg?uuid=3899ab56-e6e2-11e8-aa24-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"There are plenty of things that can ruin a person\\u2019s retirement plans \\u2014 divorce, illness, job loss, overspending. Some leave a retiree with a lifetime of regret.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A recent study has revealed for the first time the 10 biggest causes of financial regret among those who have retired or are near to retirement. The information may help those who are currently working and saving, by giving them more ability to plan their finances and prepare.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: Want to make millennials mad? Talk about saving for retirement \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"A survey of \\u201cSaving Regret\\u201d targeted 1,600 Americans aged 60 to 79 to ask them about whether they had saved enough money \\u2014 and if not, why not. The survey was conducted by researchers from the RAND Corporation and the Max Planck Institute in Munich, Germany.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The results come at a time when many Americans are struggling to save for retirement. Savers are grappling with high student-debt levels and housing costs, as well as sluggish wage growth. Many don\\u2019t have access to retirement savings vehicles through their jobs: Only about 54 million American workers put money into a 401(k) plan in 2015, the Investment Company Institute found, while 150 million were employed in that year, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Read: You can contribute more to your 401(k) and IRA in 2019 \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"At the top line, the study\\u2019s results make sobering reading. More than half of those polled \\u2014 59% \\u2014 said they wish they had saved more. And four out of five of those with savings regrets admitted that they were now worried about meeting all their future financial needs. A third feared running out of money altogether. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"These types of ratios will come to some very big numbers if today\\u2019s workers follow the same path. According to the U.S. Census, by 2035 some 78 million Americans will be over 65.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Some of the findings from the survey will hardly be news. The main cause of saving too little is spending too much. Nor is it likely to be news that those with college degrees, those who earned a lot of money, and those who inherited money from rich parents were less likely to have financial regrets in their 60s and 70s. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"However, the report also found 10 retirement killers that might not be so obvious in advance. The biggest relate to major life setbacks, such as ill health, unemployment and divorce. More than half of those polled had suffered at least one such setback, and those who had were about 50% more likely to end up with financial regrets in their 60s and 70s. If we can\\u2019t prevent these things from happening we can often prepare for the risks through insurance, experts say.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile other retirement killers, such as overestimating Social Security or failing to make a long-term plan, are more easily controlled.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Here are the 10 biggest dangers \\u2014 and the probability that each one will leave you with saving regret after age 60. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"1. Having very low financial literacy (81)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"2. Being struck by poor health that prevents you working (79)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"3. Being laid off and spending a period unemployed (77)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"4. Earning less than expected (76)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"5. Getting divorced (74)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"6. Making bad investments (70)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"7. Being hit by major medical bills (68)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"8. Overestimating Social Security (69)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"9. Not making long-term plans (64)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"10. Procrastinating (64)\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Meanwhile, nearly all of those who said they wish they had saved more money admitted that they could have done so, and were able to identify areas of their budgets that they could have cut. Respondents of both sexes said they wish they had spent less money on vacations. Men said they wished they spent less on cars, and women on clothes.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Brett Arends is a MarketWatch columnist. Follow him on Twitter @BrettArends. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0),(223,'MarketWatch','Moving back in with your parents can affect your mental health','Andrew Keshner','Published: Nov 21, 2018 10:37 a.m. ET','[{\"content\": \"https://ei.marketwatch.com/Multimedia/2018/11/21/Photos/ZH/MW-GY906_boomer_20181121101004_ZH.jpg?uuid=869d5db6-ed9f-11e8-97a8-ac162d7bc1f7\", \"type\": \"image\"}, {\"content\": \"Young adults who return to live with their parents may experience unforeseen emotional consequences. Jennifer Caputo, a researcher at the Max Planck Institute for Demographic Research in Rostock, Germany said the move back home can be detrimental to their mental health. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The findings, slated to be published in the journal Society and Mental Health, \\u201csuggest that norms about attaining residential independence in young adulthood remain powerful,\\u201d Caputo said. \\u201cThese findings are consistent with research indicating that disappointments in other areas of young people\\u2019s lives can have mental-health consequences.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Moving back in with parents can be triggered by losing a job or a relationship ending, the researchers noted. Still, the study noted that coming home \\u201cremained a significant predictor of depression even after accounting for these factors.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"An individual\\u2019s ability to get along by themselves was an indicator of a \\u201csuccessful transition to adulthood, and residential independence is highly valued,\\u201d Caputo said. \\u201cNot achieving these goals might create feelings of failure.\\u201d\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The study comes at a time when more young adults are living at home.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Pew Research Center noted that in 2016, 15% of people aged 25 to 35 were living at their parents\\u2019 place. That\\u2019s a 5% jump for millennials, compared with the 10% of Generation Xers who were at home when they were the same age, Pew found. The 15% rate is almost double the 8% rate for members of the Silent Generation, when they were the same age in 1964.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"The Pew numbers do not specify just how many of the people living with their folks once lived by themselves. But that research pointed to data saying the median estimated length of time living with their onetime empty nest parents was three years.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Millennials don\\u2019t seem to be deterred. Data released last year by TD Ameritrade found that 27% of young adults from age 20 to 26 wouldn\\u2019t have a problem living with mom and dad in their early 30s. Another 11% said they\\u2019d be fine with the arrangement even as they hit 35 or older.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Get a daily roundup of the top reads in personal finance delivered to your inbox. Subscribe to MarketWatch\'s free Personal Finance Daily newsletter. Sign up here.\", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \" Andrew Keshner is a personal finance reporter based in New York. \", \"type\": \"text\"}, {\"content\": \"Join the conversation\", \"type\": \"text\"}]',0,0);
